<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths     05-23 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths,0289</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: AMs separates moved as a0662 on Schoenbrun and as a0580 on
Grandi.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>David Schoenbrun</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Schoenbrun, 73, a war correspondent who
was recruited for CBS News by Edward R. Murrow, died Monday of
heart failure. He was 73.
   Schoenbrun was introduced to Murrow by Gen. Dwight Eisenhower in
Algiers at the end of World War II.
   Schoenbrun had gone to Europe in 1941 with the War Information
Office as an editor. He joined the Army in 1943 and covered the
invasion of southern France in 1944. Murrow hired Schoenbrun as
Paris correspondent. He was Paris bureau chief from 1947 until 1961.
   Schoenbrun later served in Washington, D.C., as CBS' main
political correspondent.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Dino Grandi</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dino Grandi, who lost out to Benito Mussolini in a
1921 bid for leadership of the Fascist Party and helped depose the
dictator in 1943, died Saturday at age 92.
   Grandi fought in World War I and joined the fascist squads that
terrorized the Italian countryside. He failed to win the leadership
of the fascists at a national congress in 1921 but successfully
made a bid for a seat in Parliament.
   He participated in the October 1922 march on Rome that led to
Mussolini's installation as head of government. Grandi served as
undersecretary of the interior in 1924 and was foreign minister
from 1929 to 1934.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Edward Adamek</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARITA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward Leo Adamek, a former
Hollywood stunt man and rodeo cowboy, died Friday of cancer at the
age of 77.
   Adamek worked in the John Wayne movie ``Rio Lobo'' and the TV
series ``Gunsmoke.''
</TEXT>
