<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BoxOffice 1stLd-Writethru a0715 05-23 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Box Office, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0715,0703</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Good First Week Tally for `Willow,' Reel Test Next Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 24th graf, `8. ``Salsa ... to CORRECT revenue for the
film to $1.13 million, sted $1.14 million.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The medieval fantasy ``Willow,'' a $55 million
gamble in an often-disastrous film genre, found an audience and box
office figures Monday show moviemaker George Lucas apparently has
another hit on his hands.
   ``Willow,'' released early to avoid first-week competition from
certain blockbusters ``Crocodile Dundee II'' and ``Rambo III,'' was
the nation's top-grossing film in its debut weekend with an $8.3
million take.
   MGM-UA chairman Lee Rich said he was buoyed by the figures and
was confident ``Willow'' could maintain its box office appeal
despite the two sure-fire sequels that will flood 2,000 screens
each on Wednesday.
   ``Willow'' surpassed the opening weekend business of ``Raiders
of the Lost Ark'' ($8.26 million in June 1981) and ``Top Gun''
($8.19 million in May 1986), Rich said.
   In addition to high expectations from ``Star Wars'' creator
Lucas and ``Cocoon'' director Ron Howard, ``Willow'' has received
interest because of the amount of money it cost to make the film
over a two-year period.
   It also comes after two expensive Lucas flops _ ``Labyrinth''
and ``Howard the Duck.'' One ``Willow'' critic recently called it
``Ron Howard the Duck.''
   Art Murphy, who monitors box office trends for Daily Variety,
noted that only five motion pictures in history have ever done $8
million-plus during May's traditional pre-Memorial Day holiday
movie slump.
   Other Top 10 films pulled in considerably less during the
weekend.
   Last week's top performer, ``Friday the 13th Part VII - The New
Blood,'' took in $3.43 million to place second in the latest
sweepstakes. It made almost as much as ``Willow'' in its debut with
an $8.2 million take on 1,796 screens.
   In third was ``Colors'' with $2.9 million, followed by
``Beetlejuice'' with $2.7 million and ``Shakedown'' in fifth with
$1.2 million.
   In ``Willow,'' the main character lives in a village of little
people and finds a baby floating in the river, but it's a special
baby who will threaten the throne of the evil Queen Bavmorda.
   The queen orders her warriors to find and kill the baby and the
story revolves around the perilous trek to a castle sanctuary.
   ``Willow,'' which opened Friday at 1,024 theaters nationwide
with little enthusiasm from reviewers, is the latest effort from
Lucas, whose ``Star Wars'' and ``Indiana Jones'' films have grossed
$1 billion.
   Chicago Tribune reviewer David Kehr said of Lucas: ``In
`Willow,' the Force has left him. He's imitating himself and he's
moping while he does it.''
   Daily Variety termed the film ``a medieval mishmash'' but
predicted ``kids will probably love it.'' The Hollywood Reporter
praised the production values but complained the storyline ``never
really kicks into overdrive.''
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release, and estimated production costs when available.
   1. ``Willow,'' MGM-UA, $8.31 million, 1,024 screens, $8,106 per
screen, $8.3 million, one week, n-a.
   2. ``Friday the 13th Part VII - The New Blood,'' Paramount,
$3.43 million, 1,796 screens, $1,912 per screen, $13.24 million,
two weeks, n-a.
   3. ``Colors,'' Orion, $2.94 million, 1,388 screens, $2,122 per
screen, $34.4 million, six weeks, $12 million.
   4. ``Beetlejuice,'' Warner Bros., $2.72 million, 1,546 screens,
$1,764 per screen, $58,8 million, eight weeks, $20 million.
   5. ``Shakedown,'' Universal, $1.22 million, 938 screens, $1,703
per screen, $8.12 million, three weeks, n-a.
   6. ``Moonstruck,'' MGM-UA, $1.17 million, 771 screens, $1,525
per screen, $73.97 million, 23 weeks, $17 million.
   7. ``Above The Law,'' Warner Bros., $1.14 million, 715 screens,
$1,604 per screen, $17.45 million, seven weeks, $14 million.
   8. ``Salsa,'' Cannon, $1.13 million, 757 screens, $1,510 per
screen, $6.79 million, three weeks, n-a.
   9. ``Biloxi Blues,'' Universal, $1.12 million, 876 screens,
$1,282 per screen, $39.3 million, nine weeks, $16 million.
   10. ``The Last Emperor,'' Columbia, $930,729, 792 screens,
$1,175 per screen, $40.29 million, 27 weeks, $25 million.
</TEXT>
