<1ST_LINE>u i AM-MissUniverse 2ndLd-Writethru a0778 05-23 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miss Universe, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0778,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thai Student Crowned Miss Universe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with California schools the
winner attended. Picks up 5th graf pvs, ``Organizers of ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINKOU, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 19-year-old student from Thailand who
studied in Pasadena and Los Angeles was crowned Miss Universe of
1988 in a flashy competition on this Asian island Tuesday morning.
   Porntip Nakhirunkanok, a black-haired Bangkok resident, won
$250,000 in cash and prizes, including a sports car and mink coat.
She wiped away tears of joy and joined her hands together in a Thai
sign of thanks after winning.
   The first runner-up was Miss Korea, Yunjung Chang. She was
followed by Miss Mexico, Amanda Olivares; Miss Japan, Mizuho
Sakaguchi; and Miss Hong Kong, Pauline Yeung. Sixty-six women had
competed.
   Among the 10 semi-finalists was Miss USA, Courtney Gibbs, of
Fort Worth, Texas.
   Miss Nakhirunkanok, who weighs 114 pounds and stands 5 feet 8
inches tall, was educated at Pasadena City College and UCLA in
southern California. She said during the program that she owed her
English-speaking ability to Big Bird on the ``Sesame Street''
children's program.
   Organizers of the 37th Miss Universe pageant estimated 600
million people in 57 countries watched the televised competition
for a successor to the 1987 Miss Universe, Cecilia Bolocco of Chile.
   The program was filmed at 9 a.m. Tuesday (9 p.m. EDT Monday)
from a 9,000-seat sports stadium in a Taipei suburb so U.S. viewers
could watch during prime time Monday evening. The schedule forced
the local audience to don tuxedos and evening attire at an hour
more appropriate for reading the morning newspaper over a bowl of
cereal.
   The live broadcast seen in Taiwan was briefly interrupted with a
bulletin for a civil defense emergency exercise in the central
island.
   Missing from this year's festivities was long-time host Bob
Barker, who resigned after last year's competition in Singapore to
protest the use of furs. He was replaced by television personality
Alan Thicke.
   Beauty pageants were banned in 1964 by Taiwan's leaders, who
viewed the competitions as an extravagance for a poor nation and
were dismayed by reports that a Miss China winner performed strip
dances in Las Vegas.
   The island has since emerged as one of Asia's most prosperous
countries, and authorities lifted the ban last year to clear the
way for a domestic airline to sponsor the Miss Universe pageant.
There is lingering opposition from a few groups, including retired
soldiers who view beauty contests as an insult to mothers.
   But the telecast generally was seen in Taiwan as an opportunity
to present the island to a worldwide audience as the Republic of
China, the official name of Taiwan seldom used internationally
because most countries recognize the rival communist Chinese
government in Beijing.
   Organizers pledged to refer to Taiwan as the Republic of China
during the telecast and promised the two-hour program would have
about 30 minutes of videotapes taken during recent weeks of the
contestants at scenic spots in Taiwan.
   The Miss Universe pageant generated much interest in Taiwan but
was pushed into the background Friday when the island's most
violent anti-government protest in recent years broke out in
Taipei. The 18-hour street battle between protesters and police
left more than 200 people injured. Nearly 100 demonstrators were
detained.
   Prizes for the 1988 Miss Universe include $76,000 in cash, a
Maserati convertible automobile, and a mink coat and mink jacket.
   The 11 judges include Dick Rutan and Jeana Yeager, who made
history with their round-the-world flight aboard the Voyager two
years ago, and Susan Ruttan of the television series ``L.A. Law.''
</TEXT>
