<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--BridgeWalk     05-23 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Bridge Walk,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>65,000 Stroll Across Chesakpeake Bridge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANDY POINT, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A record 65,000 people walked across the
4.3 mile eastbound span of the Chesapeake Bay Bridge.
   Stollers were met Sunday on the west side by Gov. William Donald
Schaefer, who kicked off his One Million Marylanders bay clean-up
campaign, an attempt to get residents to practice water
conservation and change household disposal habits.
   The Bay Bridge Walk, which began at 9 a.m. and was completed by
5:30 p.m., drew 15,000 more people this year than last year's
record, in part because Sunday was one of the first warm weekend
days in what has been a rainy, cool spring.
   The first annual walk was in 1975.
   ``I'm out here every year because it's here,'' said St. Mary's
resident James Chesley. ``Why you walk across a bridge is the same
reason you climb a mountain _ because it's there.''
 
</TEXT>
