<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 0043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OpenEnrollment Bjt   05-23 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Open Enrollment, Bjt,0764</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Open Enrollment Puts Students, Parents On Honor System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new state law allowing students to choose
their schools will improve education, proponents say. But some
educators fear the plan could hurt smaller schools and bring
unhealthy competition.
   ``We realize there may be some poor choice-making in the free
market, but the challenge is to educate parents in how to make
sound choices,'' says Nan Skelton, assistant state education
commissioner.
   The measure gives Minnesota the nation's broadest open
enrollment plan, Skelton said. Schools may refuse students only if
the transfer would interfere with desegregation ratios in
Minneapolis, St. Paul and Duluth, or if the school is too crowded.
   State funding, about $3,000 per youngster, follows the student
to the new district. Previously, parents had to pay tuition to the
new district.
   Gov. Rudy Perpich signed the measure into law May 6. It takes
effect in the 1989-90 school year in larger districts and applies
statewide in 1990-91.
   State education officials hope schools will improve their
programs in the competition to attract students. A 1986 National
Governors' Association project recommended open enrollment as a way
to boost school quality.
   ``I have mixed feelings,'' said Jeff Keller, an assistant to the
superintendent of the 89-student Humboldt-St. Vincent school
district, one of the state's smallest. ``If they're put on the
honor system, are they going to transfer for the right reasons?''
   A champion debate coach worries about students transferring for
non-academic reasons.
   ``For some students, those activities are a very important part
of what they're about,'' said Randy Keillor of St. Francis High
School, whose teams have won three state titles in six years and
one national title.
   But Keillor says he sees the value of such plans.
   ``If the concept is to allow parents and students some choice,
you have to recognize that's important for them,'' Keillor said.
   Students could transfer to schools where their chances of making
an athletic team might be better or to join friends, but it's
debatable whether those are poor reasons to switch, Skelton said.
   ``It's just who gets to judge,'' she said. ``The people who get
to make the decisions are the parents and the students. If the
Education Department thinks it's a frivolous reason, it doesn't
matter.''
   Mary Kay Frisch of St. Paul, who lives on the border between two
districts, took advantage of a forerunner of the law and sent her
two children to a different district so they could be with their
friends.
   ``They just love going to school. If they (children) aren't
happy being at a school, they aren't happy doing anything there,''
Mrs. Frisch said.
   The Minnesota School Boards Association opposes allowing
students to transfer for non-academic reasons.
   ``I don't think students should be permitted to exchange
districts for athletic reasons or for some personality reasons. It
seems to me that really could cause some chaos or problems,'' said
Executive Director Willard Baker, whose association represents 435
districts.
   The Minnesota Federation of Teachers, which represents 20,000
teachers, has not taken a position.
   ``There's a possibility that small districts could end up losing
students,'' said Sandra Peterson, federation president. ``They may
have to look at cooperative ventures with other districts or
consolidation.''
   Minnesota began open enrollment on a voluntary basis this school
year, with 137 students in 95 districts choosing to participate.
Under the voluntary program, districts had the option of accepting
transfers from outside their districts.
   For the 1988-89 school year, 435 students in 153 districts
applied, said Kenneth Zastrow, director of support services for the
state education department.
   U.S. Department of Education officials have applauded
Minnesota's efforts.
   ``The overwhelming majority will not make decisions like these
for frivolous reasons,'' said Mitchell Pearlstein, spokesman for
the department's Office of Educational Research and Improvement.
``Indeed, most students will not change school districts. But
choice is valuable even when people decide to stay where they are.''
   Keillor said he hopes the new law will prompt more schools to
offer debate programs, but worries about the effect of transfers on
his own program.
   ``If we had even four students transfer into our school and they
were good, that would lock up all positions so kids from St.
Francis would not have a shot,'' Keillor said.
   On the other hand, Keillor said, ``If open enrollment provides a
marketplace for education, then, shoot, that's going to get more
schools looking at adding this program.''
</TEXT>
