<DOCNO> AP880523-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 0050EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DistrictFight     05-23 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-District Fight,0725</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Something Happened on the Way to a Political Dynasty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOWLING GREEN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For years, Rep. Delbert Latta groomed
his son to replace him when he retired from Congress. But another
well-known Ohio Republican had a different idea about who will go
to Washington.
   After the elder Latta announced in January he would not seek
re-election, it seemed only natural that Robert Latta would declare
his candidacy for Ohio's 5th District.
   But the Lattas didn't count on a challenge from within. The
challenge came from Republican Paul Gillmor, who had irritated the
Lattas just enough to prompt murmurs of a feud.
   Gillmor was the highest ranking GOP legislator in the state and
candidate for his party's nomination for governor in 1986.
   Official vote totals from the May 3 congressional primary show
Gillmor defeated Latta by 41 votes of more than 63,000 cast in a
three-way race. But a recount is automatic because of the slim
margin _ 28,680 to 28,639 _ and even the Ohio secretary of state
says the race is too close to call.
   ``I don't think it divided the Republicans because I ran a
positive race,'' Gillmor, 49, said last week. ``I said before the
primary race that I would support the eventual nominee. I expect
they would do the same.''
   Robert Latta has refused to concede, but the 32-year-old
corporate attorney from Bowling Green said he will support Gillmor
if Gillmor is the nominee.
   ``As a Republican for my entire life, you support Republicans,''
he said.
   Hoping to pick up the pieces is Democrat Thomas Murray, a
51-year-old Sandusky attorney making his second run for Congress.
Murray believes the departure of the elder Latta will end GOP
domination in the Bowling Green district, which now boasts more
registered Democrats than Republicans.
   ``Nobody believed I could beat Del Latta in 1986, and they were
right. It was like running against an institution,'' Murray said.
``There's no doubt that he has the contacts in the district from 30
years of service, but I'm not sure the same can be said for any of
the Republicans this time.''
   Michael Marsh, chairman of the Wood County Republican Party,
said Murray may be chasing moonbeams.
   ``I think (the GOP primary) had the potential to be a real nasty
kind of thing, but basically I think the candidates did a good job
of talking about themselves rather than each other,'' he said.
   ``I think it makes it easier to put together a campaign in the
fall for the winner. ... I just don't see people flocking to vote
for Thomas Murray.''
   Marsh said a rift occurred between Gillmor and Delbert Latta in
1982, when the Legislature was redrawing congressional district
lines. At the time, Gillmor was president of the Ohio Senate _ a
position he still holds.
   Marsh said Gillmor was trying to redraw the 9th Congressional
District, a traditional Democratic stronghold that includes Toledo,
so it would be more favorable for Edward Weber, a Republican
elected in 1980.
   To accomplish that, Gillmor wanted to take away one county and
part of another from Latta's district and place it in the 9th
District, Marsh said. He also wanted to move Latta's district east.
   Latta opposed Gillmor's plan, Marsh said.
   Eventually, Latta's district moved a bit east and lost parts of
Wood and Fulton counties. The 9th District gained a part of a
Democratic stronghold.
   The result: Weber lost in 1982, and the 9th District, under
Democratic Rep. Marcy Kaptur is once again Democratic territory.
   Later, Gillmor found himself shut out of some GOP functions in
northwestern Ohio. For example, he discovered he was an outsider
during President Reagan's visit to Bowling Green in 1984.
   ``They have a dais in a hall and have 50 people up there _
Latta's neighbors are up there _ but the president of the Ohio
Senate is sitting out in the crowd,'' said one Republican official,
who spoke on the condition his name not be used.
   The elder Latta, 67, son of a barber, is serving his 15th term
in Congress. He is senior Republican member of the House Budget
Committee and a veteran member of the House Rules Committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
