<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     05-23 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poultry And Pork Consumption Grows With Meat Consumption</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's biggest meat eaters are curbing
their appetites for beef and looking for second helpings of poultry
and pork.
   Per capita meat consumption in the major producing countries _
usually the richest _ grew about 11 percent over the last decade,
says an Agriculture Department report. But the gains weren't across
the board.
   ``For instance, most of the increase came from poultry and pork,
while beef declined,'' the report said. ``Consumption of lamb,
mutton and goat stagnated worldwide.''
   In 1975-77, Americans averaged about 127 pounds of beef and
veal, 59 pounds of pork, 2 pounds of lamb, mutton and goat, and 51
pounds of poultry.
   By 1985-87, per capita consumption was: beef and veal, 106
pounds; pork, 63; lamb, mutton and goat, 2; and poultry, 73. Those
are carcass weight equivalents before being divided and trimmed
into retail cuts.
   Even in Argentina, the biggest meat-eater of all, per capita
beef consumption dropped to 174 pounds from 187 a decade earlier.
Declines also occurred for lamb, mutton and goat meat, and poultry,
each down 1 pound.
   However, the Soviet Union, which has been striving to upgrade
diets, boosted beef consumption to 62 pounds per capita from 52
pounds in 1975-77, while pork increased to 48 pounds from 43. Lamb,
mutton and goat held steady at 3 pounds, but poultry consumption
jumped to 23 pounds from 14 pounds previously.
   The report was included by the department's Economic Research
Service in the agency's quarterly National Food Review issued last
week.
   Analysts noted that per capita meat consumption is affected by
many factors, including local and world economies, religion, social
customs and even climate.
   ``Most meat is produced and consumed in high-income countries,''
the report said. ``However, new technologies, like improved
refrigeration and transportation, in developing countries have
opened the door for meat imports and improved the distribution of
such products.''
   On the other hand, religion sometimes restricts the kinds of
meats that are acceptable in certain countries. Moslems and Jews
shun pork, and Hindus avoid all meat.
   Pork is the predominant meat in Europe, especially Eastern
Europe, as well as in China, Japan and other Asian nations. In
China, alone, where about a third of the world's pork is produced,
consumption rose to about 35 pounds from 18 pounds during the
decade, the report said.
   Poultry consumption has gained the most, reflecting the
relatively brief time span and less feed required to produce a
pound of poultry meat, compared with other grain-fed livestock.
   ``Beef consumption predominates in North and South America and
in Australia and New Zealand, where an abundance of forage is
available for ruminant livestock production,'' the report said.
``Ruminants like cattle, sheep and goats can be raised without any
grain, but this requires reliable sources of cheap forage.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite sharp differences over agricultural
policy and subsidies, the 12-nation European Economic Community
remains the leading market for U.S. farm products.
   In calendar 1987, according to the Agriculture Department,
exports of farm products to the EEC were worth $6.8 billion, up by
more than 3 percent from 1986. Although sales to the European bloc
_ and farm exports generally, for that matter _ have not recovered
to their record levels of the early 1980s, USDA analysts say
further growth can be expected.
   But EEC leaders frostily reject a U.S. proposal made in
negotiations under auspices of the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade to phase out all trade-distorting farm subsidies by the end
of the century.
   Willy De Clercq, the EEC's top trade official, said in Paris
last week at a meeting of trade ministers that the trade bloc would
never agree to the elimination of such subsidies, although it
favors unspecified reductions.
   According to a recent analysis by the department's Economic
Research Service, U.S. farm exports to the EEC this year could rise
by an additional 5 percent because of ``attractive U.S. prices,
favorable exchange rates and continued economic growth'' in the EEC
countries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dispatch from an Agriculture Department
trade official in Bonn says West Germans are eating more rice these
days.
   ``Rice, noodles and additional vegetable consumption are
replacing the traditional potato as the No. 1 German food item,''
says Gerald W. Harvey, U.S. agricultural counselor. ``Rice millers
are confident that this trend will continue into 1988.''
   Harvey's comments were reported in the June issue of Foreign
Agriculture magazine.
   Competitive prices for U.S. rice pushed shipments up sharply
last year and primarily replaced rice from Thailand and Italy, he
said.
</TEXT>
