<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--HongKong-Synagogue     05-23 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Hong Kong-Synagogue,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rabbi Approves Demolition Of Hong Kong Synagogue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's chief rabbi has approved the
demolition of Hong Kong's 86-year-old synagogue to make way for a
complex containing a new synagogue and high-rise apartments, a
local Jewish leader said.
   The plan to demolish the Ohel Leah synagogue split the local
Jewish community and enraged preservationists, who see the project
as another blow to this British colony's heritage.
   However, supporters argued that the Ohel Leah synagogue is
dangerously old and better facilities are needed for a growing
Jewish community.
   The chief rabbi of the United Kingdom and the Commonweath, Lord
Immanuel Jakobovits, ``waived any religious objection'' to
demolishing the Ohel Leah synagogue, said Robert Dorfman, a
synagogue leader.
   Synagogue trustees want to demolish the building and erect two
40-story towers and a new synagogue on the site.
</TEXT>
