<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 0100EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OrganTransplants     05-23 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Organ Transplants,0725</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oregon Cuts Off Funds for Transplants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES E. BEGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To Sheila Holladay, Oregon legislators all
but voted to end her 2-year-old son's life by cutting off funds
that would have paid for a bone marrow transplant.
   So she left southern Oregon this spring to seek welfare funds
for a transplant operation in Washington, where her son David is
awaiting a transplant at that state's expense.
   ``I left my home. I left my dog. I left my life,'' Holladay
said. ``This was extremely frustrating because we had a home there,
we had school there, we had our lives set up there.''
   Her supporters in Oregon raised about $5,000 of the $100,000
needed.
   Oregon lawmakers voted last summer to finance only cornea and
kidney transplants, joining a minority of states that don't pay for
transplant operations such as those of hearts, bone marrow and
livers.
   The move drew little notice, until 7-year-old Coby Howard of
Portland died Dec. 2 of leukemia as his relatives were raising
private contributions for a marrow transplant.
   The resulting furor helped persuade the Legislative Emergency
Board, which handles budget matters between sessions, to take up
the issue. But the board voted against using emergency funds to
reverse the Legislature's action.
   As a compromise, the panel created what's believed to be the
nation's first transplant payment program to be financed by a
combination of federal funds and private donations.
   The program is triggered when $85,000 in donations are turned
over to the state.
   Some backers of restoring state financing said the compromise
was better than nothing. Others were critical.
   ``I really think it was a spineless decision on the part of the
state,'' said Tammi Howard, Coby's mother.
   Howard is leading a petition drive to put a measure requiring
the state to resume transplant financing on November's ballot.
   ``The fact that the state stood by and let a little boy die like
that has stirred up a lot of emotions,'' she said. ``If it was up
to the public, all of these people would have transplants and would
be on the road to recovery by now.''
   Susan McGee, Coby's aunt, deplored a process in which she coaxed
the boy to perform for television in his final days in attempts to
raise money.
   ``I asked him to smile for the camera when, not 30 minutes
before, he had been vomiting due to his illness,'' McGee said. ``I
had to turn Coby Howard into a marketable product so the public
would, in essence, buy him his life.''
   Relatives and friends had raised about $70,000 toward the cost
of the operation by the time he died.
   Forty-one states pay for bone marrow transplants, 36 pay for
heart transplants and about 40 finance liver transplants, said
Jeane Thorne, director of the state transplant program.
   Oregon spent about $500,000 toward 19 heart, pancreas, marrow
and liver transplants in the two-year budget period that ended last
June 30.
   Federal Medicaid funds pay 62 percent of the cost of transplants
for qualified recipients. Thorne had projected the growth in demand
for transplants would push the state's cost to about $800,000 this
year.
   Senate President John Kitzhaber, a physician and co-chair of the
emergency board, opposes renewed state financing for transplants.
He says limited health care dollars must be spent in a way that
will do the most good.
   That standard favors funding prenatal care for many low-income
women instead of financing costly and sometimes risky operations
for a few people, he said.
   ``We cannot keep people alive forever. That is a part of life,''
Kitzhaber said at one meeting. ``What we can do with our limited
money is to try to reduce the number of deaths ... to save as many
people as we can save.''
   Rep. Tom Mason, who hopes to restore state funds, said the
publicity has disgraced Oregon.
   ``The national image that this controversy has brought to the
state is horrendous,'' Mason said.
   ``How many more people actually have to die?'' he asked at the
board's first meeting on restoring the funds.
   ``There's no logic to spend money on prenatal care and then let
them die after they're born,'' Mason said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
