<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 0113EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SummitPlanning     05-23 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit Planning,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Planning A Summit in Moscow: `It's Just Different From Working
Here'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Hooley has planned presidential travel
to most of the 50 states and 18 foreign countries, including the
economic summits in Tokyo and Venice. But President Reagan's trip
to the Soviet Union this week was different.
   Preliminary preparations for the Moscow summit began in 1985
after Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev met in Geneva
and said they wanted to visit each other's country.
   ``It's a whole different mind set,'' Hooley, director of
presidential advance, said of the Soviets. ``They don't deal with
the kind of things we deal with.
   ``We are constantly pushing and urging and prodding for things
that are just sort of anathema to their system.''
   For instance, there was the matter of the private dinner Reagan
and Gorbachev are having at a country home outside Moscow.
   The Soviets insisted there be no press coverage. Hooley
reluctantly agreed, but said there should at least be an official
photographer. The Soviets said no.
   ``I can't seem to get them to grasp the concept that this is an
incredibly historic thing, or potentially historic, these guys
eating dinner out there in this house in the country,'' Hooley said
in a recent interview. ``It would be like having a picture of
Roosevelt and Stalin.
   ``They just don't think like that. You really sense that
instinctively there's a pullback from anything that's going to be
other than exactly like how they do it and how they've done it for
years and years, and that's, of course, very closed.''
   Hooley believes, however, that Gorbachev's policy of
``glasnost,'' or openness, does seem to be having some effect.
   ``There's a bit more than I expected of a willingness to let us
work directly with ... some of the people at the places where we
are going,'' he said. For example, he said, the advance team was
able to work directly with the management of the House of Writers,
which Reagan will be visiting.''
   He added, ``I don't think we were turned down from seeing
anything that we requested to see.
   ``On the other hand, you run into this kind of block with no
explanation on certain issues as to why, once you are there in
these places, you can't do certain things. The security people can
override everybody else ... and they don't feel a need to explain
the reason.''
   Hooley said the initial preparations for the summit consisted
mainly of checking with people who had been involved in Moscow
visits before, including some members of the Nixon administration.
   More active preparations began after the two superpower leaders
met in Washington in December and announced that Reagan would visit
Moscow sometime in the spring.
   Over a period of approximately two months leading up to the
summit, three advance teams visited Moscow, one more than usual.
   For a domestic trip, as when the president goes to Chicago or
New London, Conn., one person from the advance offices makes the
initial survey, checking out proposed speech sites with an eye to
establishing communications, security and the other facilities
needed for a presidential visit.
   On a foreign trip, this group is increased to about 10 or l2
senior people who ``get a few concepts agreed to'' in consultation
with their counterparts from the host country, Hooley said.
   The final advance team, whether the president is going to
Baltimore or Bali, is a larger group of maybe 45 to 50, including
technical people, to make specific arrangements.
   In the case of the summit, Hooley, Director of Communications
Thomas C. Griscom and Jack Courtemanche, first lady Nancy Reagan's
chief of staff, made an extra visit ``to negotiate the finer points
of the schedule,'' the advance official said.
   The ``ambiguous phrase'' used by people who had been to the
Soviet Union suddenly became clear, Hooley said. ``They'd say,
`It's just different from working here.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
