<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 0114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Shultz     05-23 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz: Gorbachev's Mars Mission Proposal Needs Study</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gorbachev</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Lead prospects uncertain</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz says
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's proposal for a joint mission
to Mars ``has to be studied carefully'' and may be taken up under a
U.S.-Soviet space agreement.
   ``That's something that's been talked about, but it's a long way
from being agreed upon,'' Shultz said, appearing on ABC-TV's ``This
Week With David Brinkley.''
   Gorbachev, in an interview with The Washington Post and Newsweek
published Sunday, said he would ask President Reagan to approve a
joint, unmanned flight to Mars when they meet in Moscow for their
May 29-June 2 summit.
   Asked if the United States would pursue such a venture, Shultz
noted the superpowers reached an agreement on space ventures about
a year ago under which particular projects are examined.
   ``I presume this will come up under that heading,'' Shultz said
Sunday, adding, ``Obviously this has to be studied carefully. We
always have to be careful with problems of technology transfer.''
   NASA's Samuel W. Keller said Sunday he had told Soviets
scientists 10 days ago about a U.S. decision in principle to take
Soviet Mars-probe equipment along on a U.S. space launch in 1992.
   Keller, the space agency's deputy associate administrator for
space sciences, told The Washington Post that under the U.S. offer,
the unmanned U.S. ``Mars Observer'' spacecraft would carry a Soviet
receiver. If the U.S. craft still were operating when a 1994 Soviet
spacecraft seeks to land on Mars, the Soviet receiver would improve
transmissions to Moscow, he said.
   The secretary of state also urged the Senate to approve the
U.S.-Soviet treaty banning medium-range nuclear missiles in time
for the summit.
   ``It helps certainly to have completed something and to register
that fact. ... It's good to register the fact that we can do it,''
Shultz said.
   The secretary, sidestepping any criticism of the president's
conservative allies who oppose the treaty, lauded the Senate for
its thorough consideration of the pact.
   ``I think the process has gone well. I have only compliments for
the Senate and the way in which they've handled this,'' he said,
adding, ``I think there's been a time for hearings, a time for
questions, a time for critiques and a time for debate. There also
has to come a time to decide and I think we're about there.''
   The pact, formally known as the Treaty on Intermediate-Range
Nuclear Forces, was signed by the two leaders at their December
summit in Washington.
   Both the president and administration officials are eager to
have the ratified treaty as a boost for negotiations with the
Soviet side.
   The Senate has turned aside a wave of amendments designed by its
conservative opponents to kill the treaty, and debate is expected
to continue through much of the week. Approval of the pact requires
67 votes, if all 100 senators are present.
   The secretary of state also echoed the positive remarks
Gorbachev made in the interview with U.S. reporters, in which the
Soviet leader said he hoped he could sign an agreement slashing in
half the superpower arsenals of strategic nuclear weapons before
Reagan leaves office.
   ``It's certainly possible,'' Shultz said of prospects for such a
treaty. ``And I feel certain that at the Moscow summit we will both
want to agree to keep working on it hard. But whether it will
actually happen or not, I don't know. The issues are tough.''
   Queried about talks on the disputed Strategic Defense
Initiative, which has hampered agreement on a strategic missile
pact, Shultz said Reagan has staunchly opposed any impediment to
the development of a defense against ballistic missiles.
   ``That still leaves room for a lot of things,'' the secretary
said.
</TEXT>
