<1ST_LINE>u a AM-RubberStrike 4thLd-Writethru a0885 05-23 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rubber Strike, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0885,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firestone Workers Returning To Jobs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with some workers returning;
picks up 4th graf pvs, `The URW ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the 4,700 Firestone Inc. employees in
six states who had been on strike returned to work late Sunday
after negotiators reached tentative agreement with the United
Rubber Workers on a new contract.
   Union spokesman Curt Brown said ratification votes on the
three-year contract would be held this week at Firestone offices
and plants in Akron; Noblesville, Ind.; Des Moines, Iowa; Decatur,
Ill.; Russellville, Ark., and Oklahoma City.
   Workers at Decatur, Russellville and Nobelsville plants started
to return to work Sunday night. Workers in Akron were expected to
be back on the job Tuesday morning.
   The URW members struck May 15 after Firestone declined to accept
the cost-of-living allowance provided in an industry pattern
agreement the union negotiated with Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co.
   Brown said the new contract followed the Goodyear pattern
reached May 17.
   ``Our major goal had been to keep pattern bargaining, and that
had been all we really asked from Firestone,'' Brown said. ``This
isn't really a greedy contract.''
   Firestone spokesman Robert Troyer said, ``We believe this is a
fair and realistic contract for our employees. The agreement
recognizes the particular needs of Firestone's tire operation.''
   He said the company was optimistic for early ratification of the
contract.
   Under the agreement, Firestone would:
   _ Maintain cost-of-living allowances in each year, with a
one-cent hourly increase for every increase of 0.26 in the Consumer
Price Index.
   _ Boost wages 25 cents per hour by deducting that amount from
future cost-of-living adjustments in increments of 10, 10 and 5
cents.
   _Increase retirement pensions for current workers by $3.50 to
$23.50 per month for each year of service. In addition, current
retirees would receive a lump sum bonus of $200 before Dec. 1.
   _ Provide choice of first-dollar health insurance coverage or an
80-20 percent co-payment plan that includes a $1,000 enrollment
incentive bonus.
   _ Make 35 percent matching contributions in the employee savings
plan that is part of the 80-20 comprehensive health plan. Both
plans provide for a 401-K savings plan.
   In addition, the pact assures continuation of the contract if a
Firestone plant is sold to another company during the next three
years, and contains a no-strike wage reopener clause in the third
year.
   Negotiations resumed Saturday at 1:15 p.m. with the assistance
of federal mediator David Thorley and an agreement was reached at 5
a.m. It was the only session held since the strike began May 15.
   The strike was the first involving Firestone since 1976, when
the URW struck all the Akron-based rubber companies except General
Tire.
   In a related development, the union said a contract covering
15,000 Goodyear workers was ratified Sunday when Local 2 in Akron,
which represents 1,700 members, ``overwhelmingly approved'' the
agreement.
   Brown said seven of eleven locals at Goodyear had voted on the
contract. Six locals representing a total of 8,060 members had
approved it, and one with 231 members rejected it.
   Ratification had been assured Friday when a URW local in
Danville, Va., voted by 72 percent to 28 percent to accept the
pact. It was the second Goodyear proposal to be put to a vote.
   URW members at three other Goodyear locals also were scheduled
to vote Sunday. They had approved the inital contract proposal.
   Under the URW constitution, contracts must be approved by ``a
majority of union locals representing a majority of members.''
</TEXT>
