<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Philippines     05-23 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Philippines,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Philippine Rebel Barred From Travel To U.S. Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ The former head of the Philippine communist rebel
army says he was denied entry into the United States for a weekend
seminar, despite an invitation from a congressman and assurances
from Philippine government officials that he is not a threat.
   ``Some absurd perceptions of some influential quarters in the
Reagan administration about Philippine problems prevented me'' from
attending, said the former rebel, Bernabe Buscayno.
   He spoke by telephone from Manila to the Philippine-American
group that had scheduled him as its featured speaker at a
Washington seminar on the Philippines, which ended Sunday night.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman in Manila, Jerry Huchel, said Sunday
that Buscayno was turned down for an immediate visa because of
``the unusual nature of his case,'' but he said the application was
referred to the State Department for a possible waiver. The State
Department has no official spokesman available on weekends.
   Buscayno, who is still widely known among Filipinos by his rebel
name, ``Commander Dante,'' was jailed by ex-President Ferdinand E.
Marcos but set free when President Corazon Aquino came to power in
February 1986. In the late 1960s, he founded and led the New
People's Army which officials estimate now has up to 25,000 rebels
fighting the Aquino government.
   Buscayno has not renounced communism, but a Philippine Embassy
official in Washington said he carries a valid Philippine passport
and is no longer considered a rebel or a terrorist. Buscayno was an
unsuccessful candidate for the Philippine Senate last year.
   The Philippine official, who asked not to be identified, said
top embassy representatives informally told U.S. officials they saw
no reason why Buscayno could not travel to the United States.
   Huchel said the U.S. Embassy in Manila was aware that Buscayno
also had an invitation to visit the United States from Rep. Ronald
Dellums, D-Calif., and that he had been scheduled to speak Saturday
at the national conference of the Campaign for Democracy and
Independence.
   The organization, known as CAMDI, includes U.S. groups that
opposed ex-President Ferdinand E. Marcos and originally supported
President Corazon Aquino but have become increasingly critical of
her 2-year-old government.
   Buscayno, in a statement translated for the group from Tagalog,
said he applied for a visa April 27 and was interviewed on May 2
for three hours by Manila embassy vice-consul Lois Matteson. He
said Ms. Matteson asked him if he might have reason to seek asylum
in the United States, since he survived an assassination attempt
last June.
   ``Rest assured, ma'am,'' Buscayno said he replied. ``I am still
rooted in Philippine soil and would not stay a day longer than
necessary.''
   He added: ``She was not convinced. She thought perhaps that I
would mistake the New York skyscrapers for the sugar cane fields of
my central Luzon hometown enough for me to launch a guerrilla
warfare in the metropolitan jungle of the biggest city in the world
to encircle Washington.''
   The U.S. Embassy spokesman in Manila confirmed that Ms. Matteson
interviewed Buscayno but said he could not discuss details of the
visa interview.
   Another speaker at the CAMDI seminar, University of the
Philippines regent Francisco Nemenzo, said he also had trouble
entering the United States last month.
   Nemenzo, who was also jailed for a time under Marcos and has
been critical of Aquino, said his visa was held up until the final
day of another U.S. seminar he was to attend last month. Nemenzo
was affiliated with a now nearly defunct Soviet-allied Philippine
communist party until the early 1970s, when he resigned.
   He said his past connections gave him trouble even though his
last visit to the United States in 1979 was sponsored by the State
Department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
