<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 0235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     05-23 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dispute Could Leave State Party With Two Delegations To Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dispute at Georgia's Republican convention
could leave the state with two competing delegations to the GOP's
national convention in New Orleans this summer.
   Atlanta lawyer Matt Patton took the podium at the convention
this weekend after an angry walkout by GOP Chairman John Stuckey,
who adjourned the meeting and left along with several hundred party
regulars.
   The more than 900 Republicans who remained elected Patton to
preside and continued the convention on their own, adopting a party
platform and electing 18 at-large delegates to the National
Republican Convention.
   Stuckey said he would convene a meeting of the party's state
executive committee to select the official at-large delegates,
leaving open the possibility of two Georgia delegations. Thirty
other GOP delegates were already picked at district conventions.
   Stuckey had presided Friday over an abbreviated session marked
by chanting and booing by many of the 968 delegates _ mostly Pat
Robertson supporters and newcomers to party politics _ who had been
disqualified by the party regulars' credentials committee.
   The credentials committee, complying with a court order,
considered and granted appeals by many of the disqualified
delegates Friday evening and, on Saturday, party officials began
the lengthy process of registering the official delegates.
   But Stuckey adjourned the convention, saying it had been taken
over by what he described as an unruly mob. He told reporters the
court rulings would be appealed to the state's highest court and,
if necessary, the U.S. Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cuomo Predicts a Dukakis Landslide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo says Democrat
Michael Dukakis would win the November presidential election by ``a
landslide'' and Vice President George Bush might even bow out of
the race.
   ``It's totally improbable,'' said Cuomo of a possible withdrawal
by Bush before the Republican convention in August, ``but I
wouldn't rule it out.''
   ``He (Bush) looks so weak anything could happen,'' said Cuomo.
   Cuomo, referring to national polls and continuing political
problems for the vice president, said, ``If I were Bush I'd be
concerned.''
   On the other hand, the New York governor said he was impressed
by Dukakis' ``superb campaign.''
   ``It's not going to be a victory. It's going to be a
landslide,'' Cuomo said.
   Even while talking about a possible major victory for Dukakis,
Cuomo continued to hold off any formal endorsement of the
Massachusetts governor. Cuomo has said he will make his endorsement
after the primaries end on June 7, and that his endorsement will go
to the front-runner at that point.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Poll Shows South Carolinians Support Bush Over Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush holds a
double-digit lead over Democratic presidential front-runner Michael
Dukakis in South Carolina, according to a newspaper poll.
   Vice President Bush, who swept South Carolina in the Republican
primary in March, had the support of approximately 53 percent of
the registered voters in the poll published on Sunday by The
Columbia, S.C. State.
   Dukakis was favored by 41 percent of the people who were given a
choice between the two men. Others said they didn't like either
candidate or hadn't made up their minds.
   ``In the last year we've seen the Republican Party having the
support of both the Republicans and the Independents in South
Carolina, and that hasn't changed,'' said pollster Emerson Smith.
``Bush has a majority, and it's that old situation with the leader
_ he's going to have to do something pretty bad to lose that
support between now and November.''
   Smith is president of Metromark Market Research Inc. of
Columbia, which conducted the poll of 512 registered voters May
16-18 for The State. It has an error margin of plus or minus 4
percentage points.
</TEXT>
