<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Punjab     05-23 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Golden Temple Opens For Public Worship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 600 Sikhs filed solemnly into
the Golden Temple today as it was opened to the public for the
first time in two weeks.
   The temple, Sikhism's holiest shrine, was closed during a police
siege May 9-18 that drove Sikh extremists from their temple hiding
place. The separatists, who have been waging a guerrilla war for an
independent homeland since 1982, had turned the Golden Temple into
an armed camp.
   At least 46 people, mostly Sikh militants, were killed during
the siege. Three militants committed suicide by taking cyanide
capsules rather than surrender to police. No police or paramilitary
forces were killed.
   Services in the inner sanctum of the temple, suspended on the
second day of the siege, were resumed by priests on Sunday after
volunteers washed the floor of the temple with milk to cleanse it.
   Police searched all 627 devotees today for weapons at an
Amritsar police station, then moved them in four city buses to the
temple for worship.
   Police and paramilitary troops retain a cordon around the shrine
and enforce a curfew within 300 yards of its walls.
   The cordon is likely to stay in place until the government
reaches an agreement with the Sikh Temple Management Committee,
which has so far refused its request to enforce a ban on militants
re-entering the shrine.
   One death was reported in Punjab on Sunday night.
   The United News of India said a goldsmith was shot to death by
Sikh gunmen in the village of Murh near the state capital at
Chandigarh.
   Earlier Sunday, nine deaths were reported, including four Hindus
killed in a bomb blast at a railway station in the town of
Ludhiana, 80 miles southeast of Amritsar. Indian newspapers today
said the bombing appeared to be the fourth attack aimed at Hindu
migrant workers, who are in Punjab to help with the planting.
Punjab is India's most productive agricultural state.
   The latest slayings raised to more than 1,150 the number of
people killed by Sikh extremists in Punjab since the start of the
year. In all of 1987, 1,030 people were killed. Most of the victims
have been Hindus or moderate Sikhs opposed to the separatist cause.
   Sikhs claim they are discriminated against by India's majority
Hindus. Sikhs make up less than 2 percent of India's 800 million
people but are a majority in Punjab.
</TEXT>
