<DOCNO> AP880523-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 0320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hungary-Changes Bjt   05-23 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary-Changes, Bjt,0717</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kadar Ouster Signals Open, Orderly Shifts In East Bloc Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hungary, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The departure of Janos Kadar as Hungary's
Communist Party leader came during unprecedented open criticism of
his policies and offered proof of the Soviet bloc's new penchant
for orderly transfers of power.
   Kadar, who ran the party for 32 years, stepped down as general
secretary on Sunday at the end of a three-day conference at which
delegates openly called for new faces and new policies. He turns 76
on Thursday.
   They got their new party leader in Premier Karoly Grosz, a
57-year-old pragmatist who appears open to political reform. Kadar
was named to the largely ceremonial post of party president, a
position created for him.
   According to Politburo member Janos Berecz, Kadar asked
conference delegates who made sweeping changes in the party elite
not to nominate him as party leader, citing age and ``the need for
renewal.''
   Grosz, in turn, nominated Kadar for his new ceremonial post.
   The procedure suggested the change in power may have been agreed
upon in advance in an attempt to unite party ranks increasingly
split in recent months over the pace and shape of reform.
   In Czechoslovakia in December, outgoing party boss Gustav Husak
also reportedly nominated his successor, Milos Jakes. Jakes has
kept Husak in the Politburo and in the ceremonial state presidency.
   Both transfers occurred without the outward tumult that
surrounded Husak's promotion in 1969 to replace Alexander Dubcek
after the Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968, or
Kadar's rise to power after the Soviets crushed the Hungarian
revolt of 1956.
   It is not clear how much of a role the Soviets played in either
of the recent transitions. Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has
pledged not to interfere in the affairs of his Eastern European
allies, but his reforms undoubtedly increased pressure on both
Kadar and Husak.
   Kadar's departure leaves Todor Zhivkov of Bulgaria, in power
since 1954, as the only Soviet bloc leader from the 1950s still in
office.
   Zhivkov and East Germany's Erich Honecker, who so far has
refused to follow Gorbachev's political and economic reforms, both
are 75 and likely will come under increased pressure to step down.
   They may be more willing to do so now that Kadar and Husak have
shown that it is possible to relinquish the top party post while
still remaining on the political scene, albeit with diminished
power.
   But it is unlikely that either will face such public criticism
as Kadar, who in the past two decades tolerated a degree of open
discussion rare in the Soviet bloc until Gorbachev took over the
Kremlin in March 1985.
   Hungary's relative openness was in full display at the three-day
conference, where several delegates voiced demands for radical
reform.
   They wound up sweeping from power many aging party officials,
including eight Politburo members. The changes leave Hungary with a
young and untried ruling body that contains two women, a novelty in
the Soviet bloc.
   The average age of the 11 new Politburo members is 52. Only
three men have been members since 1985, two were promoted in a
party reshuffle last June and six new members were added Sunday.
   Another Soviet bloc rarity was the promotion to the Politburo of
a former member of the body, Reszo Nyers. Dubbed the father of
Hungary's pioneering economic reforms in the 1960s, Nyers was
ousted from the Politburo in 1973 after apparently pushing too hard
for more changes.
   The promotion to the ruling body of Nyers and Imre Pozsgay, an
outspoken advocate of referendums on key issues and dialogue with
independent political groups, may be designed to muzzle their most
radical public statements.
   But it also signals Grosz' readiness to take reformists into the
top echelons of power, guaranteeing them input into a policy to
tackle Hungary's economic crisis and restore public confidence in
the party.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Alison Smale, Vienna bureau chief of The
Associated Press, has covered Soviet and East Bloc affairs since
1982. She spent four years in the Soviet Union for the AP before
moving to Vienna a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 0347EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Grosz     05-23 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Grosz,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Karoly Grosz: New Leader In Hungary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hungary, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Karoly Grosz, Hungary's new Communist
Party leader, has built a reputation as a canny, pragmatic
politician with a charisma not unlike that of his Soviet
counterpart, Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Grosz, 57, succeeded Janos Kadar on Sunday as general secretary
during an overhaul of the party leadership.
   After becoming premier in June, Grosz established himself as a
politician willing to tackle unpleasant economic issues while
softening the blow of austerity measures with the promise of
political reform.
   He has moved around the country, chatting with workers and
apparently enjoying interviews with journalists from the state-run
media. During a visit last month to Britain, he proved to be an
unabashed admirer of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   These tactics overshadowed party ideologist Janos Berecz,
Grosz's main rival in the battle to become party chief, and Kadar
himself, who was left to shoulder the blame for Hungary's economic
crisis.
   Like Gorbachev, who is two years his junior, Grosz comes from an
impeccable background and got his start in politics during the
turbulent times of Josef Stalin's death in 1953.
   Official biographies say Grosz was born into a worker's family
in 1930 in the northeastern city of Miskolc.
   A Communist by 1945, Grosz followed his mother into work in a
print shop. By 1949, he was in Budapest with the national party
youth organization.
   Seizing a chance for promotion and education, Grosz entered the
country's Military Academy in the early 1950s, training as an
officer for the Hungarian army, whose upper ranks had fallen victim
to sweeping Stalinist purges.
   Within a year, Grosz was a deputy lieutenant. He then served as
full lieutenant stationed near the Yugoslav border who also was
charged with the political education of his battalion.
   In November 1954, Grosz was discharged from the army and sent to
Borsod County Party Committee in northern Hungary to observe party
organizations, factories and coal mines in his native Miskolc.
   Official accounts suggest Grosz spent the turbulent year of 1956
in Miskolc, removed from the turmoil in Budapest, where Kadar
emerged as undisputed leader after Soviet troops crushed an
anti-Stalinist revolt and arrested liberal leader Imre Nagy.
   By 1961, Grosz had moved up to the central apparatus of the
Hungarian Socialist Workers' Party after a spell at the party
academy and was named party head at state-run radio and television.
   Between 1968 and 1973, Grosz was deputy head of the party's
Central Committee propaganda department, and from 1974 to 1979 was
in full charge of the official propaganda machine.
   He returned to Borsod as regional party head in 1979, and in
December 1984 advanced to head the influential Budapest party,
which contains almost one quarter of the nation's 800,000
communists.
   At the national party congress in March 1985, Grosz was elevated
to the ruling party Politburo.
   When Grosz was named premier, he almost immediately acknowledged
that some political reform was needed to complement stringent
economic measures he pushed to control mounting foreign debt.
   He pushed through the East bloc's first value-added and personal
income taxes, designed to deregulate price controls and tap the
income from the second jobs many Hungarians hold to make ends meet.
   Although his austerity program is to last until 1990, Grosz has
stressed there is no target date for overcoming Hungary's economic
crisis.
   Grosz has outlined vague plans for parliament to have a larger
and more supervisory role in government decision-making, and even
countenanced dialogue with unofficial opposition groups who do not
contest Communist rule.
   ``This government is not likely to go down in history as one of
the victorious,'' Grosz said last fall, ``but if we can succeed, we
will be praised for taking an interest in the country.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 0433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     05-23 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writers, Producers to Meet With Federal Mediator</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Meeting begins at 5 p.m. EDT; lede prospects unlikely</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scriptwriters' strike against movie and TV
producers entered its 12th week with potential for a break as a
federal mediator called both sides together for the first formal
talks in more than a month.
   The meeting between representatives of the Writers Guild of
America and the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers
was set this afternoon.
   It was the third such effort and the first since a 20-minute
session April 18.
   Recent informal discussions between the sides came to nothing,
said Herb Steinberg, an Alliance spokesman.
   Both sides have suffered from the walkout, which began March 7
over issues of payments for reruns, works distributed in foreign
countries and creative control.
   The meeting was set only four days before guild members were
scheduled to vote on proposed contracts with up to 24 independent
producers. The vote could provide much-needed jobs for a
substantial number of writers, said guild spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden.
   Leaders of the 9,000-member union have granted only two waivers
to independent producers but are recommending that West and East
Coast members ratify the independent contracts in hopes of
shortening the walkout, she said.
   ``It's showing that the proposals of the guild are reasonable
and that businesses feel they can conduct their business profitably
with those contracts,'' she said.
   But Steinberg said: ``They've been saying that for 12 weeks, and
we've been telling them their reasoning is unreasonable. ... There
can't be a settlement if they're coming and demanding more.''
   ``So far the only independents they've signed are none. Even the
independents find their deal too difficult to swallow,'' he said,
citing a decision by Johnny Carson of NBC's ``The Tonight Show'' to
broadcast shows despite the strike.
   On April 14, the union approved independent contracts with the
``New Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour'' and Ivan Reitman Productions,
which has produced such movies as ``Ghostbusters'' and ``Animal
House.''
   Although other independent contracts were considered, the guild
voted against approval at the time.
   Ms. Rhoden said more than 150 producers have asked to negotiate
with the guild for independent contracts.
   None of the independents who negotiated separate deals are among
the 200 represented by the alliance, Steinberg said.
   Steinberg said the signing of the independents would not affect
negotiations, because they represent less than 10 percent of
feature film and 15 percent of television production.
   Producers say the strike has cost the industry more than $15
million in lost jobs and production time, with about 1,400 clerical
workers, cast and crew members laid off due to the stop in scripts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
