<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-23 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange dropped slightly
today in Tokyo and the dollar also fell after moving in a narrow
range in lackluster and trendless trading.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues shed 144.09
points, or 0.52 percent, after recovering some of its morning
losses in the afternoon session. It closed the trading day at
27,249.76 points. The main market barometer had lost 248.79 points
by the end of the morning session.
   Nothing really affected the stock market, said Ron Napier, vice
president of the Japanese equities department at Salomon Brothers.
   ``The problem is Japan has to open all by itself Monday
mornings,'' Napier said. ``There's not really any market-moving
news.''
   He added that the ``stock market was very shaky in the U.S. last
week, which caused a general sell-off (in Tokyo).''
   Volume share in the first section of the TSE was 700 million
shares, down from its last Friday's 800-million-share total.
   In foreign exchange dealings, meanwhile, the dollar closed at
124.80 yen, down 0.02 yen from its last week close, but slightly
higher than its opening today at 124.78 yen.
   The currency fluctuated in a narrow range between 124.71 yen and
124.82 yen during the day.
   ``With no specific market-moving incentives at hand, the dollar
remains in a narrow range,'' said an exchange dealer at a major
commercial bank, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He added that market participants were trying to keep the U.S.
currency at a low 124-yen level.
   `We're likely leading to a period where Japanese trade surpluses
will be higher again, and we're concerned about that,'' Napier said.
   ``Also the U.S. does seem to have inflation problems... On that
basis the yen should be higher than the dollar,'' he added.
</TEXT>
