<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 0457EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Economy     05-23 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Economy,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economic Plan Would Turn Japan's Strength Inward</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic strategists today gave Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita a five-year plan urging that the Japanese economy
be directed at increasing domestic demand and reducing the
country's massive trade surplus.
   The plan, made public after six months of research at
Takeshita's behest, puts an official imprimatur on the recent shift
in Japan's economy, which achieved vibrant growth last year mostly
on a boom in domestic housing rather than the traditional method of
expanding exports.
   A summary of the plan for 1988 through 1992 said three major
economic problems ``can all be resolved by promoting and
consolidating the shift to a domestic-demand-led economy.''
   The problems, it said, were how to reduce Japan's trade surplus,
how to improve the quality of life for the 122 million Japanese and
how to promote ``balanced national economic and social
development.''
   If the plan's aims are attained, it should please Japan's
trading partners like the United States and Western Europe, who
have complained for years that the export-minded Japanese weren't
taking effective measures to reduce trade imbalances.
   Takeshita asked the Economic Council, a task force reporting to
the prime minister, to produce a five-year plan last November
shortly after he succeeded Yasuhiro Nakasone.
   The chairman of the council, Gaishi Hiraiwa, who is chairman of
Tokyo Electric Power Co., told reporters in a briefing that Japan's
previous 10 economic plans since 1955 had aimed at quantitative
expansion, but the new plan envisions the transformation of
economic structure and tries to attain ``qualitative enhancement.''
   Attaining the goals will mean ``pain and burden to the people at
large,'' he said. ``Therefore, I believe that the understanding and
cooperation of the Japanese people are needed more than ever.''
   The plan will be debated by Takeshita's Cabinet in coming weeks
and its general outlines are expected to guide Japan's economic
development.
   The plan's directions are similar to those in a 1986 economic
report requested by Nakasone. The Maekawa Report, compiled by a
panel headed by former Bank of Japan Gov. Haruo Maekawa, also
recommended a shift away from export industries to domestic demand
_ the direction the economy has taken _ but didn't achieve the
status of a report approved by the Cabinet.
   The new plan predicts real economic growth averaging 3.75
percent annually over the five years. Domestic demand would provide
a 4.25-percent average growth rate, it said, while exports would
provide negative growth of a half-percent annually.
   It offers no target for Japan's surpluses of trade and payments,
saying instead they should reach ``internationally harmonious
levels during the period of the plan.''
   In the fiscal year ended March 31, Japan's trade surplus dropped
for the first time in eight years, from $89.7 billion in 1986-87 to
$76 billion in 1987-88, according to government statistics.
   The high value of the yen, which has doubled against the dollar
in the past three years, has increased the Japanese appetite for
foreign goods while making Japanese exports more costly in overseas
markets.
   Last year, for instance, Japanese automakers fell slightly short
of their government-set quota of 2.3 million cars exported to the
United States because Japanese cars are no longer so much of a
bargain for U.S. buyers.
   The plan urges the introduction of the five-day, 40-hour
workweek _ now many Japanese work six days a week.
   For foreign countries, the new economic plan offers the
following directions:
   _Improving access to the Japanese market so that Japan is ``a
land of business opportunity for the world at large.''
   _``Contributing to a better world'' through trade and investment
and by increasing foreign aid and capital-recycling to developing
countries.
   _Contributing to stabilization of the international currency
markets by cooperating with other leading industrial countries on
economic policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
