<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brite-SharkSale     05-23 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brite-Shark Sale,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Great White Sells for $600</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 2,000-pound great white shark caught off of
San Clemente Island drew lots of nibbles but no bites until a
collector hooked it for $600, a fish seller said.
   A weeklong crowd of gawkers, restaurant owners and taxidermists
paraded through the freezer of Galletti Brothers Seafoods on
Terminal Island, giving manager Dino Lauro headaches but no sales.
   ``It's time to get rid of that thing,'' he said. ``I'm tired of
answering phones. It's taking away from my regular business.''
   A collector who wanted the jaws finally bought it on Thursday,
said Lauro.
   The fish broker said he initially had hoped to get $1,500 for
the shark because of publicity surrounding its May 13th capture
about 20 miles south of San Clemente Island.
   Lauro said he could not sell the meat because the fish had been
dead too long to cut into steaks, and anyway, many people refuse to
eat great whites.
   The Aggressor, a San Pedro fishing boat owned by Anthony Tipich,
snared the shark in gill nets a few days after a great white
spotted in shallow water off Newport Beach prompted authorities to
close beaches.
</TEXT>
