<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 0519EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ScienceOlympiad     05-23 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Science Olympiad,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Naked Egg Drop, Weighted Balloon Events Challenge Science
Olympians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of America's future chemists and
physicists applied scientific principles to solving puzzles that
included dropping raw eggs and slowing the ascent of balloons.
   About 1,200 junior and senior high school students from 36
states, who had already competed in local, state and regional
contests, met here Saturday for the fourth annual National Science
Olympiad. Junior high students competed in 22 events and high
school students entered 23 events.
   The competition was sponsored by the Army Reserve Officer
Training Corps.
   ``This Science Olympiad is the first thing I've seen in the last
18 years that has stimulated the minds of these students,'' said
Charles Goslein, an assiciate dean of instruction at Penn Valley
Community College in Kansas City, Mo., who presided at the balloon
race.
   Two Georgia teen-agers used motor oil, dough and foam to cushion
the landing of a raw egg dropped 25 feet to win the Naked Egg Drop.
   Laura Turner and Caroline McCoy, both 16 and from Tift County
(Ga.) High School, said the key was the motor oil blended into the
half-inch thick cushion.
   In the competition, medium-size raw eggs were dropped from great
heights and caught with cushion containers designed to keep the
shells intact. Cushion materials included marshmallow, peanut
butter, Jell-O, raspberry jam, wet towels, axle grease, noodles on
cotton, and soggy whole white bread on plastic foam.
   ``The problem wasn't really keeping it from cracking but keeping
it from bouncing off,'' said Ms. Turner. ``The motor oil ... made
it stick. It just sat there in the motor oil.''
   In the balloon race, students dreamed up ways of slowing the
ascent of balloons from the floor to a ceiling finish-line.
   Debra Martinsen, a senior at Toledo High School near Olympia,
Wash., and schoolmate Hungman Chan, a junior, designed an
accordion-shaped construction-paper anchor for their balloon.
   ``First you find the area of density of a piece of paper and
then you find the buoyant force of the balloon,'' said Ms.
Martinsen, who sat at a table in front of a scale, ``and then with
math you find out how much paper you need to counteract the buoyant
force of the balloon.''
   Ms. Martinsen had flown to the competition from Gainesville,
Fla., where she participated in a three-day National Humanities and
Science Symposium. She was worried the two events would make her
fall behind at school.
   ``When I get back I have five days to catch up on everything and
then graduate,'' she said.
   Not all the events were strictly scientific.
   Eighth-grader Adrienne Crosier of the Caesar Rodney Junior High
School in Camden, Del., fashioned a bass fiddle from a potato chip
can, broomstick handle and venetian blind cord for a competition
called the Sound of Music. All contestants were required to play
``America the Beautiful'' on instruments from nonmusical objects.
   At the end, they formed their own orchestra.
   In addition to winners in the individual events, the school with
the highest point total captured the division. Haverford (Pa.) High
School won the senior division, while Campus Junior High School in
Irmo, S.C., captured the junior division title.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
