<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Stagecoach Accident,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eight Injured in Stagecoach Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEYSERVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of horses pulling a stagecoach
bolted and ran out of control for almost a quarter mile before the
coach slammed into a telephone pole, injuring eight tourists,
authorities said.
   One woman was in serious condition at Healdsburg General
Hospital after Sunday's accident; the others were treated for minor
injuries and released, authorities said.
   The coach was part of a vineyard tour in Sonoma County, said
California Highway Patrol officer Tom Hunter.
   Tour guide Richard Dilworth was in a vineyard explaining grape
growing when he started to get back in the coach.
   It was then the horses bolted. Dilworth grabbed the reins but
the wheels rolled over them and broke them.
   The horses veered off the road and headed straight for the pole.
Hunter said half the team went to the left of the pole, the other
to the right and the stagecoach rammed it.
   Gretchen Urban of Chicago was the most seriously injured.
</TEXT>
