<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Sweep Through Iowa, Nebraska After Hitting South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms rolled across parts of Iowa and Nebraska today
after storms in the South brought destructive winds, hail and a
tornado that damaged two homes in Alabama.
   The thunderstorms extended Sunday night from Alabama and
Mississippi to the Ohio Valley. A tornado touched down in
Pickensville, Ala., extensively damaging two homes as it ripped
down power lines and trees. Gas leaks also were reported. There
were no reported injuries.
   Elsewhere in Alabama, in Huntsville a barn was destroyed and
trees were damaged in nearby Plevna, where winds were estimated
between 50 and 60 mph. In Fayette, police reported power outages as
the storm system swept north. Large hail also pelted parts of
Madison County.
   Less destructive thunderstorms were reported across southern
Iowa and eastern Nebraska this morning.
   Rain fell from northern Arkansas across northeast Oklahoma and
parts of Missouri and Kansas to eastern Colorado. Rain also fell on
much of Nebraska and South Dakota.
   Dense fog loomed this morning over portions of the Northeast.
Visibility was near zero in parts of Maine and New Hampshire.
   Clear skies prevailed in Louisiana and Texas, as well as in
northern Minnesota across North Dakota to central Montana.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from eastern portions of the Central Plains to most of the nation
from the Mississippi River to the East Coast; showers and
thunderstorms from Ohio and Kentucky across the middle Mississippi
Valley to eastern Kansas and northern Arkansas; widely scattered
showers and thunderstorms in western Montana.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s or 80s for most of
the nation; in the 60s for the upper Great Lakes, the Central
Plains, the central Rockies and the Pacific coast; lower 90s in the
south Atlantic states and the Rio Grande Valley of Texas; the 90s
for central California and between 95 and 105 in the desert
Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 38
degrees at Laramie, Wyo., to 88 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 70 cloudy; Boston 60 foggy; Buffalo 59 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 74 fair; Cincinnati 65 showery; Cleveland 66
cloudy; Detroit 64 hazy; Miami 80 fair; New York 59 foggy;
Philadelphia 61 foggy; Pittsburgh 61 foggy; Portland, Maine 51
foggy; Washington 66 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 44 fair; Chicago 58 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth
61 fair; Denver 46 cloudy; Des Moines 64 showery; Indianapolis 65
foggy; Kansas City 64 foggy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 62 partly cloudy;
Nashville 62 cloudy; New Orleans 68 fair; St. Louis 63 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 58 windy; Anchorage 54 cloudy; Las Vegas 77
cloudy; Los Angeles 61 partly cloudy; Phoenix 88 partly cloudy;
Salt Lake City 64 fair; San Francisco 53 fair; Seattle 48 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 61 fair; Toronto 57 cloudy.
</TEXT>
