<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SteinbeckSale     05-23 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinbeck Sale,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Successful Sale of Steinbeck Possessions to Have Sequel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who staged a sale of items owned by the
late author John Steinbeck says the sale was so successful she will
produce a sequel in mid-June.
   About 60 percent of the estate was sold, said Sylvia Link, who
put together the auction of Steinbeck goods inspected by an
estimated 12,000 people on Friday, Saturday and Sunday.
   ``If we had reduced prices, everything would be gone,'' she
said. Most estates are liquidated in three days, but Link and
Steinbeck's two sons decided not to drop the prices.
   Tom Steinbeck has said he probably will release more of his
father's items for sale, Link said.
   The day before the June sale will be reserved for students, who
showed great interest in Steinbeck items, she said.
   Link didn't know late Sunday how much money was raised at the
weekend sale.
   The lowest-priced items sold were cards for $5, and the most
expensive was a $4,200 desk, she said. Among the items left were a
$5,200 Chippendale corner cupboard, paintings that ranged in price
from $300 to $6,000, and lamps with prices starting at $300.
   Buyers purchased wine glasses, bow ties, a desk and a baptismal
gown. One shopper bought two oil paintings, one of which, he
learned from Tom Steinbeck, inspired the elder Steinbeck's poem
``Burning Bright.''
</TEXT>
