<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Guatemala-Quakes     05-23 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Guatemala-Quakes,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Orders Closings After Series Of Earthquakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government ordered schools, government
offices and businesses in Guatemala City to close today after
dozens of small and moderate earthquakes shook the area in recent
days.
   The quakes have caused considerable alarm among the 2.8 million
residents of Guatemala City and the surrounding Guatemala province,
but no injuries or serious damage have been reported.
   On Sunday, Communications Minister Mario Lopez announced that
public buildings and businesses in the capital must close today
only as a precaution ``because of the situation caused by the
constant and continuous earthquakes.''
   The action was taken, he said, ``to avoid any (traffic)
congestion and so that families can be together in their homes.''
   The order does not affect essential services, such as hospitals
and the international airport.
   Col. Juan Ismael Morales Lopez, coordinator of the National
Emergency Committee, initially reported that just public and
private schools would be closed today, but the order was later
expanded to include businesses.
   The National Seismological Institute recorded 22 earthquakes on
Saturday and an additional 22 temblors by late Sunday evening.
   Eddy Sanchez, deputy director of the National Seismological
Institute, said the strongest quakes, two occurring Sunday
afternoon, registered 4.4 on the Richter scale. Some local radio
stations reported the Sunday quakes caused cracks in some houses
and broken windows in the downtown commercial area.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. A quake with a magnitude of 4 can cause moderate
damage.
   The seismological service measured 22 quakes on Saturday, with
the strongest registering 4 on the Richter scale.
   The epicenter of the quakes was on the southwestern edge of the
capital near La Aurora International Airport, said Sanchez. On
Thursday, a quake registering 4 on the Richter scale was felt in
the area.
   A quake measuring 7 on the Richter scale devastated the capital
on Feb. 4, 1976, causing more than 22,000 deaths.
</TEXT>
