<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-StockTrading     05-23 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Stock Trading,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine Foreign Firms Begin Trading On Tokyo Exchange</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine foreign securities firms, including six from
the United States, began trading today on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The nine were among 22 firms, 16 of them non-Japanese, that were
authorized last week to begin trading today on the exchange. The
others will join the market by June as they become ready.
   ``Of the 122 firms authorized to trade on the exchange, foreign
companies now number 22, or about 20 percent,'' said Toshiichi
Konuma, president of Nissan Securities and a member of the
exchange's board of directors.
   ``As we internationalize the Tokyo exchange, it has become
necessary to align the needs and desires of foreign firms with the
longstanding habits of Japanese traders,'' he said in an interview.
   The first six foreign members of the exchange joined in 1986
after the United States and Britain put strong pressure on Japan to
liberalize its equities markets. The 22 were among 40 firms that
applied for membership.
   ``To participate in transactions on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, it
is very important to be a member,'' said Nick Bedford, managing
director of Japanese equities for Salomon Brothers Asia Ltd., one
of the American firms that began trading today. ``It's very
difficult to be accepted by domestic institutions. You have to be
part of the club.''
   The other foreign firms that began trading today included
Kidder, Peabody International Corp.; First Boston (Asia) Ltd.;
Shearson Lehman Brothers Asia Inc.; Smith Barney; Harris Upham
International Inc., all of the United States.
   Each firm paid $9.1 million to join the exchange. Six are
American, four British, and two each from France, Switzerland and
West Germany.
</TEXT>
