<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolShootings-Teacher     05-23 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Shootings-Teacher,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher Recalls Shooting of Children</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-School Shootings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A substitute teacher hailed by police as a
hero in an elementary school shooting spree says she thought the
assailant was a classroom observer before the woman brandished a
handgun.
   Amy Moses, 29, says she tried to share with Laurie Dann the
excitement the second-graders had over an upcoming bicycle safety
test at Hubbard Woods Elementary School.
   ``I really wanted her to know why the children were so happy,''
Ms. Moses recalled at a news conference Sunday.
   ``My impression at the moment was that she was a college student
who had come to the school to observe the class, which is not
unusual,'' Ms. Moses said.
   Ms. Dann sat next to her for a while Friday before leaving the
classroom and later returning, apparently after going into a boys'
restroom and shooting Robert Trossman, 6.
   Ms. Dann, a baby sitter with a history of ``bizarre'' behavior,
then told Ms. Moses to herd the 24 children in her class together.
   Instead, Ms. Moses grabbed the woman's gunhand. But Ms. Dann
pulled a second gun, sprayed the classroom with bullets and then
fled.
   Ms. Dunn, 30, shot five students in the classroom, killing one
and seriously wounding the others.
   Winnetka Police Chief Herbert Timm said if Ms. Moses had
followed the assailant's orders, ``We would have probably had all
of the children shot.''
   Timm called Ms. Moses a hero.
   ``I really just went on automatic pilot. ... I can't explain how
unreal the whole situation was,'' Ms. Moses said, adding that the
gun looked like a toy at first. But after the initial shot, she
said, ``I was just frozen.
   ``When the first child went down, my first thought was, `They're
filming a movie and they forgot to tell me.' It wasn't until the
second shot that we all realized it was real.''
   Ms. Dann's face was ``expressionless'' and ``hard,'' she said.
   Police also credited Ms. Moses with giving a full description of
the assailant, who later barricaded herself in a suburban home
where she wounded a 20-year-old man and killed herself.
   Ms. Moses said she would return to the school.
   ``I love Hubbard Woods School,'' said Ms. Moses, who has worked
there in various capacities for the past five years and is studying
toward a master's degree in education.
   ``I know the faculty, the administration and a lot of the
children and some of the parents. ... I feel like the support
system will be real helpful to me. The children and the families _
everyone has been wonderful.''
</TEXT>
