<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NuclearTest     05-23 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Test,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Underground Nuclear Test Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YUCCA FLAT, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear warhead was detonated
underground at the Nevada Test Site during the weekend while
visiting Soviet scientists made preparations to monitor a future
test, a Department of Energy spokesman said.
   The test, codenamed ``Laredo,'' was conducted at 3:30 p.m.
Saturday. It was originally scheduled Thursday but was postponed
because of strong winds blowing toward Las Vegas, about 75 miles to
the southeast.
   The U.S. Department of Energy, which oversees the testing
program, prohibits blasts under certain weather conditions.
   The nuclear warhead was detonated about 1,200 feet underground
as seven Soviet scientists spent the weekend in Mercury, Nev.,
about 32 miles from ground zero. The town houses test site workers.
   The Soviets are preparing for a joint experiment later this
summer in which the Soviets will monitor a U.S. test. More than two
dozen American scientists also are at the Soviet test site,
preparing to monitor a Soviet blast.
   Jim Boyer, an Energy Department spokesman, said there was
considerable ground motion noted by observers in a building eight
miles from ground zero.
   The test was not as large as the 150-kiloton maximum limit
adhered to by the United States and the Soviet Union, but Boyer
would not reveal the weapon's power.
   The blast appeared normal, he said, with no indications that
radioactivity had escaped the underground cavern. The test was the
fourth announced this year and the 679th announced test since
testing began in Nevada in January 1951.
</TEXT>
