<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson Hold-For-ReleaseLd-Writethru a0453 05-23 0778</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, Hold-For-Release Ld-Writethru, a0453,750</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 2 p.m., EDT</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 15 grafs, embargoed material on Jackson's budget
plan; picks up 6th graf, He told</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential hopeful Jesse
Jackson today released details of a five-year federal budget
proposal which would increase taxes on the wealthy by $244 billion,
cut defense spending by $164 billion and increase spending on
social programs by $344 billion.
   ``We must forge a mandate to reverse Reaganomics,'' Jackson said
in a written statement accompanying his budget blueprint.
   The spending plan, called ``Paying for Our Dreams, A Budget Plan
for Jobs, Peace and Justice,'' also calls for $87 billion in cuts
in projected spending on non-defense programs and $104 billion in
tax increases on corporations.
   Jackson said his proposals would also cut the nation's deficit
from a projected $134 billion in 1993 to $49 billion.
   Jackson scheduled release of his budget proposal for an
appearance at California's state capitol, one of many campaign
stops Jackson is making in a bid for the state's 314 delegates up
for grabs in the June 7 primary.
   Repeating a campaign theme, Jackson said he would raise up to
$58 billion a year for social programs such as housing, education
and health care by freezing the military budget at its current $300
billion level for the next five years.
   ``If we do not propose bold alternatives, our social needs will
fall victim to the soldiers of austerity which were, in David
Stockman's phrase, hidden in the Trojan Horse of supply side
economics,'' he said, referring to President Reagan's first budget
director.
   ``I am for a strong defense. I also support a sound approach to
the military budget. Our plan would freeze military spending,''
Jackson said in the prepared statement. ``Even after the Jackson
cuts, real military spending will be 25 percent higher in 1993 than
in 1980.''
   The biggest tax increase in Jackson's budget plan would restore
the top 38.5 percent income tax rate on the nation's top 600,000
taxpayers. Other revenue measures would increase the minimum tax
rate on corporations, limit deductions for business meals to 50
percent, and impose a $7-billion-a-year ``polluters tax'' on
corporations.
   Among his proposed spending increases, described as ``new
investments,'' are programs which by 1993 would spend an extra $20
billion annually on education and job training, $17 billion on
housing programs, $12 billion on health and nutrition programs and
$3 billion more annually on AIDS programs.
   It also includes $5 billion more in transportation funding, $1.7
billion annually on environmental programs and $1 billion more
annually for international economic assistance.
   ``The Jackson budget chooses social and economic investment over
military spending, restores a measure of tax progressivity, and
promotes a balanced mix of monetary and fiscal policy. These
choices can only help the economy,'' he said.
   Following release of his budget proposal, Jackson scheduled a
visit to the nearby Rancho Seco nuclear power plant, on the
invitation of critics of that plant who are sponsoring a ballot
initiative to mandate permanent closing of the publicly owned
reactor.
   Jackson was continuing his campaign Sunday while Democratic
front-runner Michael Dukakis and Republican nominee-to-be George
Bush took weekend breathers.
   Jackson joined a rally of striking Teamsters at a Salinas frozen
foods processing plant on Sunday and administered wedding vows to
the daughter of a California educator who is a hostage in Lebanon.
   He told striking workers they are ``victims of economic
violence,'' and that the Democratic Party should stand with them by
adopting his 10-point plan for ``democracy in the work place.''
   The Democratic Party ``must stand with the working people. It's
the legacy of (President Franklin) Roosevelt. It's the unfinished
business of Dr. (Martin Luther) King,'' Jackson said.
   He said Dukakis, by contrast, had offered an economic vision
that ``is very conservative, very cautious, very inadequate.''
   ``The present conservative commitment by Mr. Dukakis to economic
change represents no hope for the homeless, no hope for the
homeless, the uneducated,'' Jackson said.
   Later, Jackson administered wedding vows to the daughter of
Alann Steen, who has been held hostage in Lebanon since Jan. 24,
1987.
   Jackson said he hoped by participating in the wedding of Rebecca
Steen, a 26-year-old paramedic in Santa Cruz, and Jim Monday, a
33-year-old Santa Cruz fireman, that ``in some unlit corner of
Lebanon, this news may reach and cheer a hostage.''
   ``We will not rest until all the hostages are set free. We will
not rest until the whole Middle East is set free, because the whole
Middle East is held hostage,'' Jackson said as he introduced the
newlyweds at a campaign rally immediately after administering their
vows.
</TEXT>
