<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Chambers     05-23 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chambers,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Victim's Family Thought of Revenge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of a woman strangled in Central Park
says feelings of hate were strong enough to trigger thoughts of
killing Robert Chambers, the man convicted in the so-called
``preppy murder'' case.
   ``You go through a hundred feelings, a thousand feelings and a
thousand emotions when you lose a child. But it's a different thing
altogether when you lose a child by the hands of another,'' said
Ellen Levin, the mother of Jennifer Levin.
   ``You have feelings that you want to kill him and you have
feelings that you want to kill yourself,'' she said in an interview
broadcast Sunday on WNBC-TV's ``News Forum.'' ``There's a big
revenge feeling inside you. You have to work through these things,
but the hate is there and the hate is real.''
   Chambers was charged with murder for the Aug. 26, 1986,
strangulation of Miss Levin. The body of the 18-year-old was found
near the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
   Chambers, 21, pleaded guilty to manslaughter on March 21 and is
serving a five-to-15 year prison sentence.
   Mrs. Levin said that while family members grieved their loss,
Chambers was free to walk around town and enjoy himself as he
awaited trial.
   ``He even had the audacity to come down to Jennifer's
neighborhood and was seen in a local restaurant, two blocks from
her home, cavorting with his friends and drinking and having a
great time,'' she said. ``All of this while we'd go to visit her at
her grave.''
   It was that image that triggered thoughts of revenge in all
members of the Levin family, she said.
   With effort, Mrs. Levin said, family members finally came to
terms with their feelings.
   ``We had to _ we're civilized people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
