<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthAfrica     05-23 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Member, Two Blacks Killed In Separate Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the mixed-race
Parliament was gunned down in a church parking lot near here, and
two blacks died in a bomb blast at a political rally in the black
township of Soweto.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok today said police had no
evidence that the slaying of Peter Sam Jacobs, a member of the
majority Labor Party in the House of Representatives, was
politically motivated.
   ``The police have no reason at this stage to believe that the
murder was committed for political considerations but are
investigating the possibility that clashing personal interests
could have led to the crime,'' Vlok said.
   Jacobs, 42, was shot in the chest after getting into his car in
a church parking lot following a meeting Sunday night near his home
in Alberton, southeast of Johannesburg.
   According to press reports, Jacobs' wife and two other men were
with him in the car when a black assailant smashed the window on
the driver's side and fired a 9mm pistol at Jacobs.
   Jacobs was elected to Parliament in 1984 after a new
constitution was adopted creating segregated chambers for Asians
and mixed-race people along with the existing chamber for whites.
   The new constitution continued to exclude the black majority
from national politics. Anti-apartheid activists of all races
organized a boycott of the Asian and mixed-race elections which
helped keep the turnout below 20 percent.
   The Labor Party has remained estranged from the mainstream of
the anti-apartheid movement. However, its leader, the Rev. Allan
Hendrickse, has taken an increasingly confrontational stance toward
President P.W. Botha in the past year, demanding abolition of the
legislation which establishes racially segregated neighborhoods.
   In Soweto, the explosion that killed two blacks also injured
more than 30 during a Sunday afternoon rally held by the Sofasonke
Party, said police spokesman Noel Hartwell. The Sofasonke Party is
active in municipal politics in the huge township outside
Johannesburg.
   Police were investigating the cause of the explosion at the
outdoor gathering attended by about 100 people, the spokesman said.
He said there were no arrests.
   Municipal elections are scheduled for October, and the Sofasonke
Party is expected to take part. Although blacks have no voice in
national politics in South Africa, they can vote in local township
elections.
   Many black activists charge that the Sofasonke Party is
collaborating with the white-led government by participating in
black municipal politics.
   Hartwell said the meeting was a legal gathering that had been
authorized in advance. Under emergency regulations, outdoor
political gatherings are illegal unless prior permission is
obtained from the courts.
</TEXT>
