<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BogusLawyers     05-23 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bogus Lawyers,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC: Bogus Legal Group Took In $3.3 Million Fraudulently</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Atlanta-based group posing as a national
prepaid legal services firm took in $3 million over a nine-month
period, fooling nearly 400 would-be franchisees, federal officials
say.
   The Lawyers Access Network sold distributorships for a prepaid
legal services plan from March to December 1987, according to
lawyers for the Federal Trade Commission, which has been
investigating the case.
   Prepaid legal services programs offer consumers basic legal
services for a flat annual fee, rather than an hourly rate.
   The firm gathered $3.3 million from 392 people around the
country who believed they were buying franchises by investing
amounts ranging from $5,500 to $25,000, FTC lawyers said. The
figure did not include any fees that might have been sent in by
consumers, they said.
   At best, investors may recover only 10 percent of their
investment, one FTC lawyer said.
   ``This thing makes the movie `The Sting' look small-time,'' said
Dave McQuade, a public relations director in suburban Philadelphia
who paid a $25,000 franchise fee in order to market memberships in
the network.
   ``It was so well set up,'' he said. ``They just had all their
bases covered.''
   The firm used false market research, baseless earnings
projections and bogus references to lure purchasers into believing
its program was successful, profitable and well-established, FTC
lawyers say.
   In a series of legal actions that began in March, the FTC has
shut down Lawyers Access and its marketing arm, American Legal
Distributors Inc., which operated out of the same office in the
Atlanta suburbs. The Federal Bureau of Investigation confiscated
dozens of records from the office during a search.
   According to the FTC, American Legal representatives brought
fancy brochures and a hard-sell pitch to franchise shows nationwide.
   The FTC also won a permanent injunction and default judgment for
more than $3 million earlier this month against firm officials
Patrick Pasley and Thomas Stockton.
   However, Pasley's attorney, Bruce Morris said, ``The fact of the
matter is, whatever representations that may have been made to
(distributors) that turned out to not be true were not made by Mr.
Pasley or with his knowledge.''
   Stockton claimed, ``I didn't set up the company; I was just an
employee.''
   U.S. District Judge Marvin Shoob signed an order freezing 13
bank accounts and other assets allegedly controlled by Pasley.
   FTC lawyer Norman Cramer said, ``There does not seem to be a big
pot of gold out there, at least that we or the FBI have been able
to discover.'' The victims, Cramer said, may at best receive
restitution of 10 percent.
   ``Prepaid legal services is a growth industry, and a legitimate
industry,'' Cramer told the Atlanta Constitution. ``A legitimate
plan along these lines might well be profitable. It's just these
guys went too far.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
