<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Oxen     05-23 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Oxen,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Officials Present Zoo With Alaskan Musk Oxen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials formally presented the Beijing Zoo
with two Alaskan musk oxen today as a Georgia woman who first
suggested the gift beamed fondly at the shaggy animals.
   Four-year-old Tanana, a female, and 3-year-old Koyuk, stood with
lowered heads in their outdoor enclosure as a horde of diplomats,
wildlife experts and reporters gathered on the other side of the
fence.
   ``They're beautiful,'' said Helen Miller, 65, of Moultrie, Ga.,
said of the 300-pound animals.
   Mrs. Miller began campaigning in 1980 for the United States to
present two musk oxen to China. She felt it was a matter of
``national honor'' to replace two U.S. animals, given to China in
1972, that had died of old age.
   The original pair had been presented when President Nixon made
his historic trip to China as the two nations normalized relations.
   ``It took lots of letter-writing, lots of telephone calls and
lots of trips, but I enjoyed all of it,'' Mrs. Miller said.
   ``I heard the Chinese children were very sad'' over the death of
the original oxen, she said. ``So I had to find out what a musk ox
was and ... How can you come by some.''
   As the dignitaries dispersed for a banquet, Tanana and Koyuk ate
grass in their enclosure and Chinese zoo-goers moved in for a look.
   ``They're not bad,'' said a Chinese man in a baseball cap.
   Tanana and Koyuk, named after Alaskan rivers, were born in
captivity in a University of Alaska research herd. About 3,000 to
4,000 of the rare, migratory animals live in Alaska, Canada, the
Soviet Union, Greenland and other areas of the Arctic.
   Mike Smith, spokesman for the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Bureau,
said the pair probably would thrive in Beijing despite temperatures
that sometimes soar into the 90s.
   U.S. Undersecretary of Interior Earl Gjelde, U.S. Ambassador
Winston Lord and more a dozen other American officials attended the
presentation.
   Gjelde called the oxen a ``fitting symbol'' of U.S.-Chinese
friendship and the two countries' commitment to wildlife
preservation. He read a message from President Reagan who said,
``May these musk oxen bring joy to the visitors of Beijing Zoo.''
   ``We will do our best to keep them well,'' promised Beijing Zoo
Deputy Director Shi Senming.
   Tanana and Koyuk actually arrived in China in late March but
were in quarantine until today.
   To the untrained eye, they looked less than jubilant over the
attention, alternately presenting horns to the onlookers and
turning their heads away.
   ``They don't have a wide range of expressions,'' Smith said.
``That's pretty much the normal posture.''
   He said in the wild musk oxen generally live to be 20 to 25.
   The United States gave the original pair of musk oxen in
exchange for giant pandas Ling-Ling and Hsing-Hsing, still in the
Washington Zoo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
