<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-Floods     05-23 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Floods,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Floods Kill 78, Injured 200</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FUZHOU, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of people killed in widespread
flooding in east China's rain-drenched Fujian province has climbed
to 78, a government official said today.
   Chen Zengpo, director of the Fuzhou Economic Commission,
reported the increased death toll and said he and other officials
were monitoring the level of the swollen Minjiang River following
heavy rains Friday and Saturday.
   He said the Minjiang had flooded near Fuzhou, the provincial
capital, but Mayor Hong Yongshi said no deaths had been reported in
that area.
   The most serious flooding was in Fujian province's northern
counties of Jianyang, Chongan and Zhenghe, where the deaths
occurred. More than 200 people were injured and more than 3,100
were forced to flee their homes, according to official media
reports today.
   Officials reported Sunday that 60 people had been killed in the
flooding.
   The nationally televised evening news showed residents wading
through waist-high water carrying household goods over their heads,
or poling through the streets on rafts of logs lashed together.
   The English language China Daily said 19,760 acres were flooded,
900 homes were damaged, 400 sections of road were destroyed and 400
bridges were swept away.
   It said 12 inches of rain fell on one town in a 20-hour period,
and that the water level of a major tributary of the Minjiang was
90 feet above normal.
   Fujian Vice Gov. Yu Dexin said Sunday that land transportation
to north Fujian was cut off and that Gov. Wang Zhaoguo had flown to
the area to supervise rescue operations.
   Unusual weather has plagued much of China this month. Hailstorms
killed at least 24 people and injured more than 250 in coastal and
central China, and a tornado in Guangdong province in southeast
China killed five people.
</TEXT>
