<HEAD>Man Finally Gets Medal for World War II Combat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALLEJO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After four decades, one of the Army's
first K-9 Corps trainers has received a medal for more than 100
World War II missions behind enemy lines.
   ``I don't know why it took them so long to pass out the medal,''
Joseph S. Simpson, 69, said Sunday after he was presented with a
Bronze Star during a ceremony at a dog show at the Solano County
Fairgrounds.
   Simpson, who also established the San Francisco Police
Department's K-9 Unit nearly 20 years ago, was honored for
``meritorious achievement in ground combat against the armed enemy
during World War II,'' the citation said.
   As a member of the 33rd Infantry Scout Dog Platoon, Simpson and
his dog routinely went behind enemy lines on scouting missions,
which they completed safely.
