<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TempleVandalized     05-23 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Temple Vandalized,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Temple Desecration Marks 44th Incident in Florida This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals stenciled three red swastikas on a Dade
County temple, marking the 44th anti-Semitic incident reported in
Florida this year, according to an official of a Jewish
anti-discrimination group.
   The phrase ``Die Jew'' was also spray-painted on a terrace
leading to the entrance of the Bet Breira Congregation, police
said. The vandalism was discovered Sunday morning on the front of
the modern-design synagogue.
   ``There is a great deal of prejudice and hatred in Dade County,
and this act shows that more integration between Anglos, blacks,
Hispanics, Jews and gentiles needs to take place,'' said Barry
Tabachnikoff, rabbi at the 450-member temple.
   The temple was desecrated sometime between late Saturday and
early Sunday, police said. There are no suspects.
   ``I do feel the attack was premeditated because of the
stencils,'' said Arthur Teitelbaum, Southern area director of the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith.
   Teitelbaum said he was concerned about the increase in
anti-Semitic vandalism. A total of 44 incidents have been reported
in Florida this year, compared with 64 last year.
   Vandalism was also discovered Sunday at Miami Killian High
School, about 1{ miles from the temple; vandals used a stencil to
paint five red swastikas and the phrases ``Hitler Lives'' and
``Neo-Nazi Rules.'' Police said they didn't know whether the
incident was related to that at the temple.
   Four teen-agers were recently sentenced in Dade Juvenile Court
to 200 hours of community service and ordered to pay $14,800 in
damages for smashing windows and painting anti-Jewish slogans on
another Dade temple Feb. 26.
   Desecration of a house of worship is a third-degree felony
punishable by a maximum five years in prison and a $5,000 fine.
</TEXT>
