<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Carter     05-23 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Carter,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Mention Of `Killer Rabbit' In Carter's New Outdoor Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELLIJAY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jimmy Carter says that on second thought, he
probably should have included the ``killer rabbit'' episode in his
new book on his outdoor adventures ``just to explain there was
nothing to it.''
   ``An Outdoor Journal: Adventures and Reflections,'' published by
Bantam Books, portrays the former president as an avid hunter and
fisherman who relishes the solitude and physical and intellectual
stimulation the activities provide.
   Carter writes vividly of stalking wild turkey in the Georgia
woods, bagging ducks in Arkansas, battling trophy rainbow trout in
Alaska and fighting a blue marlin in the Virgin Islands.
   But the 224-page book, scheduled for release this week, omits
the most famous outdoor adventure of his presidency _ the 1979
killer rabbit episode, in which he beat back with a paddle a rabbit
he said was swimming toward his canoe during a fishing trip near
Plains.
   ``I guess I should have (included it) just to explain there was
nothing to it,'' Carter said in an interview at his mountain cabin
near here last week. ``But I don't want to get into another
altercation with the press about it. That was a contrivance of the
press.''
   The episode prompted numerous editorial cartoons and jokes at
Carter's expense, and the rabbit was dubbed the ``killer rabbit''
or the ``banzai bunny.''
   Some skeptics claimed that rabbits do not swim, but Carter said
a blowup of an official White House photograph showed the animal
was clearly a rabbit.
   He told reporters at the time, ``It was a fairly robust-looking
rabbit who was swimming, apparently with no difficulty.'' He said
it would have been ``an unpleasant situation for me and the
rabbit'' if the animal had gotten into the canoe.
</TEXT>
