<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Turkey, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0498,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombs Explode Before Turkish Visit To Greece</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs with foreign minister arriving, quotes;
picks up 3rd pvs, `The five-page ...' SUBS 2 grafs for grafs 10th
pvs, `Yilmaz's visit ...' to ADD scheduled Ozal visit, detail of
1987 dispute.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bombs blew up two cars owned by Turkish
diplomats early today, just hours before the arrival of Turkey's
foreign minister. A left-wing terrorist group claimed
responsibility.
   No injuries were reported in the bombings in downtown Athens.
   A few hours after the explosions, Foreign Minister Mesut Yilmaz
of Turkey arrived for talks on disputes that last year brought the
two NATO allies close to war. Yilmaz was greeted at the airport by
his Greek counterpart, Carolos Papoulias. They went to a seaside
hotel where discussions will take place through Thursday.
   Asked whether the bomb attacks would affect the atmosphere for
the talks, Papoulias said: ``I don't see how they can affect it.''
   The left-wing November 17 group, which has taken responsibility
for more than a dozen political killings in Greece, claimed
responsibility for the bombings in a statement sent to the Athens
daily Ethnos. Security police said the claim appeared genuine.
   The five-page typewritten statement was published in today's
edition of the left-wing newspaper, saying the group had targeted
``the fascist Turkish regime which has occupied Cypriot territory
by force for the past 14 years.''
   Premier Andreas Papandreou's socialist government condemned the
attacks, which damaged two cars belonging to Turkish Embassy
administrative officials.
   ``The government expresses abhorrence for these criminal bomb
attacks and condemns most categorically every form of terrorism,
whatever its origin,'' a government statement said.
   Bombs exploded at 2:20 a.m. and 2:25 a.m. beneath cars parked
300 yards apart in a downtown residential area.
   Greek bomb disposal experts defused other devices left beneath
two other cars parked near the Turkish Embassy building on
Vassileos Georgiou Street close to the city center, said the
security police spokesman who requested anonymity in accordance
with Greek practice.
   All the cars carried green diplomatic license plates.
   Yilmaz's visit is seen as a test run for a scheduled June 13-15
trip to Athens by Premier Turgut Ozal, the first by a Turkish
premier to Greece in more than 30 years.
   Greece and Turkey came to the brink of war in March 1987 over
oil drilling rights in the Aegean Sea.
   The talks are being held under tight security following
anti-Turkish threats by Cypriots, Kurdish political refugees and
Greeks who formerly lived in the Turkish city of Istanbul.
   The Cypriots are protesting the continuing presence of an
estimated 30,000 Turkish troops in northern Cyprus. Turkey invaded
the Mediterranean island in 1974 following an Athens-inspired coup.
   Since then, the island has been split into separate Greek
Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot sectors.
   November 17 previously has targeted American diplomats and
leading Greek businessmen. The group is named for the day in 1973
that troops crushed a student rebellion against the 1967-74
military dictatorship.
</TEXT>
