<2ND_LINE>PM-Nasty Primary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0421,0752</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kentucky Congressional Primary Takes A Nasty Turn</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 5th, `In turn...' to include other race.
Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK R. CHELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First, the incumbent questioned his
challenger's religious convictions and branded him a carpetbagger.
Then the Democratic primary race in the 1st Congressional District
really got nasty.
   In fact, Roll Call, a weekly Washington publication that calls
itself ``the newspaper of Congress,'' said the contest ``is turning
into the nastiest primary in the country.''
   Rep. Carroll Hubbard and Lacey T. Smith, who seeks to deny the
incumbent the nomination for an eighth term in Tuesday's election,
have traded charges of incompetence and unethical conduct.
   Hubbard has been accused of improperly directing a congressional
investigation into a bank loan received by Smith.
   In turn, Hubbard has slammed Smith as a carpetbagger, accusing
him of moving back to Kentucky for the sole purpose of seeking
political office. Smith also has been haunted by a legal
entanglement 14 years ago.
   There are no statewide races on the primary ballot, and only one
other congressional race has drawn any interest. Democratic Rep.
Romano Mazzoli is running hard against former television reporter
Jeffrey Hutter in the 3rd District in Louisville. Three Republicans
are running for the 3rd District nomination.
   Smith's race against Hubbard is the incumbent's first tough
challenge since he won the seat in 1974 by upsetting Rep. Frank
Stubblefield.
   Hubbard, 50, has a well-financed campaign and is advertising
extensively in the mostly rural district. One often-repeated jingle
on Hubbard commercials advises Smith to ``Pack up your troubles in
your carpetbag and move, Lacey, move.''
   Smith, 48, moved to Madisonville in August from Florida but has
Kentucky ties. He was a state senator from Louisville in the early
1970s. And he has said that he and his wife have more than 200
relatives living in the district.
   In 1974, Smith was tried on a charge of obtaining money under
false pretenses for allegedly soliciting a bribe from an insurance
agency while he was on the staff of the Louisville mayor. He was
acquitted, and Smith said the charge was brought by an overzealous
Republican prosecutor seeking re-election.
   As for Hubbard, a complaint was filed with the House Standards
of Official Conduct Committee alleging that he improperly ordered
an investigation of a $2.5 million loan Smith received from a
Washington bank.
   The General Accounting Office investigated the loan at the
request of a banking subcommittee that Hubbard chairs but found no
wrongdoing. A GAO official said the agency would not have
investigated if it had known Smith was a candidate.
   Smith has charged that Hubbard is an incompetent lawmaker who
misses important votes and has never passed any significant
legislation. Hubbard counters that Smith's only goal is election to
Congress from a district he does not know.
   The Louisville Courier-Journal, the state's largest newspaper,
reluctantly endorsed Hubbard, saying:
   ``They've spent a lot of time and money accusing each other of
incompetence and sleaze. What's so depressing is that, when you
examine the candidates, the kinds of charges we've heard seem
believable.''
   In a letter to supporters before Smith formally announced his
candidacy, Hubbard sent along copies of church bulletins, voter
registration records and corporate publicity releases showing that
Smith was baptized in a West Palm Beach, Fla., Baptist church on
Aug. 30, four days after he registered to vote in the 1st District.
   Smith later transferred his membership to First Baptist Church
of Madisonville.
   ``I'm glad Lacey Smith has become a Baptist since he's come to
our area,'' Hubbard said in the letter. ``But I find it ironic that
he joined the (Florida church) four days after he registered to
vote in Madisonville.''
   Hubbard's father was a well-known Southern Baptist preacher in
the area for many years.
   Though no reliable polls indicate how the race is going, Hubbard
said he has been the victim of a ``vicious, vitriolic, venomous''
campaign conducted by ``a desperate man trying to do something to
reverse the tide here in the last week.''
   Smith, who recently sold his interest in a Madisonville
engineering firm, said Hubbard has been a ``pen pal congressman''
interested only in his own self-preservation.
   ``If it's taken a nasty turn, it hasn't been because of anything
that I've done,'' Smith said. ``People say that's negative because
his record's negative.''
</TEXT>
