<1ST_LINE>r p PM-GeorgiaGOP     05-23 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Georgia GOP,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dispute Could Leave GOP With Two Competing Delegations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GOP national officials will try to mediate a
dispute that could result in Georgia's Republican Party showing up
at the presidential nominating convention in New Orleans with
competing delegations.
   At the state Republican convention over the weekend, two slates
were elected _ one after party regulars stormed out of the Albany
Civic Center.
   Roger Allen Moore, general counsel for the national Republican
Party, said GOP officials would hear from both sides in the dispute.
   The case first would go before the party's nine-member contest
committee, which would report its findings to the credentials
committee, Moore said. A ruling by the 106-member credentials
committee could be appealed to the national convention in New
Orleans this summer, he added.
   Party regulars elected Fred Cooper, state chairman for the
George Bush campaign, to head the state's 48-member delegation to
this summer's convention, but not until after they had angrily left
the civic center Saturday.
   About 900 dissidents remained at the civic center afterward and
elected a slate headed by Brant Frost, state chairman for Pat
Robertson's failed presidential campaign.
   All 48 delegates are required to vote for Bush at the
convention, since Bush won every county in the state during
Georgia's March 8 presidential primary.
   Robertson captured only 13 percent of the state vote, but his
backers, many of whom are party newcomers, organized in an effort
to influence the party platform and the selection of a vice
presidential nominee.
   The turmoil this weekend stemmed from efforts by state GOP
Chairman John Stuckey and other party regulars to deny
Robertson-dominated county delegations a chance to participate in
the state convention.
   ``This will probably wind up in an awful mess,'' said national
committeeman Carl Gillis. ``All he (Stuckey) had to do was let
these folks be seated.''
</TEXT>
