<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CarolinaOutages     05-23 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carolina Outages,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine-Hour Phone Outage Causes Confusion, Inconvenience</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-No Phones</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A power surge or short circuit at a
Southern Bell switching station in Charlotte plus workers' failure
to notice an alarm light knocked out phone service for up to
400,000 North Carolinians, officials say.
   Southern Bell spokesman Ladd Baucom said Sunday a
battery-powered system took over after the power failure, but when
no one noticed the alarm, the batteries ran down and service was
disrupted.
   ``We missed it,'' he said. ``Ideally, if we had caught the
alarms when we should have, it would have been fixed.''
   Henceforth, additional workers will be posted at the switching
station's alarm area to monitor it round-the-clock seven days a
week, Baucom said.
   Saturday's nine-hour scattered telephone failures affected
customers from Boone in the western mountains to just west of
Rockingham, about 180 miles away, frustrating callers and wreaking
havoc with airline and retail computer systems.
   Calls to 911 were silenced as well, leading police in Charlotte,
the state's largest city, to post officers at fire departments and
major intersections where people who might need help could get them.
   Most officers worked double shifts Saturday, said Chip Bailey,
spokesman for the Mecklenburg County Police Department, which
includes Charlotte.
   ``We don't have any horror stories to come out of it so far,''
Bailey said Sunday after service had been restored.
   The police spokesman said he knew of no crimes, fires or
accidents going unanswered because of the telephone troubles.
   ``In fact, not too long after 911 came back, we got (a report
of) an armed robbery in progress and were able to stop it,'' Bailey
said.
   Other phone customers were not so lucky.
   ``It's going to affect us massively,'' said Carrol Mane,
training manager at Ivey's department store in Gastonia.
   ``We're requiring credit approval on all credit purchases and
we're really going to have a problem closing tonight because we
can't transfer out data,'' she said Saturday evening.
   Martha Eddins, a spokeswoman for Wachovia Bank in Winston-Salem,
said automated teller machines in the affected areas could not
operate without long-distance phone lines to connect computer data
bases.
   The situation also caused confusion at Charlotte-Douglas
International Airport, where arriving passengers could not call
relatives or friends or even a taxicab to pick them up, said J.F.
Terrell of the airport's security force.
   Terrell said airline reservation clerks were forced to process
by hand tickets normally printed and filed by computer.
</TEXT>
