<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Postal     05-23 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Postal,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Will Take Up California Case Involving Court Jurisdiction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether two U.S. Postal Service workers involved in California
traffic accidents while delivering mail must face criminal charges
in state court.
   The justices said they will hear a Reagan administration attempt
to transfer the prosecutions to federal court.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last year that state
courts have authority in the cases, which stem from accidents in
Santa Clara County.
   In one, Kathryn Isabella Mesa was accused of misdemeanor
manslaughter after her mail truck collided with and killed a
bicyclist. In the other, Shabbir A. Ebrahim was charged with
speeding and failing to yield after his mail truck collided with a
police car.
   Both defendants initially succeeded in having their cases
transferred to a federal court but the 9th Circuit court sent the
prosecutions back to state courts.
   The appeals court rejected arguments that the cases should be
handled in federal court to prevent possible bias against the mail
carriers.
   ``The attentuated federal interest in ensuring that their trial
be unbiased does not justify an invasion of the state's authority
to police its streets,'' the appeals court said. ``There is simply
no reason to believe that, on a systematic basis, postal workers
will not get a fair shake in state court.''
   The appeals court added that overburdened federal courts ``do
not need a new category of pesky cases turning solely on state
law.''
   In the appeal acted on today, Justice Department lawyers said
the appeals court ruling violates a federal law aimed at protecting
federal officials in the performance of their official duties.
   The appeals court decision would ``permit states ... to
undermine federal policies and programs,'' the appeal said, adding
that it ``presents a potential threat to federal (legal) supremacy
anywhere federal policies encounter local hostility.''
   The 9th Circuit court noted that the federal law providing for
removal of such cases to federal court was enacted in response to
New England's opposition to a trade embargo declared during the War
of 1812 between the United States and Great Britain.
   Federal customs officials were given authority then to board
vessels in order to collect duties, assuring they would avoid
prosecution in state courts for any alleged misconduct in the
performance of their duties.
   The appeals court said there is no claim by the two mail
carriers that their allegedly illegal conduct was justified by the
duties they were performing.
   ``There is no effort on the state's part to criminalize activity
important to federal interests, as there was during the War of
1812,'' the appeals court said.
   The case is Mesa vs. California, 87-1206.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
