<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1020EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Libel     05-23 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Libel,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Libel Award Against Virginia Newspaper Left Intact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a $100,000
libel award won against a Richmond, Va., newspaper and one of its
reporters by a high school teacher in that city.
   The justices, without comment, refused to hear the Richmond
Times-Dispatch's challenge of the judgment won by Vernelle
Lipscomb, a longtime English teacher in Richmond's public schools.
   Ms. Lipscomb, then head of the English department at Thomas
Jefferson High School, sued over an Aug. 16, 1981, article that ran
atop the newspaper's front page.
   In it, students and their parents were quoted as calling Ms.
Lipscomb ``disorganized, erratic, forgetful and unfair,'' and
charging that she ``demeans and humiliates students.''
   Ms. Lipscomb was quoted as saying she had been advised by her
lawyer not to talk about the complaints.
   A state court jury, finding that the article included libelous
statements made with ``actual malice,'' awarded Ms. Lipscomb $1
million in compensatory damages from the newspaper and Charles E.
Cox, the reporter who wrote the article.
   The jury also ordered Cox to pay $45,000 in punitive damages.
   The presiding judge later reduced the compensatory-damages award
to $100,000.
   The Virginia Supreme Court last Oct. 30 ruled that the trial
judge erred in considering Ms. Lipscomb a public official rather
than a private citizen for purposes of the libel suit.
   Public officials who sue for libel must prove the sued-over
statement was false and was made with actual malice _ either
knowledge of or reckless disregard of its falsity.
   Private citizens who sue for libel have an easier burden of
proof _ that the statement was false and was made negligently.
   The state Supreme Court, because it ruled that Ms. Lipscomb is
not a public figure, ordered the punitive-damages award against Cox
dropped.
   But the state court upheld the $100,000 judgment, ruling that
there was sufficient evidence of negligence.
   In the appeal acted on today, the newspaper's lawyers argued
that Ms. Lipscomb should have been considered a public official who
could not win her libel suit unless she proved actual malice.
   The case is Richmond Newspapers Inc. vs. Lipscomb, 87-1636.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1023EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Racketeering     05-23 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Racketeering,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Men Convicted as Members of Colombo Family Lose Appeals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six men convicted as members of the Colombo
crime family in New York City and one of their associates lost
Supreme Court appeals today.
   The court, without comment, left intact a ruling that the rights
of crime syndicate boss Carmine Persico and six others were not
violated in the government's racketeering prosecution.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the seven
convictions last October, rejecting numerous arguments. The
defendands said, for example, they were subjected to double
jeopardy and that the jurors should have been sequestered during an
eight-month trial.
   Persico was sentenced to 39 years in prison on racketeering
conspiracy charges, for conspiring to extort money from concrete
construction firms, for paying a gratuity to a federal prison
official and for offering a $20,000 bribe to a federal official to
transfer him to a different prison.
   Persico also has been convicted in a separate racketeering trial
with heads of other crime families and sentenced to 100 years in
prison.
   His eldest son, Alphonse Persico, and John DeRoss, described by
the government as an underworld captain, each were sentenced to 12
years in prison.
   Anthony Scarpati and Andrew Russo, each a reputed captain in the
Colombo family, were sentenced to 35 years and 14 years,
respectively.
   Dominic Cataldo, described as a soldier in the family, was
sentenced to 14 years. And Hugh McIntosh, a Colombo crime family
associate, received a 10-year sentence to run consecutively to a
nine-year term he already was serving on a bribery conviction.
   Prosecutors said the Colombo family was involved in a wide range
of criminal activity _ including loansharking, narcotics
trafficking, extortion, labor racketeering, theft and bribery.
   The cases are Russo vs. U.S., 87-1314; Carmine Persico vs. U.S.,
87-1323; Alphonse Persico, DeRoss and Scarpati vs. U.S., 87-1324;
Cataldo vs. U.S., 87-1553; and McIntosh vs. U.S., 87-6597.
</TEXT>
