<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GulfRdp     05-23 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Ships Sighted In Strait of Hormuz</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A large Iranian warship, two frigates and
a landing craft sailed in coastal waters in the Strait of Hormuz
today, shipping executives reported. Iran said it was conducting
naval manuevers in the area.
   The executives, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
vessels could not be identified as to type or number. But it
appeared that one, described as ``very large,'' could be a
destroyer.
   None of Iran's three destroyers has been active in the Persian
Gulf for more than a year.
   Iran announced Sunday that it was carrying out naval exercises
in the Persian Gulf and the Gulf of Oman, and that the 50 ships
participating included ``missile carrying destroyers, destroyers,
missile launching frigates and personnel carriers.''
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency reported today that
Iranian armed forces staged amphibious maneuvers in the Gulf of
Oman to demonstrate that the U.S. Navy has not crippled its naval
forces.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, said the maneuvers involved
``various land, sea and air operations'' and included electronic
jamming of radar and radio communications, aircraft detection,
paratroop drops and air raid interceptions.
   IRNA quoted an unidentified naval intelligence officer as saying
the exercises were aimed at ``disproving U.S. claims that it had
crippled half the hardware of the Iranian Navy'' in clashes on
April 18.
   The United States has not claimed to have cut Iran's navy by
half, but said its warships and combat jets sank or crippled six
Iranian vessels in the daylong fighting.
   These included the 1,540-ton, British-built frigate Sahand, a
fast attack patrol boat and two armed speedboats sunk, the frigate
Sabalan disabled and a speedboat probably sunk.
   Iran has said more than 40 of its men were killed and several
vessels, including the Sahand and Sabalan, were damaged by missiles
and bombs. The only U.S. casualties were two Marine Corps pilots
killed when their AH-1 Cobra helicopter gunship was lost, possibly
to Iranian fire.
   The United States has since broadened the role of U.S. warships
in the gulf, enabling them to intervene in attacks by Iranian
gunboats on neutral shipping under any non-belligerent flag and in
international waters.
   Jane's Fighting Ships, an authoritative naval reference, says
Iran's forces include three destroyers: the Damavand, a 3,360-ton
destroyer built for the Royal Navy in 1945 and two former American
warships launched in 1944, the 3,320-ton destroyers Babr and Palang.
   All of these vessels, sold to Iran in the late 1960s and early
1970s, were fitted with surface-to-surface and anti-aircraft
missiles and other weapons, but none have been reported operating
in at least the past year.
</TEXT>
