<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Annuities     05-23 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Annuities,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Says Fixed Annuities Fall Under Securities Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a case the insurance
industry was watching closely, today let stand a ruling that
millions of so-called fixed annuities are subject to federal
securities law.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that fixed
annuities paying fluctuating interest rates may be regulated the
same as stocks and bonds.
   Fixed annuities traditionally have been regarded as insurance
contracts because investors never risk their principal. Annuity
holders are assured of receiving the money contributed plus a
certain amount of interest in payments made at regular intervals.
   In 1985, 10 million individual annuities representing $24
billion in present and deferred annual payments were outstanding,
according to insurance industry sources.
   Some 33 million Americans were covered under private pension
plans funded by group annuity contracts that received $35 billion
in contributions during that year and paid out $10 billion in
benefits.
   There also existed seven million ``universal life'' policies _ a
form of annuities _ representing $564 billion of insurance in 1985.
   Holders of fixed annuities are assured of a minimum rate of
return on contributions. And most annuity plans provide for
``excess interest'' paid at the discretion of the annuity company.
   In 1967, the Supreme Court ruled that so-called variable
annuities, those that do not assure any minimum interest payments
on contributions, may be treated as securities regulated by federal
law.
   But a ruling by the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last April
15 marked the first time a fixed annuity was treated as a security.
   Beverly Otto sued the Variable Annuity Life Insurance Co.
(VALIC) in 1982, charging the Texas-based stock insurance company
with failing to disclose the method it used to calculate
excess-interest payments.
   Her ``class action'' lawsuit was filed in behalf of all Illinois
residents who invested in VALIC's fixed annuity program between
Oct. 17, 1975 and Aug. 2, 1982. The suit contended that the fixed
annuity is a ``security,'' and that VALIC had violated anti-fraud
provisions of federal securities law.
   A federal judge threw out the suit, ruling that the fixed
annuity is not a security.
   But the 7th Circuit court reversed that ruling, reinstating the
suit.
   The appeals court relied, in part, on a 1986 rule issued by the
Securities and Exchange Commission providing certain annuities with
a ``safe harbor'' exclusion from federal securities law.
   The appeals court said VALIC's fixed annuity did not qualify for
such treatment because its excess-interest rate on existing
deposits could be changed at any time at VALIC's discretion.
   In the appeal acted on today, VALIC said, ``The court's ruling
will unquestionably increase insurance companies' costs of doing
business, which will make annuities more expensive for consumers
and limit the availability of these policies.''
   The appeal was supported in ``friend-of-the-court'' briefs
submitted by the American Council of Life Insurance, the National
Association of Insurance Commissioners, the National Association of
Life Companies and the National Organization of Life and Health
Insurance Guaranty Associations.
   The case is VALIC vs. Otto, 87-600.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0090 </DOCNO>
