<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Marcos-Money     05-23 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos-Money,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos Says Swiss Supreme Court Violated Banking Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos
says the Swiss Supreme Court violated that country's laws by
allowing investigators to examine his bank accounts.
   The court announced Saturday that it had ordered Credit Suisse
to open the records to Swiss investigators, despite objections
raised by the bank.
   The Philippine government of President Corazon Aquino had asked
Switzerland for help in locating an estimated $1 billion Marcos
allegedly deposited in Swiss banks.
   According to a statement released Sunday night by Marcos
spokesman Gemmo Trinidad, Swiss authorities told the Aquino
government last year that, under Swiss law, criminal charges would
have to be filed against Marcos in the Philippines before his bank
accounts could be investigated.
   The Philippine Supreme Court recently certified that no criminal
charges have been filed against Marcos in any Philippine court,
Trinidad said.
   ``The news that the Swiss Supreme Count announced that it has
authorized a bank to allow investigators to examine bank account
records is definitely contrary to Swiss laws governing bank
deposits,'' Trinidad said.
   The court's ruling does not affect a freeze that has been placed
on Marcos' accounts, Swiss Justice Ministry spokesman Joerg Kistler
said in Lausanne.
   Marcos has lived here since he fled the Philippines in 1986.
</TEXT>
