<1ST_LINE>r p PM-MoynihanCandidacy     05-23 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Moynihan Candidacy,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moynihan Announces He Will Run For Third Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Daniel Patrick Moynihan today announced
his candidacy for a third term in the U.S. Senate, saying the
welfare of young Americans and fighting drugs will be among his
chief concerns.
   ``The issue of drugs is a tormenting one in this country now. I
have been, and will continue to be seized with the issue of drug
abuse,'' the New York Democrat said after announcing his candidacy
outside a Syracuse office building.
   He also said long-term health care for the elderly and
rebuilding the nation's transportation system would be among the
top concerns of a third term.
   The senator called it ``a personal tragedy and a national shame
that we require millions of seniors to become paupers before their
medical costs are covered.''
   Moynihan, 61, was scheduled to repeat his announcement this
afternoon at the Manhattan Center of Mathematics and Science and
attend a fund-raising rally in New York City.
   The senator cited his longstanding efforts in the battle against
drugs in response to the charge made by his likely Republican
opponent, Long Island attorney Robert McMillan, that Moynihan was
soft on drugs.
   Moynihan noted that as President John Kennedy's assistant for
urban affairs he conceived the strategy that broke the notorious
``French Connection'' of heroin traffic flowing into the United
States from Turkey via France.
   ``If anybody has that record, please come forward and tell us
about it,'' said Moynihan, who is co-chairman of the Senate's
Democratic Task Force on Substance Abuse. ``I saw the job through.
I mean to see this one through as well.''
   McMillan, 55, has not yet officially announced his candidacy but
has been lining up the support of GOP leaders behind a probable run.
   Moynihan defeated former state Assemblywoman Florence Sullivan
of Brooklyn by more than 1.5 million votes in 1982, the largest
margin in a U.S. Senate election in New York state history. He won
the seat in 1976 by defeating Republican incumbent James Buckley.
</TEXT>
