<HEAD>Court Will Consider Overturning Adoption of Indian Twins by
Mississippi Couple</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds; Subs graf 3, The children, to CORRECT location of reservation</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to consider
overturning the adoption by a Mississippi couple of Choctaw Indian
twins.
   The justices said they will hear arguments by tribal leaders
that state courts lacked the authority to grant the adoption.
   The children, a boy and a girl, were born Dec. 29, 1985, in
Philadelphia, Miss., near the Choctaw reservation. Their mother,
Jennie Bell, and their father, Windell Jefferson, are members of
the Mississippi Band of Choctaw Indians.
   The twins were put up for adoption by their parents, and were
adopted by Orrey and Vivian Holyfield.
   A Mississippi judge, noting that Ms. Bell had traveled off the
reservation to give birth, said the Choctaw tribe therefore ``never
obtained exclusive jurisdiction over the children.'' The
Mississippi Supreme Court upheld the adoption.
   Choctaw leaders said the ruling unlawfully violates the tribe's
sovereignty over its own legal affairs.
   They also said the decision could encourage illegal adoption of
Choctaw babies by making Mississippi ``a potential adoption Mecca
for, among others, black marketeers trading in Indian children.''
   The case is In the Matter of B.B. and G.B. vs. Holyfield, 87-980.
</TEXT>
