<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Weinberger,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weinberger Decorated With Rising Sun Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan today bestowed the Grand Cordon of the Order
of the Rising Sun on former U.S. Defense Secretary Casper
Weinberger for his contribution to Japan's defense, the Foreign
Ministry said.
   A ministry official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno praised Weinberger for his contribution
to strengthened security between Japan and the United States.
   The decoration is a high award usually given by Japan to foreign
heads of state. Uno presented the award to Weinberger.
   The official quoted Weinberger as saying he tried while in
office not to link U.S.-Japan defense issues with trade disputes
stemming from the restrictions of Japan's markets. Defense is much
more important than trade, the official reported Weinberger as
saying.
   Weinberger was defense secretary for seven years before retiring
last November. He arrived Saturday in Tokyo for a four-day visit at
the invitation of the Foreign Ministry.
   It was the second foreign award given to Weinberger in four
months. On Feb. 23 in London, Queen Elizabeth II declared
Weinberger an honorary knight.
   Before meeting with Uno, Weinberger met separately with Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita and the director general of defense
agency, Tsutomu Kawara, the Foreign Ministry official said. He said
details of the talks were not available.
   But Kyodo News Service reported that Weinberger gave Takeshita a
message from President Reagan saying Reagan was looking forward to
seeing the Japanese prime minister next month when the two leaders
will visit London.
   Takeshita told Weinberger he will try to discuss Japan's imports
of U.S. beef and oranges with Reagan, Kyodo said.
   Takeshita is to stop in London after attending the U.N. General
Assembly on June 1.
</TEXT>
