<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Escape, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0506,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prisoner Takes Guards Hostage, Escapes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with location of Days' relatives, spokesman's
comments about gun smuggling and belief that child is Mrs. Day's
daughter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHILLICOTHE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities continued their search
today for an armed escapee who took two guards hostage in a prison
Jeep before leaving them at a hotel and fleeing with his wife and a
child in a getaway car, officials said.
   Michael Day, 31, of Athens, escaped Sunday night from the
medium-security Ross Correctional Institution, said prison
spokesman Robert Prosser.
   ``At this point we have an all-points bulletin out throughout
Ohio and in surrounding states,'' Prosser said early today.
   Prosser said Day has relatives in the Cincinnati area and his
wife has relatives in Indiana.
   Day was serving a sentence of 18-to-55 years in the prison,
about 50 miles south of Columbus, for burglary and other felonies.
He was believed to be armed with a .25-caliber weapon, said Todd
Bennett of the State Highway Patrol.
   Prosser said Day took the guards hostage shortly after 7 p.m.
with a gun apparently smuggled into the prison, Prosser said.
   ``That's how he got through the prison security,'' Prosser said.
   A .38-caliber revolver that was kept in the Jeep was discarded
near the prison after the escape, Prosser said. A shotgun also kept
in the vehicle was recovered.
   Day took the guards, whose names were not released, to the
Holiday Inn near downtown, Prosser said.
   Day handcuffed one guard to the Jeep steering wheel and took the
other into a room registered in the name of Day's 27-year-old wife,
Sylvia Caraveo Day, said Prosser. Day told the guard to handcuff
himself to a towel bar.
   Prosser said that guard freed himself after Day and his wife
left the hotel. The guard went to the window and saw the two get
into a car.
   The couple, who Prosser said married while Day was in prison,
had a 9-year-old child with them, but officials weren't sure if the
child was related to the fugitives. Prosser said authorities were
acting on the assumption the child was Mrs. Day's daughter.
   Authorities found the getaway car behind a restaurant near U.S.
23 and U.S. 35 on the city's east side, Prosser said.
   The highway patrol said Mrs. Day had checked in at the hotel
Saturday.
   Day was convicted of attempted abduction, burglary, receiving
stolen property and carrying a concealed weapon, said Sandy Price,
a prison spokeswoman. He had been at the Ross prison since June and
had served at the Chillicothe Correctional Institute and Ohio State
Reformatory in Mansfield since April 1985.
</TEXT>
