<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1147EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-ChildPorn     05-23 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Child Porn,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Agrees to Consider Reinstating Massachusetts
Child-Pornography Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to consider
reinstating a Massachusetts child-pornography law a state court
said could be used to prosecute parents who photograph their naked,
infant children on the beach.
   The justices voted to review a Massachusetts Supreme Judicial
Court ruling, reached by a 4-3 vote, that the state law too broadly
interferes with a form of expression.
   The state court ruling overturned the criminal conviction in
Worcester County of Douglas Oakes for ``soliciting a child to pose
for pornographic purposes.''
   Prosecutors said Oakes in 1984 induced his 14-year-old
stepdaughter to pose for photographs while clothed only in bikini
underpants and with a scarf draped around her neck.
   Police were contacted after the girl's mother discovered the
photographs.
   When Oakes appealed, the state's highest court threw out his
conviction and dismissed the criminal indictment.
   The state court's 4-3 majority said photography is a form of
expression with which the state may interfere only when the
interference serves an important governmental purpose and is
narrowly drawn to serve that purpose.
   Looking at the state law involved, the state court said, ``The
overbreadth is substantial. It criminalizes conduct that virtually
every person would regard as lawful.''
   ``For example,'' the state court added, ``(the law) makes a
criminal of a parent who takes a frontal view picture of his or her
naked one-year-old running on a beach or romping in a wading pool.''
   The state court's three dissenters said taking photographs is
not a form of expression and the ``narrowly drawn'' test
traditionally used in free-speech cases should not have been used.
   In the appeal acted on today, Massachusetts Attorney General
James M. Shannon said a 1982 Supreme Court decision excluding child
pornography from free-speech protections ``established that states
are entitled to greater leeway in the regulation of pornographic
depictions of children than might be appropriate in other
contexts.''
   The case is Massachusetts vs. Oakes, 87-1651.
</TEXT>
