<HEAD>White House Spokesman Says `Kiss-and-Tell' Books Should Wait</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABILENE, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Kiss-and-tell'' books by former White
House staff members Donald Regan and Larry Speakes should not have
been published until President Reagan left office, White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater says.
   ``There are legitimate, historical reasons for writing a book
after serving in the White House,'' Fitzwater said Sunday in
Abilene, where he spoke at commencement at his old high school.
``But there is no reason to trash the president and your
colleagues.''
   Fitzwater said Reagan is very upset about what the authors wrote
about his wife.
   ``It's hardly fair to say we have astrology in the White
House,'' he said of the book by Regan, former White House chief of
staff. Regan wrote that Mrs. Reagan made decisions based on regular
conversations with an astrologer.
   ``It's an interesting story, but I don't think the public or the
media are taking it too seriously,'' Fitzwater said.
   Fitzwater refused to comment about Speakes, his former boss at
the White House. ``He's paid the price by losing his job and having
his reputation damaged. I see no reason to add to that,'' he added.
   Fitzwater said he might write a book about his time in the White
House _ but not while Reagan is in office. ``If I do, it will not
be like Regan's or Speakes','' he said.
   Fitzwater graduated from Abilene High School in 1960.
</TEXT>
