<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-LongtermCare Bjt   05-23 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Longterm Care, Bjt,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress' Sudden Hot Issue: Home Health Care for Everyone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public concern over the cost of longterm
illnesses has become the driving force behind Rep. Claude Pepper's
determined campaign to force Congress to vote on his plan to expand
Medicare _ and Medicare taxes _ to cover the expenses of home
health care.
   With polls claiming enormous support for a government program to
address those concerns, longterm-care proposals are proliferating
on Capitol Hill.
   ``This issue is one that voters will carry into the ballot
box,'' said Bruce Fried, executive director of the National Health
Care Campaign, a coalition of 100 organizations with affiliates in
35 states.
   ``Virtually every family stands at risk of needing longterm home
care at any time, and none of us are protected very well against
that eventuality,'' Fried said. ``It cuts across age lines, it cuts
across economic lines, it cuts across whether people view
themselves as liberals or conservatives. This is what the
population wants.''
   Pepper's five-year, $30 billion proposal would expand Medicare
to pay for various home care services for the chronically ill of
all ages. It would be financed by subjecting all income to the 1.45
percent Medicare payroll tax; currently only income up to $45,000
is taxed. No deductible or co-payment requirement would be imposed.
   Business interests are critical, partly because they would have
to match the additional Medicare tax payments. And budget watchdogs
predict the financing mechanism will prove inadequate, leading to
higher deficits or costly premiums and co-payments.
   The plan advanced by Pepper, D-Fla., is encountering a lot of
competition.
   Rep. Ralph Regula, R-Ohio, has proposed what is likely to be the
House Republican alternative: a $25 million, 30-month demonstration
program in five geographically diverse sites. Medicare would pay 80
percent of home-care costs after a $500 deductible is met.
   In the Senate, George Mitchell, D-Maine, chairman of the Finance
subcommittee on health, has offered a plan of his own. Medicare
would pay up to $2,000 for respite care; 80 percent of the cost of
home health care after a $500 deductible is met; and 70 percent of
nursing home costs after a two-year exclusionary period.
   And Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., plans to introduce an $18.6
billion Medicare expansion called ``Lifecare.'' The program would
pay for home care services and six months of nursing home care with
no co-payments or deductibles, and 35 percent of subsequent nursing
home care, minus the cost of room and board.
   But Pepper's bill is the only one heading for quick action,
probably early next month, for several reasons: He is chairman of
the powerful Rules Committee; at 87, the oldest House member, he is
revered by senior citizens across the country as their advocate and
he has campaigned for many of his colleagues.
   ``I'm trying to cooperate ... provided they don't make us wait
too long'' for a vote, Pepper said last week. ``We're getting
almost to the edge of our endurance.''
   Initially, Pepper planned to offer his bill as an amendment to a
catastrophic health plan designed to help the elderly deal with the
heavy cost of acute illness. But House leaders feared that tactic
would sink the whole bill.
   Pepper withheld his proposal in return for Speaker Jim Wright's
promise of a House floor vote on it. Ordinarily, the bill would
have gone to the Ways and Means Committee, but Pepper sped the bill
out of his Rules Committee last November and has been waiting ever
since.
   Ways and Means Chairman Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., doen't hide
his distaste for Pepper's bill. He contends it is too expensive and
technically flawed and should go through his committee for review.
   There is little doubt, given the political climate, that
Pepper's bill will win House passage. In the Senate, Mitchell said,
``We'll do the best we can as fast as we can. Maybe it'll be this
year, maybe it'll be next year. We don't have to have a deadline.''
   Those who work closely with Pepper say it is a mistake to count
him out this year.
   Kathy Gardner, staff director of a health subcommittee chaired
by Pepper, noted that half the members of the Senate Finance
Committee are up for re-election and longterm care is a staple on
the campaign trail this year. She said a similar atmosphere existed
two years ago when Pepper pushed through a bill outlawing mandatory
retirement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
