<DOCNO> AP880523-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scientists-ArmsControl     05-23 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scientists-Arms Control,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Soviet Scientists Discuss Arms Issues Out of Limelight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Arms Treaty Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the superpowers strive to put into force
the treaty banning medium-range missiles, senior U.S. and Soviet
scientists have been getting together for confidential talks to
discuss future arms control issues and ways to avoid nuclear war.
   Thetalks, taking place through two committees operating under
the aegis of the National Academy of Sciences, have been described
by American participants as surprisingly frank and productive.
   One group, the Committee on International Security and Arms
Control, known as CISAC, recently completed a three-day closed-door
meeting with leading Soviet academicians headed by Roald Sagdeyev,
director of Moscow's Space Research Institute.
   Chairing the 17-member U.S. panel is Wolfgang K.H. Panofsky,
former director of Stanford University's Linear Accelerator Center.
   The latest meeting _ the 12th in a series of confidential
sessions that CISAC has held with Soviet counterparts since 1981 _
took place May 4-6 at a conference center in Queenstown, Md., about
60 miles east of Washington.
   The tone of the meeting was ``very constructive and very
friendly,'' said John D. Steinbruner, a committee member and
director of foreign policy studies at the Brookings Institution, a
liberal Washington think tank. ``It's a very pragmatic, congenial
working atmosphere.''
   ``We discussed strategic force reduction, issues of verification
and conventional force questions that have to do with the mainline
items of arms control,'' he said. ``Our ground rules are that we do
not, however, discuss directly the negotiations that are under
way.''
   Steinbruner said the main verification issue that came under
discussion dealt with cruise missiles, which pose special problems
because they are relatively small and easily concealed.
   He said that over the past seven years, ``there's no question
but that we have seen in the course of these meetings very
extensive development in the thinking of people on the Soviet side
who are in touch with high-level officials in the leadership. ...
It's pretty encouraging.''
   Another CISAC member, Spurgeon M. Keeny Jr., president of the
Washington-based Arms Control Association, said ``one not only
gains insight into Soviet positions but also informs influential
Soviet scientists about U.S. thinking on these issues.''
   Other Americans currently serving on the committee include
Joshua Lederberg, president of Rockefeller University; Charles H.
Townes, a physics professor at the University of California,
Berkeley, and former White House science adviser Jerome B. Wiesner,
a professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
   A second group operating under the sponsorship of the National
Academy of Sciences is the Committee on Contributions of Behavioral
and Social Science to the Prevention of Nuclear War.
   This 20-member panel, formed in 1985, has been looking beyond
the strategic and technical aspects of nuclear war to consider
questions such as how superpower leaders interpret each other's
actions and under what conditions they might resort to nuclear
weapons.
   William K. Estes, co-chairman of the committee and a psychology
professor at Harvard University, said the group is starting to
develop a joint U.S.-Soviet project involving public opinion
research in the two countries.
   He said that during two working trips to the Soviet Union last
year, he was impressed by the change of mood under Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``Among academicians, which is my immediate concern, it's just a
tremendous uplift,'' Estes said. ``For some _ for example,
sociologists whose field is public opinion research _ just a total
liberation. They can come out of the bushes for the first time in
their memories.''
   Panel co-chairman Herbert A. Simon, a Nobel laureate in
economics at Carnegie-Mellon University, said he had been ``rather
pleasurably surprised'' with the rapid pace at which the group has
been able to develop contacts with Soviet social scientists.
   Simon said he too was encouraged by the Soviet leadership's
increasing sensitivity to sounding out and analyzing public
attitudes on U.S.-Soviet relations and arms control.
   ``The whole idea behind this committee is that a sane and
informed world _ a world in which people understand better how they
themselves and other people behave _ has a chance of being a little
better world than a world in which we fly by the seat of our
pants,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
