<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WALLED LAKE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The clerk at the Wash Basin Laundromat
thought she smelled a rat.
   A couple of vans cruised by the business just before closing
time Saturday night, stopped and unloaded people wearing dog
muzzles, pig snouts and anteater noses.
   They walked back and forth out front.
   The clerk called the cops.
   When officers questioned the people, everything became as clear
as the noses on their faces, police said.
   It seems that it was the annual St. Matthew Lutheran Church
adult spring rally and scavenger hunt. This year, the participants
wore disguises as they looked for oddball items.
   There were no arrests.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CANNON BEACH, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Castles and alligators rose up out of
the sands as sculptors, artists and other would-be van Goghs
descended upon this beach community for the 23rd annual Sand Castle
Day.
   The event showcased the talents of 115 teams whose works of art
were viewed by an estimated 30,000 people.
   Under sunny weather Saturday, the beach artists hauled water,
packed sand and sculpted their creations.
   Jon Taylor and his crew of six from Washington state won the
``Best Castle'' award.
   Their 7-feet high work was ornately detailed with turrets and
towers, etched stonework, stairs that led to doors, a moat and
beyond the moat a forest _ all made of sand.
   As people gathered behind the roped-off area to ooh and aah the
work, one father assured his child, ``It's a real castle.''
   ``Gladi-gators,'' sculpted by a Seattle team of landscape
artists and urban planners won the ``Art in Sand'' award.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Hambrick knows a good idea when he has
one, and so does his employer, IBM.
   Hambrick, of Ladera Heights, won a $150,000 employee suggestion
award for an idea that will shave weeks off the time needed for
International Business Machines Corp. to prepare a semi-annual
report on minority employees.
   The bonus is IBM's highest Suggestion Plan award, IBM spokesman
Justin Fishbein said last week.
   ``I feel absolutely great,'' said Hambrick, 44, who works in the
Los Angeles office. ``I intend to make it grow as fast as I can.''
   ``We may go on a cruise,'' said Hambrick, who is married and has
three children.
   Hambrick also won a $150 IBM award in 1973.
</TEXT>
