<HEAD>New Party Chief in Bucharest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hungary, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Constantin Radu, until recently a deputy
premier, has been named Communist Party chief and mayor of
Bucharest, it was reported Monday.
   Constantin Olteanu, the former defense minister who had headed
the Bucharest party ``was given other assignments on a party
line,'' the state news agency Agerpres said without elaboration.
   As a deputy premier, Radu was responsible for construction
projects and investment. His new appointment to the Bucharest job
gives him responsibility for the giant construction projects
underway in the capital and due for completion by 1990.
   The historic heart of Bucharest has been altered radically since
1985, when work started on a giant new Communist Party headquarters
and a long boulevard lined with new apartments for the party elite.
   Hundreds of old, private homes have been pulled down to make way
for the project, and 28 churches or synagogues have been destroyed
or moved.
