<2ND_LINE>AM-Ga Gubernatorial,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miller Makes It Official: He's Running For Governor in 1990</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gov. Zell Miller said Monday he will seek the
Democratic nomination for governor in 1990.
   ``That's a long time off. Lots can happen between now and then,
but that is my intention,'' said Miller, the first candidate to
make his intentions known.
   The 56-year-old former history professor and state legislator is
serving an unprecedented fourth term as Georgia's second-highest
official. Democratic Gov. Joe Frank Harris is barred by the state
constitution from seeking a third four-year term.
   Miller said the early announcement makes his actions as
lieutenant governor subject to close scrutiny for any political
implications but gives him ``the comfort of conscience, the peace
of mind that goes with being open and candid.''
   Among the others known to be considering bids for governor are
Secretary of State Max Cleland, House Majority Leader Larry Walker
of Perry, state Rep. Lauren ``Bubba'' McDonald and Sen. Roy Barnes,
all Democrats.
   Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young, a Democrat, also has indicated he
may enter the race.
