<DOCNO> AP880523-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Summit-Gulf     05-23 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Gulf,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan To Ask Gorbachev Support For Ban On Arms Sales To Iran,
Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, currying
favor with Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, is likely to balk if
President Reagan asks him to back a U.N. Security Council
resolution barring arms sales to Iran and Iraq, U.S. officials say.
   The Persian Gulf war is expected to be on the agenda when Reagan
and Gorbachev meet May 29-June 2 in Moscow.
   The Soviets went along with a U.S.-sponsored Security Council
resolution in July 1987 urging Iran and Iraq to end the war, which
began in September 1980. The Soviets and the Chinese, however, have
refused to support a followup resolution to stop the flow of arms
to the belligerents.
   ``The chances of passing that resolution peaked about February
or early March,'' said a State Department official, who spoke on
condition he not be identified.
   Because Khomeini wants to continue the war, and Iraqi leader
Saddam Hussein wants to end it, the second resolution ``would
amount to a de facto embargo on Iran,'' the official said.
   Also, Gorbachev does not want to offend Khomeini, particularly
as Soviet troops leave Afghanistan and the United States and Iran
remain at loggerheads in the Persian Gulf, the experts say.
   The Soviets and the Chinese are key because they are permanent
members of the Security Council and could veto any resolution.
   The Chinese, who supply Iran with close to half of its weapons,
eased their opposition in February, increasing pressure on the
Soviets, who are the major arms supplier to Iraq.
   But pressure on Moscow fell after the U.S.-Iranian naval battle
on April 18, in which American ships killed 44 Iranians and knocked
out half the opposing navy by disabling two Iranian frigates and
sinking or damaging four speed boats.
   ``The U.S. action in the gulf pushed the Chinese and the
Russians away from backing the resolution,'' said the State
Department source. ``The Russians had always been reluctant on the
second resolution, but this gave them something to hang their hat
on.''
   Khomeini rode to power in 1979 on a wave of indignation against
Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, a long-time U.S. ally, but the
ayatollah paired his vehement condemnation of the United States,
``the Great Satan,'' with anti-Soviet rhetoric that was nearly as
strong.
   Soviet-Iranian relations improved somewhat following the
disclosure in November 1986 that the Reagan administration secretly
had sold arms to the Khomeini regime.
   And ties between Tehran and Moscow further improved after the
U.S. decision last year to offer naval protection to 11 reflagged
tankers belonging to Kuwait, a non-belligerent ally of Iraq in the
war.
   Lately, however, ``there has been nothing really terribly new''
in Soviet-Iranian ties, said Shireen Hunter, an expert on Iran at
the Center for Strategic and International Studies in Washington.
   Gorbachev faces a ticklish situation as he fulfills his promise
to withdraw an estimated 115,000 Soviet troops out of Afghanistan,
which not only borders Iran, but shares much of its cultural,
ethnic and linguistic heritage.
   Khomeini's cooperation is vital in repatriating 2.5 million
Afghans who fled to Iran following the Soviet invasion in 1979. An
additional 3.5 million Afghan refugees in Pakistan pose a similar
problem.
   Iranian cooperation also would assist the Soviets in assuring
``that a neutral state is established in Afghanistan,'' said
Hunter. ``The Russians do not want a pro-Western government in
Afghanistan.''
   Additionally, Khomeini has been backing several groups of
anti-Soviet Afghan guerrillas who share his fundamentalist Shiite
Moslem faith.
   As the Red Army pulls back from forward positions in
Afghanistan, ``the Iranians have the capability to make life
difficult for the Soviets, at least in the outlying areas,'' said
the State Department source.
   In at least one instance, the mujahedden guerrillas and the
Soviets appear to have worked out a modus vivendi.
   ``The mujahedeen have been distributing leaflets in the area of
Ghazni (in eastern Afghanistan) saying they will allow the Soviets
to leave peacefully if the Soviets do not loot civilian houses as
they depart,'' said the source, citing a diplomatic cable from
Kabul. Similar arrangements may exist elsewhere in Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
