<DOCNO> AP880523-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1314EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czech-Drugs     05-23 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czech-Drugs,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Drug Treatment Center Scrapped After Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia's first in-patient
drug abuse treatment center has been scrapped following protests
from residents, one of whom said addicts should be shot ``like
vermin,'' a weekly newspaper reported.
   The treatment center was to have been housed in a small castle
in Tuchomerice, north of Prague, according to the popular weekly,
Vlasta.
   Opposition grew rapidly once word of the plans spread in a TV
broadcast before authorities informed residents, Vlasta said.
   ``The TV statement was premature, ill-considered and resulted in
hysteria,'' said Jan Klima, a Prague health official. ``Complaints
poured in, then came a signature campaign of those protesting the
plan _ simply, enormous pressure.''
   He said the castle instead will be a center for the elderly, he
said.
   Vlasta quoted unidentified doctors as complaining that drug
addicts now can be treated only in a psychiatric ward in a Prague
suburb or at a center for alcoholics.
   Vlasta first reported on drug addicts last fall and said its
stories on the Tuchomerice case brought ``an unprecedented
response'' from readers. Some letters were sympathetic, but others
used strong language.
   ``I would send them to forced labor or shoot them like vermin,''
wrote one unidentified reader.
   Only recently has drug abuse been discussed in the state-run
media. In 1986, according to the latest statistics, 703 people were
prosecuted on drugs-related charges, Vlasta said. It gave no
figures for Slovakia.
</TEXT>
