<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     05-23 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Attack on Afghan Capital Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas rocketed Afghanistan's capital on
Monday, killing one woman, and the Marxist government again
protested Pakistani support of the Moslem insurgents, Tass reported
   A dispatch from the official Soviet news agency said the
guerrillas fired six rockets into Kabul and hit a shoe factory. In
addition to the one woman killed, another was wounded, Tass said.
   Afghanistan's Foreign Ministry gave United Nations monitors in
Kabul a note demanding an investigation into the aid given to the
guerrillas from Pakistan.
   It was the third time the Afghanistan government has protested
to the United Nations that Pakistan is violating the April 14
international agreement providing for withdrawal of Soviet forces.
   The previous note was given to Pakistan on Thursday, Tass said.
   The April 14 agreement, signed in Geneva, pledges that Pakistan
not interfere in Afghanistan's internal affairs. Pakistan is home
to Afghan guerrillas in bases on its territory, and they receive
their weapons from the United States.
   A Soviet-inspired revolution in April 1978 brought a Marxist
leadership to power in Afghanistan. The Kremlin sent troops and
tanks in December 1979 to help the allied Kabul government fight
widespread rebellion.
   The Kremlin is to withdraw its troops, estimated to number
115,000, within nine months under the Geneva accord. The first
troops left Afghanistan on May 15.
</TEXT>
