<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0997</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Walters likens ``20-20'' co-anchor Hugh
Downs to Superman's alter ego, the quiet but dedicated Clark Kent.
   Walters, in town to give a speech to the newly formed Forum
social club, recalled Sunday night that Downs went underwater in a
shark cage to view a great white shark for a television segment.
   ``I thought he was crazy, ...'' she said. ``Hugh and I have
worked for years together and there's this sort of Clark Kent thing
about him.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two ``masters of modern architecture,'' Oscar
Niemeyer of Brazil and Gordon Bunshaft of the United States, have
been named 1988 co-winners of the Pritzker Architecture Prize.
   ``We are delighted that the jury has used the occasion of the
10th anniversary of the prize to honor not one, but two masters of
modern architecture,'' said Jay Pritzker, president of the
sponsoring Hyatt Foundation.
   The $100,000 prizes were established by the Pritzker family of
Chicago in 1979 to honor a creative endeavor not included in the
Nobel Prizes.
   The foundation said in a release that Niemeyer, 80, and
Bunshaft, 79, will share the grant equally.
   Niemeyer, a native of Rio de Janiero, is perhaps best known for
his designs for most of the public buildings in Brasilia, the
Brazilian capital built from scratch in a remote area.
   Niemeyer also designed the United Nations headquarters in New
York City in collaboration with the late French architect Le
Courbusier.
   Bunshaft became famous in the 1950s for his skyscrapers, many in
New York City.
   His 24-story Lever House, completed in 1953, is the newest
building to be granted landmark status by the New York Landmarks
Conservancy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lia Belli, the wife of famed lawyer Melvin
Belli, faces a $75,000 fine for alleged campaign financing
violations in her unsuccessful 1984 state Senate campaign, a
newspaper reported Monday.
   The San Francisco Chronicle reported that its sources said Mrs.
Belli has agreed to pay the fine as part of a deal with the Fair
Political Practices Commission.
   Sources said the fine concerns at least $60,000 in hidden
campaign contributions from a family member.
   Mrs. Belli and her husband both declined to respond to several
requests for interviews. An attorney who represents her, Richard
Brown, said, ``It's just not in anyone's interest to discuss this.''
   Mrs. Belli raised $882,505 for the campaign, most of it in loans
from the family, according to the Chronicle. She was defeated by
Milton Marks by a 2-1 margin.
   It is not illegal for candidates to lend themselves money to
finance their campaigns, but the money must be fully disclosed on
state reports.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth II is getting a loaner from
Australia for her press office.
   Buckingham Palace announced Monday the appointment of Australian
diplomat Geoffrey Crawford as the queen's assistant press secretary.
   Crawford, 37, will be on loan from the Australian Department of
Foreign Affairs and Trade, which he joined in 1974.
   His appointment revives longstanding links between the
Buckingham Palace press office and the Commonwealth, the 48-nation
association of Britain and its former colonies.
   When Crawford takes up his duties in June, he will be the ninth
assistant press secretary from the Commonwealth. The last, Canadian
Vic Chapman, resigned in October, two months before he died of
cancer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tyka Nelson, the sister of Rock star Prince,
is into blue for her recording debut rather than the color purple
associated with her famous brother.
   Her album, ``Royal Blue,'' will be released next week.
   The name of Nelson's album comes from an included song title and
reflects the tone of the record, she told the Star Tribune of
Minneapolis in an interview published Monday.
   ``I'd call it a different kind of blues. That's the mood I was
in,'' said Nelson, 28, who lives in a suburb near where she grew up
in Minneapolis.
   ``The album is basically about love relationships between a man
and a woman. I'm royal blue because I can't find him,'' she said.
   Nelson's material, mostly adult-contemporary or easy-listening,
is far removed from Prince and the so-called Minneapolis sound.
Hers is a mature, romantic sound aimed at 25- to 45-year-olds.
   Prince, who lives in the Minneapolis suburb of Chanhassen where
he has a recording studio, is best known for his 1984 blockbuster,
``Purple Rain,'' which was the soundtrack for his movie of the same
name.
   On her relationship to her brother, Nelson told the Star
Tribune: ``The funniest thing is people say, `How does it feel to
be Prince's sister?' They don't actually realize what they're
saying. I've been Prince's sister ever since I got here on Earth.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Keith Carradine chose to stay away from
strictly leading-man roles and looked for character parts that
would prove he was talented as well as versatile.
   ``I come from a family of character actors,'' said Carradine,
whose show business family includes father John Carradine and
brothers David and Robert. ``It is a business, and the Hollywood
career strategy is to cater to the widest possible range.
   ``My career consists of art films and television. I've gone into
TV work to subsidize my features career. Peculiar, isn't it? But
I've managed to choose TV that's quality. Just now, in the next few
years, it is starting to pay off,'' Carradine said in an interview
published last week.
   Carradine's credits include ``Southern Comfort,'' ``The Long
Riders,'' ``Pretty Baby'' and the just-released ``The Moderns.''
   ``I could easily have taken the leading-man route. But I
consciously chose character roles. This is a town where you have to
prove what you can do,'' he said.
   ``I'd be bored being a personality actor.''
</TEXT>
