<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TinyClass     05-23 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tiny Class,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small High School Graduating Class Gets Visit from Governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AGATE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It took all of 21 seconds to hand out
diplomas to Agate High School's graduating class and for Gov. Roy
Romer to shake hands with the graduates.
   Richard Padilla was class valedictorian, and Penny Robbins was
the salutatorian. They were also next-to-last and last in their
class.
   Romer gave the commencement address Sunday at the high school
about 70 miles east of Denver because he wanted to show that big is
not better than small.
   ``When you're from a small town, you feel like Tail-End
Charlie,'' said Romer, whose hometown of Holly isn't much bigger
than Agate, population 100. ``I want to reverse that.''
   The 59-year-old chief executive told the two graduates and about
100 of their neighbors and relatives: ``You have a gift being from
Agate. It's a gift of a community small enough to know each other,
to share your hopes and fears and dreams. There's something
absolutely good about that.''
   ``Maybe when you're in the work world, you will be able to say,
`Let me tell you how we did it in Agate,''' Romer said. ``Don't
laugh at that phrase. There's a lot of wisdom that comes from rural
communities.''
   After the 48-minute ceremony, Robbins and Padilla walked
hand-in-hand down the center aisle and threw their mortarboard caps
into the air.
   Padilla plans to be a mechanic, and Robbins plans to study
business management this fall at Morgan Community College in Fort
Morgan.
</TEXT>
