<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TempleVandalized     05-23 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Temple Vandalized,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latest Temple Attack Brings Call for Prison Terms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals stenciled swastikas and scrawled an
anti-Semitic slogan on a synagogue, prompting the Anti-Defamation
League of B'nai B'rith to demand prison terms for such offenses and
post a $1,000 reward for information.
   ``I'd like to see the steel doors slam shut behind someone this
time,'' said Arthur Teitelbaum, ADL southern area director. ``Maybe
that's what is needed to put a stop to this.''
   The three swastikas and the words ``Die Jew'' were painted on
the Bet Breira synagogue in suburban Kendall over the weekend,
police said.
   About 1{ miles away at Killian High School, vandals also
stenciled five swastikas, along with ``Neo-Nazi Rules'' and
``Hitler Lives,'' police said.
   Police had no suspects, Metro-Dade police spokesman James Wright
said Monday.
   Desecration of a house of worship is punishable by up to five
years in prison and a $5,000 fine.
   Teen-agers charged with throwing rocks and scrawling a swastika
at a synagogue Feb. 26 recently were sentenced to 200 hours of
community service, and had to pay for $14,800 in damage.
   Reported anti-Semitic incidents have nearly doubled in Florida
this year, with 44 reported so far compared to 64 in all of 1987,
Teitelbaum. Nationwide there were 694 incidents in 1987, Teitelbaum.
   The weekend attack at the synagogue was particularly unsettling
because it appeared well-planned, Teitelbaum said Sunday.
   ``I do feel the attack was premeditated because of the
stencils,'' he said. ``Fundamentally, it is the virus of bigotry
that is expressed in these acts. What is really worrisome is that a
new generation of persons has been infected.''
   ``There is a great deal of prejudice and hatred in Dade County,
and this act shows that more integration between Anglos, blacks,
Hispanics, Jews and gentiles needs to take place,'' said Barry
Tabachnikoff, rabbi at the 450-member Bet Breira Congregation. ``We
still have a lot of work to do, especially in the religious
community.''
</TEXT>
