<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BuckledSign     05-23 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Buckled Sign,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In A Clinch, Hollywood Sign Sure To Attract Attention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood's famous sign had been abbreviated
and obliterated, but never belted or buckled _ until Monday.
   It's a cinch that's sure to click with a lot of drivers,
promoters hope.
   Several celebrities and safety representatives teamed up Monday
to strap what they called the world's largest seat belt around the
landmark Hollywood sign.
   ``Knot's Landing'' star Michele Lee, chairwoman of the Committee
for Safety Belt Awareness for the Entertainment Industries Council,
joined National Highway Traffic Safety Administrator Diane Steed
and members of the American Coalition for Traffic Safety for the
ceremonial buckling.
   The safety belt, measuring 400 feet long and 10 feet wide, was
fastened with a symbolic click around the 55-foot high letters to
kick off Buckle Up America! Week.
   ``Buckling up and drunk driving have long been priority issues
for myself and for the Entertainment Industries Council,'' Miss Lee
said. ``We welcome this opportunity to show America that Hollywood
cares about saving lives and that the entertainment community is
committed to these two vital issues.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1419EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Party Bjt   05-23 0941</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Party, Bjt,0968</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Meeting Shaping Up as Face-off on Reform Pace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Next month's Communist Party conference is shaping
up to be a face-off between supporters of radical change and
advocates of just ``a little polishing up'' of the old Soviet
system, party activists reported Monday.
   Despite efforts by Mikhail S. Gorbachev to draw only backers of
his policy of ``perestroika,'' or wholesale rebuilding of Soviet
society, some who fear reform is being introduced too quickly may
be selected as delegates to the June 28 conference.
   A closed-door meeting of the party Central Committee devoted to
preparations for next month's conference selected Gorbachev to
deliver the key address to the gathering, which will pass judgment
on his reform program, the Tass news agency reported.
   But senior advisers on the economy and social trends made clear
at a news conference that conflicting viewpoints on the pace of
reform are becoming more apparent.
   It has not even been decided whether the party gathering _ the
first of its kind since 1941 _ will be televised, according to
delegate Sergei P. Zalygin, editor of the journal Novy Mir (New
World).
   Gorbachev addressed the plenary session of the Central Committee
before and after a debate among the more than 300 members, Tass
said. No details of his or other speeches were released.
   Kremlin No. 2 Yegor K. Ligachev told a foreign policy meeting
later in the day that the plenum had ``a very interesting and
lively debate'' over the proposals to be presented at the
conference.
   Ligachev has made clear in previous speeches that he favors a
more moderate pace of reform.
   The theses put together by the ruling 13-man Politburo make ``a
number of important suggestions and proposals relative to the
implementation of perestroika, glasnost, democratization and the
implementation of a healthy political atmosphere,'' Ligachev said.
   He gave no details, but said the proposals will be published
before the conference.
   Four of the nation's most respected advisers on perestroika told
reporters the conference is heightening differences among
policy-makers.
   Tatiana Zaslavskaya, the nation's leading sociologist and a
staunch reform advocate, said if perestroika is to succeed, ``we
will have to fight and struggle for it to see that we meet these
goals.''
   She indicated there are two groups which want perestroika
carried out differently. Asked who heads the factions, Ms.
Zaslavskaya said Gorbachev is obviously the figurehead for the
radical-reform branch, but she said she did not know any leading
``personalities at the head of the other movement.''
   Ligachev is reputed to champion more conservative views on the
Politburo, and last month was reported to have had a showdown with
Gorbachev following publication of a defense of Stalinism in the
party newspaper Sovietskaya Rossiya. But he has made several
high-profile appearances, including his parliamentary address
Monday, indicating he and Gorbachev are putting out a unified front
leading up to the important conference.
   In an interview with The Washington Post that was published
Sunday, Gorbachev labeled as ``Western media'' creations those
accounts that he and Legachev are locked in a struggle for power,
although he acknowledged that ``heated debate'' has developed over
perestroika within the nation.
   Party conferences, which consider major changes in direction in
social and economic development, can be called between party
congresses, which take place every five years. They were held
frequently until World War II.
   Ms. Zaslavskaya appeared to criticize the party's monopoly on
power when asked about the system for selecting the 5,000 delegates
to the conference.
   ``The fact that the party delegates are selected by the party
machinery, by the party committees, effects the procedure, and not
in every case can it be called a democratic effect,'' she said.
   It was not clear whether she was advocating extension of the
delegate selection into non-party groups or criticizing some of the
officials chosen.
   Gorbachev's reforms curry much less favor in rural regions and
industrial zones outside the capital, where many entrenched party
bureaucrats fear their jobs and privileges hang in the balance. In
those areas, party conference delegates are likely to oppose
radical change.
   On May 7, Gorbachev appealed for selection of those who would
support his approach to reform.
   ``There must be no more quotas, as were the case in the past,
specifying how many factory workers and farmers and how many women
are to be elected, among others,'' Gorbachev told a gathering of
media representatives and ideologists. ``The principal political
directive is to elect active supporters of perestroika to go to the
conference.''
   Little is known about the proposals to be put before the party
conference next month, although several officials have said the
delegates will consider limiting the tenure of the general
secretary.
   There has also been speculation that Gorbachev might take the
opportunity to replace as much as 25 percent of the Central
Committee, ousting those who have not shown sufficient dedication
to his reform programs.
   But Fyodor M. Burlatsky, a prominent political scientist and
writer, told the news conference that ``as far as I know there
would not be additional elections during this party conference.''
   Burlatsky, like Zaslavskaya and the other two officials who
appeared at the news conference, is in the running to attend the
party conference, although the selection procedures have not been
completed.
   ``From my point of view the most important struggle is between
those who want deep changes and others who want a little polishing
up,'' Burlatsky said. ``The struggle is continuing in these areas.''
   Economist Leonid I. Abalkin restated Gorbachev's philosophy that
economic change and broader democracy must go hand in hand.
   ``One without the other is unthinkable,'' Abalkin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1436EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hungary Bjt   05-23 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary, Bjt,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Changes Open Way for Reform in Hungary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The reformers who now control the
Communist Party embarked Monday on a program of sweeping changes
they hope will rescue the faltering economy.
   Hungary's turn from old leadership to a new generation of highly
trained managers, intellectuals and economic theorists may be the
most dramatic change of course in Eastern Europe since Alexander
Dubcek's liberal ``Prague Spring'' of 1968 in Czechoslovakia.
   The most important difference is that Moscow now supports
reform, under Mikhail S. Gorbachev's ``perestroika'' plan, and the
Warsaw Pact invasion that drove Dubcek out is not likely to be
repeated.
   An outline of Hungarian reform plans was revealed Sunday along
with major changes in party leadership that replaced party leader
Janos Kadar and many of his aging supporters.
   Kadar, leader for nearly 32 years, was replaced by the
reform-minded premier, Karoly Grosz, and top decision-making posts
went to advocates of change.
   Delegates to the three-day party congress that ended Sunday
dropped Kadar, who will be 76 on May 26, from the ruling Politburo
but elected him party president, a new post expected to be largely
ceremonial.
   Some party officials said Kadar might seek to wield a
conservative influence from his new position, but the strength of
reformers in the new leadership indicate they will be able to set
policy.
   Grosz, 57, will continue as premier until the next session of
Parliament, when a replacement might be chosen.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said
the United States wishes Grosz well and ``we expect our good
relationship with Hungary will continue to improve.''
   The new party policy statement approved Sunday gives few
specifics, but calls for a greater public voice in economic and
political affairs. It also contemplates a much larger role for
private enterprise to revive the stagnant economy.
   ``The economy must be left alone to make its own decisions,''
Sandor Demjan, president of the Hungarian Credit Bank,'' said
Monday. ``The dullness of Hungarian political life in recent years
has clouded the economic sphere.'' Kadar's government pioneered
economic reforms, which brought relative prosperity from the late
1960s through the 1970s.
   Recent economic setbacks, however, have burdened Hungary with
Eastern Europe's highest per capita foreign debt. It now stands $18
billion.
   Inflation is running at more than 18 percent annually and
austerity measures have been imposed.
   In surprisingly frank debate, delegates to the congress assailed
Kadar and the Communist Party for not averting the economic crisis.
   Budapest party members, who make up almost one quarter of
Hungary's 800,000 Communists, were among the most critical. They
demanded new faces, new policies and a move toward political
pluralism.
   Reformers argued that economic change would fail without similar
action in the political field.
   While the policy document made clear the party's leading role
was not being challenged, it referred frequently to the need for
``socialist pluralism'' in which opposing views would be allowed.
   It outlined the advantages of more foreign investment and joint
ventures with foreign companies. Among political reforms endorsed
were limited terms of office for party officials and laws
guaranteeing freedom of association and other civil rights.
   ``The right of voluntary organization, assembly, association,
freedom of conscience and religion ... and guarantees for the
protection of individual and collective rights must be regulated by
law,'' it said.
   A leading proponent of independent interest groups, Imre
Pozsgay, was among those elected to the ruling Politburo. The
pollicy statement acknowledged his recent comments by saying local
referendums should be held on issues of importance to Hungarians.
   Many interest groups have been formed recently that do not seek
official approval and range in nature from sports groups to an
independent labor union.
   Another notable appointment to the Politburo was Reszo Nyers,
the economist who pioneered reform in the late 1960s. He was ousted
from the party's ruling body in in 1973 for advocating further
changes.
   Thirty-one members of the Central Committee, nearly one-third of
the total, were replaced by young intellectuals and workers. Few
came from the party bureaucracy.
   Six members of the Politburo are new, including two women, and
the membership was reduced from 13 to 11. Its first meeting was
scheduled for Tuesday.
</TEXT>
