<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Oxford Bjt   05-23 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oxford, Bjt,0763</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oxford Blues: Prestigious Posts Vacant Due to Money Shortage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oxford University said Monday it is leaving two of
the world's most prestigious academic posts vacant indefinitely,
citing a financial crisis.
   The regius chairs in Greek and modern history become vacant in
fall 1989 and won't be filled for at least a year, said Anne
Lonsdale, an Oxford spokeswoman.
   She said the regius chairs _ so named because they were created
by royal command _ could remain frozen beyond 1990, depending on
faculty priorities.
   The decision heightens longstanding concern over the ancient
university's future as a citadel of scholarship and scientific
research.
   ``There is a question mark over our status as a world-class
university,'' Sir Michael Howard, the retiring regius professor of
modern history, said in an interview. ``We are being starved of
essential resources.''
   The regius chair in Greek was founded by King Henry VIII in
1546, and the modern history chair by George I in 1727. Both are
widely regarded as being at the apex of scholarship.
   They being left vacant as part of a retrenchment program brought
on by an 11 percent cut in government funding, Mrs. Lonsdale said.
   Under the program, any academic post that becomes vacant is
frozen, usually for two years, until the Faculty Board decides
whether there is enough money to appoint a successor.
   As a result, 122 of Oxford's 1,420 faculty posts in virtually
all disciplines are vacant, Mrs. Lonsdale said.
   Failure to exempt the professorships in modern history and Greek
from the retrenchment reflects the seriousness of Oxford's cash
problem.
   Oxford has a budget of about $186 million, and its deficit is
running at about $3.3 million.
   The university has announced that it will launch a five-year,
worldwide campaign in October to ensure the future of the
university, which received its first charter in 1213. It has not
said how much money it wants to raise in its campaign, but says it
hopes to ensure the financial security of the university into the
next century.
   ``Oxford is beginning to seem like a place under siege,'' the
author A.N. Wilson wrote Monday in London's Daily Mail newspaper.
   Commenting on the professorial vacancies, the deterioration of
books and manuscripts in Oxford's Bodleian Library and the planned
closure of Oxford Playhouse, Wilson said:
   ``When you have a university which can't afford professors of
Greek and history; which can't afford to repair the priceless books
on its library shelves; which can't afford to keep open one of the
most famous undergraduate theaters in the world, then you are
entitled to ask: What is going on?''
   Howard, who is retiring one year early to take up a newly
created chair in military history at Yale University in 1989, said
his post could remain vacant for several years.
   ``There's simply not enough money to go around,'' he said.
   Oxford, Cambridge and Britain's 44 other state-funded
universities have long complained that spending limits imposed by
the Conservative government are threatening the nation's scientific
base and accelerating a brain drain to foreign universities.
   Critics say the government is denying support for research that
has no apparent short-term economic or military benefit. In a 1985
protest, Oxford denied an honorary doctorate to Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher, herself an Oxford graduate in chemistry.
   ``There is a lack of understanding of the value of scholarship
as an end of itself, irrespective of whether it contributes to the
national income or not,'' Howard said.
   Government officials contend the universities are overly
dependent on state funding and have refused to aggressively pursue
money from industry or even their own alumni.
   The regius professor of Greek, Hugh Lloyd-Jones, who is leaving
next year at the mandatory retirement age of 67, said the failure
to name his replacement goes beyond government policy, and reflects
the values of society at large.
   ``We have a society in which a footballer gets four times as
much as Sir Michael and I get together,'' said Lloyd-Jones.
``Someone who displays himself on television can get 10 times as
much.''
   The base salary for each regius chair is about $48,620 a year.
   Lloyd-Jones said the vacant posts should serve as ``a reminder
to anyone who thinks that we in the 20th century live in a
civilized society.''
   Howard said Oxford is moving fast to become self-sufficient, but
``there is a limit to what we can do over the short term.''
</TEXT>
