<1ST_LINE>r p AM-TahoeVote     05-23 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tahoe Vote,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vote Tuesday On New Tahoe City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STATELINE, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in several resort communities
decide Tuesday whether to form a new city to be called Lake Tahoe,
a measure opposed by casinos but favored by residents demanding
more for their taxes.
   The new city, with a population of about 6,500, would embrace
the gambling resort of Stateline and would be situated along 15
miles of Lake Tahoe's southeastern shore.
   Fewer than 3,000 registered voters in the Tahoe Township of
Douglas County are expected to go to the polls Tuesday to decide on
the measure, which has generated some 20 years of debate, hearings
and court battles.
   If the plan is approved, another election will be held to
organize the government.
   Proponents of the new city say the lakeshore communities
comprise nearly 25 percent of the county's population while
contributing 60 percent of the tax revenue. They say they do not
receive a proportionate share in services.
   ``We want to keep our tax dollars here,'' said Bill Bigham, a
leader of the movement to create the city Lake Tahoe, Nev.
   Ron Nino, leader of the opposition, said a city government will
only raise taxes without a corresponding improvement in services.
   The opposition has received financial support from the Stateline
casinos, whose tax burden Nino said would rise by at least $300,000
yearly under a city government. ``What will they get for it? Not
much,'' he added.
   Douglas County commissioners also advised against the idea.
   The county has said it stands to lose about $1.8 million in
yearly tax revenue, most of it from the big Stateline casinos, if
voters approve the plan, because property and gaming taxes will
shift from the county to city.
   The plan also produced an unsuccessful challenge in state court
last year and complaints from communities in California, on the
western side of the lake, that the name Lake Tahoe would create
confusion in the public mind between Lake Tahoe the lake and Lake
Tahoe the city.
   The new city, which would embrace such communities as Glenbrook,
Zephyr Cove, Round Hill, Cave Rock and Marla Bay, couldn't start
its business before July 1, 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
