<DOCNO> AP880523-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1555EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     05-23 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Ships Maneuver in Hormuz; U.S. Ships Steam Through Suez</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several Iranian warships conducted
maneuvers Monday in the Strait of Hormuz, apparently trying to show
continued readiness despite recent losses.
   Five U.S. warships destined for duty in the Persian Gulf passed
through the Suez Canal on Monday. The destroyer John Hancock and
missile frigates Fahrion, Halyburton, Nicholas and Robert G.
Bradley are to replace a missile cruiser and four frigates at the
end of this month.
   Gulf shipping executives said a large Iranian vessel that may
have been a destroyer, two frigates and a landing craft were seen
near Iran's naval base at Bandar Abbas.
   They said the ships could not be identified with certainty, but
the largest appeared to be a destroyer that has not been active for
more than a year in the gulf, where Iran and Iraq have been at war
since September 1980. The executives spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Iran has three destroyers, built during World War II for Britain
and the United States. They were modernized in the early 1970s with
anti-ship and anti-aircraft missiles, radar and other equipment.
   None has been seen in many months, leading military analysts to
speculate they were out of commission.
   Capt. Richard Sharpe, editor of Jane's Fighting Ships, said the
status of the former Royal Navy destroyer Damavand was ``very
doubtful'' but at least one, and probably both, former U.S. Navy
ships were operational.
   The Iranians said Sunday it was conducting naval exercises in
the Persian Gulf, Gulf of Oman and Indian Ocean. It said about 50
ships were involved, including ``missile carrying destroyers,
destroyers, missile launching frigates and personnel carriers.''
   Their official Islamic Republic News Agency said the maneuvers,
called Zolfaqar-3, would last several days. It said they would
involve ``land, sea and air operations and ... the latest
technology in sea wars,'' including radar and radio jamming, aerial
target tracking, paratroop drops, mine sweeping and interception of
air raids.
   IRNA quoted a naval intelligence officer it did not name as
saying the exercises were aimed at ``disproving U.S. claims that it
had crippled half the hardware of the Iranian navy.''
   Iran accused the U.S. Navy of providing assistance for Iraqi
jets that made a devastating air strike May 14 on Iran's Larak
island oil terminal in Hormuz, the narrow southern gateway to the
gulf, in which five tankers were damaged.
   On Apri1 18, U.S. warships and planes sank or disabled six
Iranian naval craft in a series of clashes.
   Iran's losses included the British-built frigate Sahand, a fast
attack boat and two armed speedboats sunk, the frigate Sabalan
disabled and a speedboat probably sunk.
   Tehran has acknowledged damage to several ships, including the
Sahand and Sabalan, and more than 40 sailors killed.
   U.S. casualties were two Marine pilots killed when their AH-1
Cobra helicopter gunship was lost. The Iranians claim they shot it
down.
   Since the clashes in April, the ``rules of engagement'' for U.S.
Navy ships have been changed so they can intervene in attacks by
Iranian vessels on neutral ships in international waters.
   Iranian speedboats have raided two ships in Hormuz in the past
week, but there have been no confrontations with the U.S. Navy
since April 18. None of the larger Iranian vessels sighted Monday
were involved in that fighting.
   The only one seen previously, on May 10, was the Alvand, a
sister ship of the two frigates hit last month. Western analysts
have said the other frigate, Alborz, was non-operational but senior
Navy officials said recently that both were back on duty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
