<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1617EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Sikhs     05-23 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs ,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Golden Temple Opened to Public After Bloody Siege</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh worshipers sobbed as they entered
the Golden Temple on Monday for the first time since the sacred
shrine was reopened after a two-week siege in which at least 46
people died, a city official said.
   Over 15,000 Sikh men, women and children waited solemnly in the
113-degree heat as security officials frisked them for weapons
before allowing them to enter the 400-year-old temple.
   It was closed during a police siege May 9-18 aimed at driving
Sikh separatists from their hiding places inside. At least 46
people, mostly Siklh militants, died during the clashes.
   Amitsar deputy commissioner Sarabjeet Singh said no incidents of
violence were reported Monday.
   ``We had a few emotional ourbrusts by some of the devotees,'' he
added.
   Some wept as they walked past the rooms from which Sikh radicals
shot back at Indian security men during the siege.
   ``I knew some of the boys, they were brave, maybe misguided,''
said Harbans Singh, 70, a Sikh farmer.
   ``The government operation has hurt our sentiment, there was no
need to kill so many people,'' said Surinder Kaur of Amritsar.
   United News of India quoted a majority of the worshipers
praising the government action.
   Religious services in the inner sanctum of the temple, suspended
on the second day of the siege, were resumed Sunday after
volunteers washed the floor of the temple with milk in a cleansing
ritual.
   Police and paramilitary troops cordoned off the shrine to
enforce a curfew still imposed on the area within 300 yards of its
walls.
   Deputy Commissioner Singh said the cordon would be lifted after
the government reaches an agreement with temple officials to stop
the shrine from being used as a hideout for Sikh radicals.
   Sikh gunmen, meanwhile, shot and killed four people in other
parts of Punjab state in overnight attacks, police said.
   Among the victims was a Hindu school headmaster, Tilak Raj, who
was shot and killed Monday by two Sikh radicals in front of 400
students in the town of Sangatpura, 15 miles north of Amritsar.
   The assailants ordered him out of his office and shot him at
point-blank range with a revolver, according to Gurmeet Singh, a
police officer.
   A note left by the Khalistan Commando Force, the most powerful
of the Sikh separatist groups, said Raj was killed to avenge the
siege of the Golden Temple. The note said more killings would
follow.
   Sikh separatists have been waging a guerrilla war since 1982 for
an independent Sikh homeland in this agricultural state, where they
form a majority of the population.
   The Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to India's warring Hindus and Moslems, make up 2
percent of India's 800 million people. They claim they are
discriminated against by the majority, which is 80 percent Hindu.
   Monday's killings raised to more than 1,150 the number of people
killed by Sikh extremists in Punjab state since the start of the
year. In 1987, 1,030 people were killed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
