<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1641EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Business     05-23 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Business,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Campaign Lining Up Business Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, whose relations with the business
community have been mixed during his tenure as Massachussetts
governor, is not willing to concede business support to its
traditional home in the Republican Party.
   Business leaders aligned with the Democratic front-runner's
campaign hope to sign up a minimum of 5,000 executives nationwide
for a national business coalition, with group leaders appearing on
behalf of Dukakis at conventions and other events.
   George Bush, with his entrepreneurial background and Republican
pedigree, has a ready-made base of support in the business arena.
But organizers of the Dukakis effort, to be officially announced
when leadership roles are filled, say their venture into
traditionally Republican circles has been well received because of
dissatisfaction with the Reagan administration's handling of the
trade and budget deficits.
   ``The conventional question about the Democratic Party's
candidates is their ability to make the hard economic decisions,
the business decisions,'' said Robert Farmer, a wealthy businessman
and Dukakis' top fund-raiser. ``For the first time in 20 years,
we've got a candidate with credibility on the economy and a record
of fiscal responsibility.''
   The first phase of the effort involves recruiting professionals
who have donated to the Dukakis campaign. Farmer has given Richard
Giesser, who is organizing the coalition, lists of contributors
with business ties.
   ``That's where you start,'' said Farmer. ``If you already bet $2
on a horse race you're apt to root for that horse all the way
around the track.''
   Giesser, chairman of the Massachussetts Port Authority, declined
to list prospective members of the group. Among Massachusetts
businessmen working with Giesser are Joe Henson, president of Prime
Computer Inc., and John J. Cullinane, the founder and president of
computer software maker Cullinet Inc.
   Another recent addition is prominent New York businessman John
Dyson, who promised to recruit 400 to 500 business officials in his
state.
   ``I think we will be able to organize such a group around the
country that (it) will surprise people,'' said Dyson, who met with
Dukakis at the Massachusetts Statehouse last week. ``Much of the
Republican Party takes business for granted,'' he said.
   Norman Ornstein, a political analyst at the American Enterprise
Institute in Washington, termed it unlikely that Dukakis could pull
support of a majority of top business leaders.
   ``But I think you're going to find that Dukakis is going to have
some success in getting serious business support,'' he said. ``It
can help. He's running the umbrella type campaign and trying to
keep the umbrella as big as possible. The more support he gets from
credible people in business and other groups, the more credence
people will give to his message.''
   Hensen and Cullinane are among Dukakis' top business backers in
Massachusetts _ proponents of public-private partnerships that
Dukakis has promoted to steer companies to economically struggling
areas of the state.
   Many other high-tech officials have long battled Dukakis on
issues ranging from state spending to environmental policy, and
small businessmen lately have criticized a new state law that
requires most employers to give workers health insurance by 1992.
   Even his detractors believe Dukakis will have at least limited
success in lining up business support.
   ``We've been saying for some time that he has been
overspending,'' said Howard Foley, chairman of the Massachusetts
High Technology Council. ``But how many business people in Texas or
California or Illinois or Pennsylvania are really going to care
about that?''
   The council was established in 1977, near the end of Dukakis'
first term as governor, by high tech executives dissatisfied with
Dukakis' record on taxes and economic development. Lobbying
pressure from the influential group led to several economic
development programs that Dukakis now touts on the campaign trail.
Members of the high-tech group also have complained that Dukakis
takes too much credit for the state economy.
   But Foley said the so-called ``Massachusetts miracle'' and
political momentum will attract business officials to Dukakis.
   ``Business and labor and every other constituency will be
anxious to be with a winner,'' Foley said. ``That's human nature.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
