<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1644EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     05-23 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Attack U.S. Diplomatic Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students hurling firebombs and rocks
attacked a U.S. diplomatic office Monday as thousands of
demonstrators battled riot police for a sixth consecutive day in
the southern city of Kwangju.
   The attack did not damage the single-story U.S. Information
Service building.
   Police said they fired tear gas to thwart the attack by bands of
students shouting anti-U.S. slogans and hurling firebombs at the
building in the provincial city 165 miles south of Seoul.
   At least four policemen were reported injured.
   The Korean news agency Yonhap said police arrested two
protesters who scaled the roof of an annex to the USIS building and
tossed five firebombs that smashed several rooftiles, but caused no
fire.
   A student was seen unfolding an anti-U.S. placard at the top of
a nearby building, while another 100 students surged out of
sidestreets to hurl rocks and about 30 firebombs that exploded
around the gate and walls of the USIS office.
   Also on Monday, groups of students attacked four police stations
in Kwangju, smashing windows and doors before being driven off.
Clashes between police and some 1,000 protesters also broke out in
downtown Kwangju after dark, the agency said.
   The firebomb attack followed demonstrations Monday at Kwangju's
Chonnam University, where police fired barrages of tear gas to stop
about 3,000 students and dissidents trying to march off campus.
   ``Down with the military dictatorship!'' and ``Drive out the
Yankees!'' the demonstrators shouted as they called for a full
investigation into the South Korean army's bloody suppression of a
1980 uprising in Kwangju in which about 200 people were killed.
   Thousands of demonstrators have clashed with police in Kwangju
since rallies began Wednesday marking the eighth anniversary of the
uprising.
   Anti-U.S. sentiment has been running high in the recent wave of
protests, with students demanding the removal of all U.S. influence.
   The U.S. government has denied any involvement in the Kwangju
incident, but dissidents contend the United States condoned the
movement of South Korean soldiers to suppress the protests. Under a
mutual defense pact, the United States controls both Korean troops
and 42,000 U.S. soldiers stationed here.
   Last week, protesters broke windows and hurled firebombs at the
USIS building in Seoul and hurled home made bombs at the U.S.
Embassy. A policeman and two students were hurt in the incident.
   But other parts of South Korea were reported quiet Monday after
five days of anti-government demonstrations that often turned into
violent clashes with riot police in the streets and on campuses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1654EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Tate     05-23 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tate,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Royal Visit Symbolizes Port City's Rebirth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIVERPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rum warehouse converted into a new
Tate Gallery of modern art opens Tuesday as the crown jewel in the
revived waterfront of this economically depressed port city.
   Prince Charles accepted Liverpool's invitation to open the
``Tate of the North,'' a permanent gallery housing more than 200
20th century works of art from London's Tate Gallery.
   ``The prince's visit is symbolic of the turnaround in our
city,'' said Keith Robinson, director of Liverpool Chamber of
Commerce.
   ``We have been hit hard and we are delighted that His Royal
Highness is coming here just as the tide is starting to flow
economically again in Liverpool's direction,'' he said in an
interview.
   The Tate is on 140-year-old Albert Dock in the city that was
founded on American and Caribbean trade in cotton, tobacco, sugar,
rum and African slaves.
   It is named after its Victorian benefactor, sugar cane magnate
Sir Henry Tate, a Liverpudlian whose sugar was imported through the
docks.
   The new northern gallery is the first endeavor by a state museum
in Britain to show its works on a large scale outside the capital
city.
   ``We will change the displays and exhibitions every nine months
and I expect half a million visitors a year,'' said curator Richard
Francis. ``The aim has been to take works out of storage and put
them in a place where they would be of benefit.''
   The first displays include surrealist art such as Salvador
Dali's ``Lobster Telephone,'' British sculpture of the past 20
years and a room of abstract paintings by the late American Mark
Rothko.
   ``I am absolutely delighted at this move,'' said Sir Alan
Bowness, who directs the Tate Gallery holdings of 40,000 works,
representing all British art and international 20th century art.
   ``Our space in London is large enough to show only about 15
percent of our modern art _ because modern art works tend to be big
_ and Liverpool will raise that to 25 percent.''
   The international council of the Museum of Modern Art in New
York visited Liverpool on Saturday to see how the five-story
warehouse of red bricks and stone, supported by cast-iron columns,
was converted at a cost of nearly $14 million by architect James
Stirling.
   ``It was filthy and ruinous when I saw it, with dead pigeons
lying everywhere, the roof collapsed and water pouring in,''
Stirling said. ``I was glad to work on it, as it is perhaps the
most magnificent dock of its type ever built in this country.''
   Said gallery staffer Sarah Hughes, 23: ``My friends here have a
bit of a giggle about modern art, which is an unknown quantity in
Liverpool.''
   ``But there's a great spirit of pride in this city, and not just
because we're the Beatles' hometown. We all want to get involved in
helping it,'' she added.
   Government and business moved to help Liverpool with millions of
pounds in cash grants in 1977 after the decline of the docks,
shipbuilding and automaking.
   Investment expanded after 1981 riots by the unemployed in the
Toxteth district led to one death, 3,000 arrests and streets of
homes and shops set ablaze.
   The city of 476,500 people still has a jobless rate of 25
percent and is having to overcome a history of strikes and leftist
political anarchy on the city council.
   Keynote of the revival is the transformation of the
once-abandoned city center docks along the Mersey river into a
leisure area of museums, shops, offices, apartments and businesses.
   ``The first sign we had that things were changing was one year
ago when employers reported shortages of skilled workers,'' said
Robinson.
   The docks are busy again because European businessmen are
realizing that Liverpool is still the nearest port to the United
States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1543EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CancerExperiments Bjt   05-23 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cancer Experiments, Bjt,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cancer Institute Hopes To Double Number of Patients in Cancer
Experments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Cancer Institute said Monday it
will try to double over the next four years the number of patients
who receive experimental treatments in an effort to speed up the
search for ways to stop the biggest cancer killers.
   Largely because of physicians' reluctance to enroll their
patients in cancer experiments, officials said, it may take 10
years or longer to assess the value of promising new therapies.
   ``We are not getting enrolled anywhere near the number of
patients we need to get answers within a reasonable period of
time,'' Dr. Vincent T. DeVita Jr., director of the cancer
institute, said at a meeting of the American Society of Clinical
Oncology.
   Currently, about 25,000 cancer patients each year are enrolled
in treatment experiments, known as clinical trials, that are
sponsored by the cancer institute.
   Through appeals to doctors and directly to the public, the
institute hopes to double this by 1992.
   Clinical trials are medicine's primary way of figuring out
whether new drugs and combinations of surgery and radiation are
better than the standard ways of coping with the disease.
Typically, patients are randomly assigned to have the standard
treatment or the new form of therapy.
   Only about 1 percent of patients with colon or breast cancer are
currently enrolled in clinical trials. DeVita said the institute
hopes to increase this to 10 percent.
   The goal is to enroll all the patients who will take part in an
experiment within one year, instead of over three, five or even 10
years, as often now happens. Once patients are enrolled, doctors
must wait five years to see which treatment worked best.
   DeVita said patients are often worried about taking part in
cancer experiments.
   ``The public is confused,'' he said. ``They think they are
guinea pigs, that they will get nothing and we'll just watch their
tumors grow. That's not the case.''
   Instead, DeVita maintained that participants in clinical trials
get the best available treatment, even if they are assigned to the
comparison group that doesn't get the experimental therapy.
   However, experts said that the unwillingness of doctors, not
patients, is the primary obstacle to increasing the number of
patients in clinical trials.
   Dr. Bernard Fisher of the University of Pittsburgh, who has been
conducting clinical trials since the 1950s, said doctors often want
to stick with the style of care they learned in medical school and
are also afraid they will lose control of their patients'
treatments.
   Dr. Robert E. Wittes, head of the cancer institute's Cancer
Therapy Evaluation Program, added, ``The main problem of
participating in trials is that they take time.''
   He said physicians are reluctant to spend time explaining the
treatment trials to their patients and keeping up with the paper
work involved.
   Another study, presented at the conference, suggested that many
doctors believe they already know what kind of treatment is best.
   Dr. Malcolm J. Moore of Princess Margaret Hospital in Toronto
surveyed 300 physicians in North American and England who treat
cancer of the bladder, kidneys and prostate gland. Seventy percent
responded that if they had one of these kinds of cancer, they would
not enroll themselves in a clinical trial. Instead, they would
prefer the kind of therapy they already offer their patients.
   Wittes said the cancer institute is trying to appeal to doctors'
sense of public duty.
   ``We are saying, `You will do good for society, and you will do
good for your patients.'''
   Wittes said the cancer institute will concentrate at first in
enrolling more patients in clinical trials of new treatments for
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma and cancers of the breast, colon, rectum and
bladder.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1556EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GunBill Bjt   05-23 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gun Bill, Bjt,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maryland Law Hailed as Gun Control Breakthrough</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Griisser is cq in 13th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM STUCKEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Against a backdrop of nearly 200 police
officers, Gov. William Donald Schaefer signed a law Monday making
Maryland the first state to ban the sale of cheap handguns known as
Saturday Night Specials.
   ``This is the first time a legislature has stood up and said,
`These guns are wrong,''' the governor said. He said the measure is
a step toward stopping ``the senseless killing on our streets.''
   Looking on was White House press secretary James Brady, who was
wounded by a Saturday Night Special in the 1981 assassination
attempt on President Reagan by John W. Hinckley Jr. Brady's wife,
Sarah, had lobbied for the bill.
   ``I'd like to see other states like dominoes fall into line,''
said Brady, who has been in a wheelchair since the shooting.
``Thumbs up for Maryland.''
   ``I can't think of a sweeter, more wonderful day. This is indeed
a great step for public safety,'' said Mrs. Brady.
   In the last 20 years, Saturday Night Specials have been used to
kill 250,000 people and injure 1{ million, she said.
   The law makes it illegal after Jan. 1, 1990, to sell or
manufacture a Saturday Night Special in Maryland. It will not be
against the law to own such weapons.
   The measure also sets up a nine-member board appointed by the
governor to prepare a list of handguns that may be sold. Weapons
that are easily concealed, inaccurate, unsafe and poorly made will
be banned under the law.
   The bill also allows the board to ban plastic guns that can be
slipped through metal detectors.
   Nearly 200 uniformed police officers from Maryland,
Pennsylvania, Delaware, Virginia and West Virginia witnessed the
signing in an effort by the governor to demonstrate wide support
among law enforcement agencies.
   Gun owners, backed by the National Rifle Association, already
are collecting signatures to put the law to a vote in a referendum
in November.
   Jim Goss, an NRA official in Washington, said the organization
had no comment on the bill. He referred callers to leaders of the
Maryland Committee Against the Gun Ban.
   Fred Griisser, a spokesman for the committe, said he doesn't
have a count on the number of signatures collected so far, but that
he is confident his organization will meet the requirement of
33,044 to put the bill to a vote.
   After that, ``it will be an uphill battle to explain the true
nature of the law to the voters,'' he said.
   Under the law, manufacturers can be fined up to $10,000 and
dealers and gun owners up to $2,500 for each violation. Each time a
gun is made or sold constitutes a separate violation.
   Mrs. Brady, who has been campaigning nationally for tougher gun
laws since her husband was shot, said the Maryland approach solves
the difficult problem of trying to define Saturday Night Specials
by leaving the decision to a review board.
   The board will consist of three citizen members, the
superintendent of state police and one representative each of a
state prosecutors association, the Maryland Association of Chiefs
of Police, Marylanders Against Handgun Abuse, the National Rifle
Association and a Maryland gun manufacturer.
   Other states are interested in the Maryland approach and gun
control groups are gearing up to try to pass similar laws
elsewhere, Mrs. Brady said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1609EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GunLaw Bjt   05-23 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gun Law, Bjt,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmitting to correct slug</HEAD>
<HEAD>Maryland Law Hailed as Gun Control Breakthrough</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Griisser is cq in 13th graf</NOTE>
