<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1721EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ScholarSentenced     05-23 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scholar Sentenced,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scholar Sentenced To Three Years In Prison For Transporting Stolen
Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Brooklyn-born art scholar with the air of a
British gentleman was sentenced Monday to three years in prison for
transporting stolen documents belonging to the National Archives
and the Library of Congress.
   Charles Merrill Mount, 60, also was ordered to repay $20,000 to
a Boston bookstore that bought some of the documents.
   Mount predicted he would win an appeal.
   U.S. District Judge Rya Zobel sentenced Mount to two three-year
prison terms, but suspended the second term and instead ordered
Mount to serve five years' probation after his release.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Martin F. Murphy had recommended a total
prison sentence of eight years, while defense attorney Charles
McGinty requested a suspended sentence. Mount, who was convicted
April 11, could have received up to 10 years in prison and a
$500,000 fine.
   McGinty asked Monday that Mount be allowed to remain free long
enough to help prepare for a trial in Washington on charges of
possessing federal property. Ms. Zobel ordered Mount taken into
custody pending her decision on the request.
   Before the sentence was read, Mount professed his innocence in a
rambling 35-minute speech to Ms. Zobel about how he was the victim
of libel and plagiarism by envious historians.
   Ms. Zobel told Mount: ``You continue to proclaim your innocence.
However, the jury did not believe your testimony. ... You stole
those documents from us all. Those documents belong to the national
heritage.''
   An art historian and a Guggenheim Foundation fellow at the age
of 26, Mount was accused of selling letters by James McNeill
Whistler, Winston Churchill and Henry James that belonged to the
Library of Congress. Last July he sold the letters to Goodspeed's
Book Shop, a Boston dealer of rare books and documents.
   A month later, FBI agents arrested the dapper historian at the
bookshop while he tried to sell letters and papers bearing the
signatures of Abraham Lincoln and Civil War generals. The documents
were taken from the National Archives.
   Murphy said the documents had been stored in Massachusetts
during the trial but will be returned to the institutions in
Washington.
   Mount claimed the documents belonged to him for years and that
he showed them to two Irish men while living in Dublin in the 1960s.
   But his legal troubles left him broke and he couldn't afford to
bring the witnesses to his trial, he said. The federal government
seized his $18,400 in savings after his arrest. That money will now
go to repay Goodspeed's.
   During his three-week trial, Mount protested that he wasn't
being allowed to present his side of the case. He claimed he was
being railroaded because the government would not pay to bring the
witnesses from Ireland.
   Despite having a British-sounding accent, Mount started in life
as Sherman Merrill Suchow of Brooklyn, N.Y. He changed his name in
the 1950s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1721EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Meat-Drugs     05-23 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meat-Drugs,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Rules Proposed for Liability When Carcasses Condemned for
Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed change in federal regulations would
hold farmers and others in the marketing chain financially
accountable for livestock carcasses condemned at slaughter plants
because of illegally high traces of drugs, the Agriculture
Department said Monday.
   B.H. ``Bill'' Jones, administrator of the department's Packers
and Stockyards Administration, said the proposal is intended to
deter the sale of medicated aniamls for slaughter and shift
economic responsibility for illegal drug residues from the meat
packer to those who cause the violation.
   Under the proposal, a meat packer would be able to ``bill back''
the person from whom the livestock was bought if it is condemned
because of illegal drug residues.
   In order to make the plan work, Jones said, each purchaser or
selling agency in the marketing chain would be permitted to use the
bill-back procedure. If a seller failed to settle up, the buyer or
selling agency would be permitted to deduct from a subsequent
purchase from the same person.
   Jones said that although a small percentage of livestock
producers are selling medicated animals for slaughter, the
illegally high drug residues continue to be a problem, notably in
swine, culled dairy cows and young calves.
   The proposal will be open 60 days for public comment. Those can
be sent to: Packers and Stockyards Administration, Room 3039-S,
USDA, Washington, D.C. 20250.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
