<DOCNO> AP880523-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1724EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PrisonEscape     05-23 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Escape,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Escapee, Wife Still At Large</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHILLICOTHE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An escaped inmate accompanied by his
stepdaughter and the wife he married while in prison remained at
large Monday and may be driving a Cadillac rented by his wife,
authorities said.
   Michael Day, 31, of Athens, took two guards hostage at gunpoint
and escaped Sunday in a prison jeep, said spokesman Robert Prosser
of the medium-security Ross Correctional Institute.
   Day and the two guards then went to a Holiday Inn where his wife
was waiting with a getaway car. The woman was accompanied by her
9-year-old daughter, Prosser said Monday.
   Day left one guard handcuffed to the jeep's steering wheel and
the other to a towel bar in a room registered to Day's wife, Sylvia
Caraveo Day.
   Prosser said the guard in the hotel room freed himself in time
to watch from a window as the Days got into a silver Nissan.
   Authorities found that car abandoned here and believe Mrs. Day
rented a Cadillac from Avis at the Columbus airport. They said Day
had paid a man they refused to identify to drive them to Columbus.
   ``At this point, we have an all-points bulletin out throughout
Ohio and in surrounding states,'' Prosser said Monday. ``We're
pursuing some leads, but I can't comment on them.''
   Prosser could not say what type of gun was used in the escape,
but said authorities ``are working on the assumption it's the same
gun he has now.'' He said the gun apparently came from a source
outside the prison.
   ``It was an obvious breach of security and we're very concerned
about that,'' Prosser said.
   Prison spokeswoman Sandy Price said patrol officials and prison
Superintendent Gary Mohr questioned the two guards late Sunday
night. The guards' names were not released.
   Day was convicted of attempted abduction, burglary, receiving
stolen property and carrying a concealed weapon after a felony
conviction, Ms. Price said. He had been at the Ross prison since
June 1987 and had served at the Chillicothe Correctional Institute
and Ohio State Reformatory in Mansfield since April 1985.
   Prosser said Day got married while he was in prison.
</TEXT>
