<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bouvia     05-23 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bouvia,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bedridden Right-To-Die Figure Says She Still Wants Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The paralyzed woman whose right-to-die court
fight set a precedent says she temporarily has abandoned plans to
starve herself to death.
   Frail, bedridden Elizabeth Bouvia said she still wants her life
to end, but added in an interview with the Los Angeles Times:
   ``If I tried to starve myself, I would be publicly shunned.
Starving myself would take too long. I wish there was a quicker
way.''
   The 30-year-old former social worker, crippled by cerebral
palsy, lives in reclusion at Los Angeles County-University of
Southern California Medical Center, where she passes her time
watching television and smoking 1{ packs of cigarettes a day.
   Weighing 90 pounds, up from 68, Ms. Bouvia said she eats at
least one meal a day.
   She is registered at the hospital as a Jane Doe and lives in one
of the hospital's few isolation rooms. She has left the room six
times in the last two years _ once to see a dentist, the other
times to make telephone calls.
   She said she last tried to starve herself in January 1987, but
gave up when she learned she would have to endure several painful
weeks before dying.
   Her 1986 court battles against hospitals where doctors force-fed
her rather than allow her to die established case law defending
patients' rights to control medical treatment, regardless of age,
health or motives.
   She has visitors about once a week, and her family in Oregon
travels south to see her a few times a year, she said.
   Nonetheless, she abhors her condition.
   ``The thought of being here another 10 years, I just can't
fathom,'' she said. ``I would rather die than live here.''
</TEXT>
