<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1757EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NavyDeath     05-23 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Death,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Experts Meet, Hearing Set in Recruit's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy and Coast Guard review began
Monday of proposed changes in an air-sea rescue training program
suspended since the March 2 drowning of a recruit.
   Six sailors accused in the drowning also face a public hearing
Wednesday as Navy officials denied charges by the man's family that
they were slow to investigate his death. Airman Recruit Lee
Mirecki, 19, of Appleton, Wis., died while allegedly held in the
pool by instructors.
   The review of recommended changes at the Rescue Swimmer School
is closed to the public, said Lt. Cmdr. Dennis Hessler, a spokesman
for Vice Adm. N.R. Thunman.
   The school at the Pensacola Naval Air Station had a 40 percent
attrition rate and already was under study prior to the death, said
Thunman, chief of naval education and training. He added that such
high rates often mean ``we haven't put the right people there and
we haven't prepared them properly for training.''
   Mirecki died after instructors allegedly dragged him into a pool
against his will and held his head under water after he failed a
drill.
   Other recruits reportedly were told to turn their backs to the
pool and sing ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' as loudly as they could
to drown out Mirecki's screams for help.
   Family members say they were told Mirecki's death was an
accident, and Navy records in Washington initially attributed his
death to natural causes. They complain that they had to wait two
months before getting any official word on how he died.
   The five instructors were charged with involuntary manslaughter
and conspiracy to commit battery. Their commanding officer was
charged with dereliction of duty.
   The Wednesday hearing is the military's equivalent to a grand
jury inquiry, though some differences exist, including it being
open to the public.
   Lt. Lee Saunders, a public affairs officer, said portions of the
hearing might be closed for legal reasons, however.
   The presiding officer, Cmdr. Daniel J. D'Alesio of the Naval
Legal Service Office in Philadelphia, will recommend whether the
charges should go to court-martial, be dismissed or handled through
non-judicial penalties.
   The accused sailors could be dismissed from the service if they
are found guilty at a court-martial. Those charged with involuntary
manslaughter also could be imprisoned up three years. Their
commander could face three months.
</TEXT>
