<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BabyMReaction     05-23 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby M Reaction,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baby M's Mother Unhappy With TV Account</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary Beth Whitehead-Gould, the real-life
mother of Baby M, says she's not impressed with the television film
about her groundbreaking surrogate motherhood.
   ``I think the only truth in the whole thing ... was my dog and
the nine puppies,'' said Whitehead-Gould, who was in Washington on
Monday to join in a call to end commercialized surrogate parenting.
   She said she saw only the second hour of the film, broadcast
Sunday on the ABC network. The movie, ``Baby M,'' was to conclude
Monday night.
   She called the film a ``whitewashed'' depiction of the surrogate
agreement and ensuing battle in New Jersey courts that made her the
nation's best-known surrogate.
   She said she was particularly upset by the film's shallow
portrayal of her ex-husband, Richard Whitehead.
   The Whiteheads were divorced this year, and Mary Beth Whitehead
married Dean Gould. The couple had a child earlier this month.
   Whitehead-Gould gained fame after she refused to surrender her
infant daughter to its biological father, William Stern, also of
New Jersey.
   Stern and his wife sued, and a New Jersey state court last year
upheld the contract under which Whitehead-Gould accepted a $10,000
fee to bear Stern's child.
   The contract was voided in February by the state Supreme Court,
although the court let the Stern's keep the child they named
Melissa. Whitehead-Gould has visitation rights.
   The made-for-television film stars JoBeth Williams as
Whitehead-Gould. The film, based entirely on court records, was
made without the cooperation of Whitehead-Gould or the Sterns.
</TEXT>
