<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1930EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Soviet     05-23 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Soviet,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Soviets Visit Western European Chemical Warfare Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Soviet-Summit, Bjt
^By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain on Monday welcomed the first Soviet
delegation to visit a chemical warfare facility in Western Europe.
   Thirteen Soviet scientists and military experts will spend three
days inspecting Britain's chemical warfare defense center and
related facilities in southwestern England and talking with British
chemical weapons experts.
   Britain stopped making chemical weapons in the 1950s and
destroyed its stockpiles in 1957.
   The Ministry of Defense said it will be the first exchange visit
on chemical weapons between the Soviet Union and a Western European
country.
   ``It is intended that the full range of chemical warfare-related
issues should be discussed ... including production, assessment of
the chemical warfare hazards, storage, trials, detection,
protection, monitoring, decontamination, medical countermeasures
and disposal,'' said Ian Stewart, minister of state for the Armed
Forces.
   The visiting delegation is led by Yuri Nazarkin, the chief
Soviet negotiatior at the Geneva Conference on Disarmament and
includes Maj. Gen. R.F. Razuvanov, commander of the Soviet chemical
establishment in Shikhany, located on the Volga in eastern Russia.
   The Soviets will visit the Chemical Warfare Defense Center at
Porton Down, which sprawls across 7,000 acres on Salisbury plain
near the ancient Stonehenge monument, about 80 miles southwest of
London.
   Since Britain's stockpiles have been destroyed, Porton Down now
does only defensive work, making protective equipment such as gas
masks, clothing and monitoring instruments for the armed forces and
developing antidotes to chemical weapons.
   The Soviets also will visit the nearby Public Health Laboratory
Service Center, where applied microbiological research is
conducted, and the United Kingdom Defense Nuclear Biological and
Chemical Center, where instructors are trained to use defensive
equipment to counter chemical weapons.
   In return, British scientists will in July visit the Soviet
chemical warfare facility in Shikhany.
   Britain proposed the exchange in 1986, before the Soviets
acknowledged that they possess chemical weapons.
   In early 1987, the Soviets conceded they have a chemical weapons
stockpile amounting to 50,000 tons and accepted the British
invitation later that year. Western estimates, however, put the
Soviet stockpile at 300,000 tons _ the largest in the world.
   Britain, which has been in the forefront of negotiations to
achieve a worldwide ban on chemical weapons, said last week that
such a ban, as well as reductions in conventional forces, must come
before any further negotiations on cutting nuclear weapons in
Europe.
   The United States, the only other country that acknowledges
possessing chemical weapons, ended an 18-year moratorium on their
manufacture in December and has an estimated stockpile of 30,000
tons.
   The massive Soviet stockpile has been a major stumbling block at
the 40-nation Geneva Conference. A 1925 Geneva protocol bans the
use of chemical arms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
