<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SoilProgram     05-23 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soil Program,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>3.4 Million More Acres of Erodible Cropland Go Into Conservation
Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An additional 3,375,367 acres of highly
erodible cropland will be taken from production under the 10-year
Conservation Reserve Program, the Agriculture Department said
Monday.
   Milton Hertz, administrator of the department's Agricultural
Stabilization and Conservation Program, said the acreage was
accepted from offers, or bids, during the program's sixth signup
held Feb. 1-19. A total of about 4.5 million acres was offered
during the signup.
   In all, counting the earlier signups, more than 25.5 million
acres have been accepted into the program, he said. Another signup
will be held July 18 through Aug. 5.
   Congress in the 1985 farm law set a goal of 40 million to 45
million acres for the program by 1990.
   Under the program, farmers agree to take land from production
for 10 years. In return, based on bids they submit, they get annual
rental payments from the government and one-time assistance pay for
half the cost of planting grass, trees and shrubs to guard against
erosion.
   Hertz said the bids accepted from the latest signup averaged
$47.90 per acre annually, compared with $48.45 for the first five
signups.
</TEXT>
