<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1932EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia     05-23 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>80,000 Peasants March on Half Dozen Colombian Cities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 80,000 peasants marched on
a half dozen Colombian cities Monday, demanding land,
nationalization of foreign oil companies and an end to what they
call the army's ``dirty war'' against them.
   The military said leftist guerrillas organized the protests.
   There have been 20 peasant marches in Colombia in the last year.
This is the first time the protests were aimed at foreign oil
companies.
   There are approximately 30 such companies here.
   Newspapers and radio chains with reporters accompanying the
peasants estimated the total number of protesters as about 80,000.
   In Bogota, the capital, troops occupied Colombia's national
university after the rector, Marco Palacio, said young people with
guns organized protests that led to cars being stoned and to
university property being destroyed.
   Peasants marched on the northern cities of Barranquilla,
Cartagena, Santa Marta and Valledupar, on Bucaramanga in the east
and on Barrancabermeja in central Colombia.
   In another development, guerrillas of the National Liberation
Army threw a bomb and hijacked a bus in the northwest city of
Medellin, police there reported.
   A police release said little damage was caused by the bomb
explosion Sunday night at the Medellin headquarters of a banana
plantation owners' association.
   Banana growers and banana pickers have been at odds for months.
Right-wing death squads have killed 95 workers. The National
Liberation Army, known as the ELN, has killed 10 workers believed
to be army informants.
   ELN guerrillas hijacked a busload of workers in Medellin on
Monday, but freed everyone and fled after harranguing the
passengers, the police said.
   Defense Minister Gen. Rafael Samudio Molina said in an interview
with the radio chain RCN that Monday's peasant protests were
organized by the ELN.
   The ELN demands that foreign oil companies get out of Colombia
and that the government nationalize their holdings.
   The guerrilla group has bombed the country's main oil pipeline
two dozen times this year.
   The line runs 500 miles from Bogota's biggest oil field, on the
Venezuelan border in northern Arauca province, to the Caribbean
port of Covenas.
   As in past protests, the peasants claimed that the army is
behind death squads that have killed hundreds of people in the last
two years.
   Death squads killed about 800 members of a leftist party, the
Patriotic Union, during that time. In the last two months, death
squads killed more than 150 peasants, including those in the
banana-growing regions, for alleged sympathy with leftist
guerrillas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
