<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Colombia-Hijacking 8thLd-Writethru a0633 05-23 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia-Hijacking, 8th Ld-Writethru, a0633, a,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hijacked Colombian Plane Lands in Aruba</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with plane landing, CHANGE
number of passengers freed; picks up 8th graf pvs, ``Guerrero said
...; CORRECTS spelling of Oranjestad in dateline, 3rd graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ORANJESTAD, Aruba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An armed hijacker commandeered a
Colombian jetliner today and diverted it to Panama then Aruba after
freeing 131 people, authorities said.
   Colombian Civil Aeronautics chief Yezid Castano said the
hijacker was demanding $100,000. Castano said the man claimed to
have a fatal disease and wanted to live out his days in Cuba.
   The plane landed at Reina Beatrix International Airport in
Oranjestad, Aruba this afternoon, said an American Airlines
employee there.
   ``The plane is here at this moment,'' the employee said,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``There are police at the
airport. No one is being allowed near the plane.''
   Nilka Vergara, spokeswoman at Omar Torrijos International
Airport, said the aircraft was fueled after a three-hour stop in
Panama.
   Airport administrator Eduardo Guerrero said the lone male
hijacker carried two hand grenades and at least one pistol and was
holding the pilot, co-pilot and a flight engineer hostage.
   There were no passengers on board.
   Speaking to reporters, Guerrero called the man ``desquiciado'' _
Spanish for mentally unbalanced _ and said a special negotiating
team that talked with him on a ground-crew intercom could not learn
his identity, nationality or what he wants.
   Castano initially said 135 people were let of the plane in
Medellin, but later revised the figure to 131 people, including
three flight attendants.
   The hijacker forced the airliner's crew to cut off
communications with the airport control tower after the plane
landed in Panama, Guerrero said. But he said a three-man
negotiating team walked up to the plane and spoke through the
intercom.
   Guerrero said the negotiating team was made up of Panamanian Air
Force Capt. Miguel von Siedlitz, chief of security at the airport;
Luis Rossi, director of all Panamanian airports; and Maj. Fitz
Gibson of the Panamanian Defense Forces.
   He said a special Defense Force team was deployed around the
plane. Soldiers could be seen in ditches about 80 yards from the
jet.
   The Avianca jet took off from the Colombian city of Medellin
this morning on a flight to Bogota, about 200 miles to the
southeast, and was hijacked, the security chief of Colombia's Civil
Aeronautics Administration told the radio network Caracol.
   Capt. Edgard Lozano told the radio in Bogota that the plane was
forced back to Medellin, where 129 passengers and six flight
attendants were freed.
   The Boeing 727 then took off for Panama, where it landed at the
international airport outside Panama City and taxiied to a stop on
the grass next to an isolated runway. Reporters and most officials
were kept about 600 yards away.
   In Medellin, several passengers spoke to radio Caracol.
``Everything happened very fast, but there was no panic,'' said one
passenger, Luis Fernando Piedrahita.
   He said the hijacker was a young man. The hijacker carried a
briefcase that he said contained hand grenades, Piedrahita said.
   Another passanger, Javier Robledo, said he was sitting next to
the hijacker.
   The young man gave a note to a flight attendant and she led him
to cockpit, Robledo told Caracol.
   ``Both the hijacker and the flight attendant were very
nervous,'' Robledo said. ``Nothing happened, and 10 minutes after
going back to the airport the pilot told everyone they should get
off the plane.''
</TEXT>
