<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1952EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Soviet-Agriculture     05-23 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Agriculture,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Farm Exports to Soviet Union Expected To Rise Sharply This
Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The value of U.S. agricultural exports to the
Soviet Union this year is expected to be at a three-year high of
$1.4 billion, up 50 percent from $938 million in calendar 1987, the
Agriculture Department said Monday.
   ``Behind the gain will be much larger wheat shipments at higher
prices and much bigger soybean and soybean meal sales,'' the
department's Economic Research Service said.
   Farm product sales to the Soviets exceeded $1.9 billion in 1985
but plummeted to a 13-year-low of $658 million in 1986 before
starting their rebound.
   A major factor has been large sales of U.S. wheat at subsidized
prices under the department's Export Enhancement Program.
   ``The U.S. value share of Soviet grain imports may be above 30
percent for the first time since 1984 and (may comprise) over 8
percent of total agricultural imports,'' the report said.
   Although total Soviet agricultural imports may increase 5
percent in 1988 from last year's estimated $16 billion, the value
still will be below the $19 billion average during the first half
of the 1980s.
   ``Grain imports now cost about $3 billion a year instead of $7
billion as in 1981-85,'' the report said. Despite a possible 20
percent rise in the per-ton cost of imported grain in 1988, this
``unit value'' will still be around one-third lower in the early
1980s.
   Earlier this month, the USDA forecast 1988 Soviet grain output
at 215 million metric tons, up 2 percent from last year. It also
would be the third consecutive harvest of more than 200 millon
tons, a historic first for the Soviet Union.
   ``Crops are off to a much better start than in 1987 following a
good fall sowing, overwintering and spring planting conditions,''
Monday's analysis said. ``Barring unusually severe weather through
the spring and fall, 1988 crop output should increase.''
</TEXT>
