<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChainSawMurder     05-23 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chain Saw Murder,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Opens for Prof Charged With Dismemberment Slaying of Teen
Prostitute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It will take up to two months to complete the
trial of a professor accused of the chain saw murder of a teen-age
male prostitute whose body parts were scattered across the state,
potential jurors were told Monday.
   Max Bernard Franc, 58, who taught political science at Fresno
State University but maintained an apartment in West Hollywood, has
denied killing the 18-year-old runaway, blaming a man who has never
been found.
   The trial is expected to offer insight into the plight of young
runaways in the West Hollywood gay community.
   Superior Court Judge John H. Reid told 70 prospective jurors
Franc's trial could last as long as eight weeks.
   ``Some have referred to this as the chain saw case,'' the judge
told the prospects and informed them that body parts had been found
in various locations in California.
   He instructed them not to read anything further about the case.
   The victim, Tracy Leroy Nute, of Kansas City, Mo., was 18 when
he died on Aug. 20. He had left home the previous February, telling
his mother that he was headed for California to become a movie star.
   After his arrival, he bleached his dark hair blond and wore it
in spikes. Counselors in the gay community said Nute turned to them
for help after his dreams of stardom faded and he wound up working
as a homosexual prostitute.
   Franc, a bespectacled professor originally from De Pere, Wis.,
was arrested Aug. 29 after he returned a chain saw to a West
Hollywood rental company with bits of flesh and blood in its inner
workings.
   Police alleged that the saw was used to cut up Nute's body,
which was found in pieces scattered across a 200-mile area. Some
parts of the body were never found.
   In early interviews with police, Franc claimed that Nute was
murdered by another man, Terry Adams, but no such person was ever
located and a prosecutor contends the man was invented by Franc.
   If convicted, Franc could face life imprisonment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
