<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PandaExhibit     05-23 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panda Exhibit,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zoo Gets Green Light on Panda Exhibit _ for Now</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service has decided
to allow an Ohio zoo to begin exhibiting two giant pandas on loan
from China while zoo officials work to produce the required export
papers, the service said Monday.
   Last week, the agency said the Toledo Zoo would not be allowed
to display the pandas until it could provide the original export
permit. The zoo, which has scheduled to open the panda exhibit
Tuesday, was given 10 days to come up with the documentation.
   However, USFWS spokesman David Klinger said Monday that lawyers
for the zoo gave the service a copy of the Chinese export permit
over the weekend and appear to be making a good-faith effort to
deliver the original document.
   ``We're not going to stand in the way of them opening their
exhibit this week,'' Klinger said. ``They appear to be making an
effort to deliver the documents. We'll accept that in good faith
from them as a first step. We'll allow them to open as they want.''
   However, Klinger said the zoo still will be required to provide
the originals by May 29. Zoo officials have said they have a
representative in China working on getting the documents to the
service.
   Zoo spokeswoman Patty Napierala confirmed that the zoo had
gotten the green light to open the exhibit and plans to do so at
noon Tuesday.
   The zoo has spent nearly $3 million in preparing to exhibit the
pandas as part of Toledo's 150th anniversary celebration.
   In a bid to stop the exhibit, the World Wildlife Fund filed suit
against the wildlife service, arguing that the exhibit would
violate an international convention that bars trafficking in
endangered species for commercial purposes.
   Klinger said Toledo Zoo officials had sought unsuccessfully to
be exempted from the convention on endangered species and had filed
an exemption form with the service instead of the full export
permit as required.
   When the pandas arrived in Chicago on May 13, the paperwork had
not been corrected. Klinger said the service decided it would be
best for the pandas to allow them to go on to Toledo and to take up
the issue later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
