<2ND_LINE>AM-GOP Convention,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fund-Raiser: The Money's Coming In</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition raising money for New Orleans'
share of Republican National Convention costs has picked up nearly
$450,000 in less than two weeks, a fund-raiser said Monday.
   ``More than $448,000 has been raised since May 11 in pledges and
contributions,'' said Ron Jones, president of the Louisiana
Business Council.
   That means the city still has about $3.3 million to go in its
effort to cover $5.5 million in estimated expenses for the GOP
convention Aug. 15-18 in the Louisiana Superdome, he said.
   Jones predicted the New Orleans Special Events Fund will have
all but about $1 million by mid-July.
   Two weeks ago, the head of the money-raising effort, oilman
Patrick Taylor, said the job was too big for one man and that
donations were trickling in at a disappointing rate.
   Jones, Jim Bob Moffett, president of the New Orleans Chamber of
Commerce, and Mervin Trail, president of the New Orleans Tourist
Commission, then announced they would join the fund drive.
   At a news conference Monday, 85 days before the convention,
Trail also responded to reports that some Republican organizers
were unhappy with the availability and quality of hotel rooms being
offered for the convention.
   The Republican National Committee has not defined a first-class
hotel room for local coordinators, Trail said. But he said he will
meet with RNC officials on Wednesday to work out any problems with
accommodations.
   Jones also spoke of community plans to prepare the city for the
convention.
   ``Between July 4 and Aug. 15, you can expect the city of New
Orleans to be covered in red, white and blue,'' he said.
</TEXT>
