<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MathOlympiad     05-23 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Math Olympiad,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadian Wins USA Mathematical Olympiad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 18-year-old from Toronto, Canada, captured
first place in the 17th U.S.A. Mathematical Olympiad, a math
association said Monday.
   It was the third time that Ravi D. Vakil, a 12th grader from
Martingrove Collegiate Institute in Toronto, has won a medal in the
American math competition that is open to U.S. and Canadian
residents.
   Second place went to Jordan S. Ellenberg, 16, a junior at
Winston Churchill High School in Potomac, Md., who won a gold medal
in last summer's International Mathematical Olympiad in Cuba.
   The Mathematical Association of America said the other top
finishers, in order, were: Tal N. Kubo, 18, an Israeli-born senior
at Brookline High School in Massachusetts; Joshua B. Fischman, 15,
a sophomore at Montgomery Blair High School in Bethesda, Md., and
Hubert L. Bray, 17, a senior at Westbury High School in Houston,
who tied for fourth; Nhat Nguyen, 15, a native of Vietnam who is a
ninth grader at Columbus Academy in Columbus, Ohio; and Eric K.
Wepsic, 18, a senior at Boston Latin School in Boston, and David M.
Patrick, 16, a senior at Batavia High School in New York, who tied
for seventh.
   The eight medalists topped a field of 145 students who competed
in the U.S.A. Mathematical Olympiad. They were the top performers
in an earlier exam taken by more than 389,000 students in the
United States and Canada in March and a subsequent tougher exam
taken by more than 1,000 students.
   Wepsic, like Ellenberg, also won a gold medal at last summer's
International Olympiad.
   The eight students will be feted at a dinner at the State
Department on June 7. The American medalists and 16 others will
then spend a month in training at the U.S. Naval Academy in
Annapolis, before a team of six U.S. students is chosen to compete
in the International Mathematical Olympiad in Canberra, Australia,
July 9-21.
   Vakil was expected to compete in Canberra for Canada.
</TEXT>
