<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Charny     05-23 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Charny,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Appeal For Release of Soviet Cancer Patient</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Congress and family members on
Monday urged the Soviet Union to allow mathematician Benjamin
Charny to emigrate to the United States for medical resons.
   ``The reason they refuse to let him go is ludicrous,'' said
Charney's daughter, Ann Charny-Blank of Brookline, Mass. Officially
Charny is being denied emigration because of work he did 17 years
ago on the Soviets' rocket re-entry system, she said.
   Charney, 50, has a serious heart condition which cardiologists
in the Soviet Union say make removal of two tumors on his neck and
thyroid gland too risky, she said. Western physicians who examined
Charny said the necessary surgery would be routine if conducted in
the West.
   The tumor on Charney's neck, which reportedly doubles in size
every few months, is now 3.5 inches in diameter and threatens to
block nerves and arteries to the brain, Mrs. Charny-Blank said at a
news conference.
   Noting the move to sign a U.S.-Soviet agreement on a joint
mission to Mars as ``a sign of trust,'' Mrs. Charny-Blank said ``it
is especially ridiculous under these circumstances to claim that my
father's work is still secret.''
   ``It looks as if the Soviets are planning to fly to Mars,
together with the Americans but return separately, since they still
consider the work of my father on the return (to Earth) to be a
secret,'' she said.
   ``I cannot understand it,'' she said. ``My only hope is that
with this coming summit, responding to all the indignation of
people in America and all over the world during the summit (that)
my father's case will finally be resolved and this race against
time will finally be over.''
   Mrs. Charny-Blank, who was allowed to emmigrate with her husband
and daughter last fall, was joined at the news conference by Reps.
Barney Frank, D-Mass., and Louis Stokes, D-Ohio.
   A group of children from nearby Falls Church, Va., presented
part of 15,000 letters from American schoolchildren and one signed
by more than 100 members of Congress on Charny's behalf.
   Reps. Frank and Stokes said the Reagan administration had been
supportive of Charny's bid for emigration, but they noted the
Soviets had the last word.
   ``It has been our experience that often they won't tell you a
thing,'' Frank said. ``But if you keep trying and you keep talking,
it does have an effect.''
   Frank and Mrs. Charny-Blank met with the Soviet counsel general
later Monday to discuss her father's case.
   Following the 30-minute meeting, Mrs. Charny-Blank said the
general counsel `` told me he wished he didn't have to discuss
these cases because it was not his decision (to make), but he would
send the information to Moscow as soon as possible.
   ``He didn't say this, but I think the situation makes them
uncomfortable,'' she said.
 
</TEXT>
