<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Walters     05-23 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Walters,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Envoy Says US Will Continue Seeking Iran Arms Embargo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABDEL-JALIL MUSTAFA</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American envoy Vernon Walters said Monday the
United States will continue pushing for an arms embargo on Iran
unless it accepts a U.N. resolution calling for a cease-fire in the
war with Iraq.
   Walters, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, spoke to
reporters before flying to Oman, the fifth stop on a tour that also
has taken him to Israel, Syria and Iraq.
   Omani officials would not comment on the purpose of the visit,
saying only that it would last two days and they would discuss
U.N.-related issues.
   In Kuwait, the ambassador praised the government's refusal to
free convicted terrorists despite pressures that included the
hijacking of a Kuwait Airways jumbo jet and the killing of two
passengers.
   The release of 17 jailed terrorists convicted of bombing the
U.S. and French embassies in 1983 was the hijackers' only demand
during the 16-day hijack last month. Kuwait refused to free them
and the hijackers surrendered the plane in Algiers in return for
safe conduct.
   Release of the 17 also has been the main demand of pro-Iranian
Shiite Mosleh`fxtremists holding nine American hostages in Lebanon.
   Walters met with Kuwait's emir, Sheik Jaber Ahmed Sabah; Crown
Prince Saad Abdullah Sabah, and Rashed Abdel-Aziz Rashed, minister
of state for Cabinet affairs.
   Asked whether he and the Kuwaitis discussed the hijacking and
several terrorist bombings in the sheikdom, he said: ``The United
States thinks that the Kuwaiti government demonstrated great
courage during the recent hijacking.
   ``We are not here to make a deal about terrorists and in no way
will the United States ever bring any kind of pressure on the
Kuwaiti government,'' he said in reference to the hostages in
Lebanon.
   Asked about Security Council measure of last July 20 calling for
a truce in the Iran-Iraq war, which began in SeptMm|er 1980,
Walters said Resolution 598 was ``unanimously approved and it's
binding on every member of the United Nations.''
   ``The United States will never abandon its support of 598 and
will work ... and urge our friends to support a second resolution
and an arms embargo on Iran'' if it does not accept the resolution,
he said.
   Iraq has said it will accept the resolution, but only if Iran
does.
   Iran says Iraq must be declared the aggressor before there can
be a cease-fire. Iraq invaded Iran in September 1980 after several
border skirmishes.
</TEXT>
