<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-US-China,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Denies Israel Helped Develop Missile China Sold to Saudis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin on Monday denied
an American newspaper report that Israel helped develop
surface-to-surface missiles that China sold to Saudi Arabia.
   The report in the Washington Post quoted U.S. commercial sources
and Saudi experts as saying Israeli scientists refined the guidance
system used in China's medium-range CSS-2 missile.
   It became known two months ago that Saudi Arabia had bought and
deployed CSS-2s, which have a range of 2,200 miles and could reach
any target in Israel.
   Washington did not known of the deal in advance and could not
persuade the Saudis to cancel it.
   Rabin said on Israel radio: ``Israelis were never partners in .
.. the transfer of technology or anything related to
ground-to-ground missiles to China. If anyone ... is looking for an
alibi about how the United States was taken by surprise by a
friendly nation, Saudi Arabia ... and is trying to pin the blame on
Israel, let him look elsewhere.''
   Saudi leaders told the United States they bought the missiles to
defend themselves against Iran and pledged not to launch them at
Israel.
   In March, an aide to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir hinted that
Israel might attack and destroy the missiles.
   Israel and China do not have diplomatic relations but there have
been reports of increasing agricultural and business links between
the two nations.
   An Israeli newspaper said last July a joint company had been
formed to help China with agricultural and technological projects.
The Sunday Times of London said Israel was sending technicians to
modernize Soviet tanks and heavy artillery used by the Chinese army.
