<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Sequoyah     05-23 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sequoyah,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TVA Investigates Second Nuclear Shutdown Since Sequoyah's Restart</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN GEORGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigative team is looking into
what caused Sequoyah Nuclear Plant's balky Unit 2 reactor to shut
down Monday for the second time in 3{ days.
   The reactor automatically shut down at 12:28 a.m. Monday because
of an instrument problem in its reactor coolant system, said Joe
Bynum, the Tennessee Valley Authority's assistant manager of
nuclear power.
   Bynum described the incident at the twin-reactor plant outside
Chattanooga as minor and said it represented no danger to plant
employees or the public.
   The shutdown was the second at Sequoyah since May 13, when Unit
2 became TVA's first reactor to go back on line since the federal
utility shut down its nuclear program in August 1985 because of
safety concerns.
   Unit 2 was approaching 75 percent power at the time of Monday's
shutdown _ about the same level it had reached on May 19 when a
water gauge problem caused the reactor to automatically power down.
   ``It was a relatively minor instrumentation problem that we can
correct,'' said Janice Brady, a plant spokeswoman. ``As we've said
repeatedly, because of the complexity of any nuclear plant, it's
not uncommon for a unit to automatically shut down.''
   The reactor had restarted Saturday after repairs and
adjustments, and plant workers were calibrating a transmitter that
provides readings on reactor water flow when Monday's shutdown
occurred.
   ``The plant's investigative team will be evaluating the cause of
the shutdown,'' Bynum said. ``The transmitters will be recalibrated
and Unit 2 will be returned to safe operation when all activities
are completed.''
</TEXT>
