<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Journalist, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0639,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Expel American Found In Restricted Military Zone</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with details on
Nicaraguan remarks about Moore. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American free-lance journalist was
arrested and expelled from Nicaragua last week, the U.S. State
Department said Monday. A Nicaraguan official said the man entered
a restricted military zone with fake identification documents.
   The source at Nicaragua's Interior Ministry identified the man
as Gary Moore, 38. He said Moore was working for a conservative
group and was arrested on Wednesday, May 18, at Laguna de Perlas, a
military zone on the Caribbean coast. He was deported to
neighboring Costa Rica either late Friday or Saturday.
   He said Moore ``entered military bases illegally. He also
falsified an accreditation from the presidency's International
Press Center.''
   When in custody, Moore said he worked for the National Forum
Foundation, a conservative group based in Washington, D.C. which
cooperates with the U.S.-supported rebel umbrella group called the
Nicaraguan Resistance, the source said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Moore was also found to be carrying a letter of recommendation
from Aristides Sanchez, a leader of the Nicaraguan Resistance, the
source said.
   Moore told The Associated Press in an interview Sunday in San
Jose, the capital of Costa Rica, that he was 38 years old, was from
Tupelo, Miss., and had worked for the Atlanta Constitution and the
Miami Herald.
   The Washington Times said Moore reported in a telephone
interview Sunday that he has contributed to the Wall Street Journal
and ABC News and had credentials from the National Forum Foundation.
   The Times quoted Moore as saying he was not mistreated while
under arrest.
   Moore told the AP said he was working on a documentary on
alleged human rights abuses by the leftist Sandinista government
when arrested.
   ``They confiscated all my material,'' he said, adding that he
was worried the Sandinista authorities would take reprisals against
the people he interviewed.
   Moore said the material consisted of videotapes, notes and
photographs.
   ``They (Sandinista security agents) said they would return it
all in about 15 days,'' he added.
   He confirmed that he was working for the National Forum
Foundation.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said
Moore was 37 years old and was taken into custody May 17 in
east-central Nicaragua, apparently for visiting a restricted zone
without permission.
</TEXT>
