<DOCNO> AP880523-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 2020EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FinancialAdvisers     05-23 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Financial Advisers,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SEC Suspends Investment Adviser</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission, in a
warning to the financial planning industry, said Monday it was
suspending a New Mexico investment adviser for failing to tell
clients she was earning commissions on the securities she
recommended.
   Without admitting or denying guilt, Nida Rae Ellis, vice
president of Westmark Financial Services, Albuquerque, N.M., agreed
to accept an SEC censure and a 120-day suspension from working as
an investment adviser or securities broker.
   In what SEC officials said was a ground-breaking case, the
commission found that beginning in June 1986, Ms. Ellis, who was
president of the New Mexico chapter of a national organization of
financial planners, violated federal laws by failing to tell
clients she would receive a commission when they bought into
limited real estate partnerships she was selling.
   She also failed to tell customers they did not have to go
through her to purchase the investment, the SEC said, and some of
the clients were not suited for investments of that level of
sophistication and risk.
   Officials said it was one of the first cases brought against an
investment adviser who is also registered as a securities broker.
   ``It is very important that when investment advisers are wearing
these various hats that they have to bear in mind they have a
fiduciary responsibility to their client,'' said Fred L. Chavez,
SEC assistant regional administrator in Denver.
   Kathryn B. McGrath, director of the SEC division of investment
management, said, ``Consumers seem to approach financial planners
as trusted advisers and financial planners seem to market their
services in that light: `You can come in to us and you don't have
to worry about those brokers or insurance agents who are trying to
sell you something.'
   ``However, many of them, if not most of them, are in fact just
like the broker or the insurance agent that's trying to sell
something,'' she said. ``We're saying they just have to make that
clear to the consumer so they can evaluate the advice with a grain
of salt.
   ``The action we brought hopefully will tell other financial
planners: We're dead serious. These are rules you're subject to and
you have to comply or else,'' she said.
   Ms. Ellis did not immediately return telephone messages left
Monday afternoon at Westmark's office in Albuquerque. A woman
answering the telephone at the office said no officers of the firm
were available to discuss the case.
   Hewitt Covington, counsel for the International Association of
Financial Planning in Atlanta, would not comment on the Westmark
order but said the association investigates complaints against any
of its 24,000 members and would reprimand or expel a member when
justified.
   Covington said many investment advisers work only for fees, much
as a lawyer or accountant, and accept no commissions on securities
they sell, while others are paid both.
   ``Life is full of conflicts of interest and it is not
necessarily nasty to sell something you're recommending, provided
you make the proper disclosure,'' he said.
   Investment advising is a fast-growing field. About 12,000 firms
are registered with the SEC as advisers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
