<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas, Contras Deadlocked Over Where to Negotiate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega extended a
cease-fire Monday so peace talks with U.S.-supported rebels can
continue, but disagreement persisted on the site for the next round.
   Ortega insisted that three days of talks scheduled to start
Wednesday be held in Managua but a statement issued in Miami by the
rebels, known as Contras, said the meeting should be in Sapoa, a
southern border post.
   Ortega told reporters his leftist Sandinista government decided
to extend the cease-fire by 30 days. The 60-day truce agreed upon
at the first meeting March 23 in Sapoa would have expired May 30.
   At a second meeting April 28-30, the first held in Managua, the
Sandinistas and Contras tried to negotiate a more permanent truce
in the 6{-year-old war, which Ortega says has killed 26,500 people
and caused $3 billion in damage.
   He said Monday the Sandinistas decided to extend the cease-fire
``in the interest of allowing negotiations to continue on a
definite truce,'' adding: ``We hope the counterrevolutionary
directorate contributes to this effort and acts in accordance with
the Nicaraguan people's wishes for peace.''
   Contra leaders said that, during the last negotiations in
Managua, the Sandinistas denied them free movement and the right to
meet with domestic opposition groups.
   In the statement Monday, the five Nicaraguan Resistance
directors said Sapoa and San Juan del Sur were proposed as meeting
sites by Defense Minister Humberto Ortega, the president's brother
and head of the government delegation.
   President Ortega said Monday the Contra delegates would be
allowed to meet in Managua with representatives of the Democratic
Coordinate, the principal opposition group; the opposition
newspaper La Prensa, and Roman Catholic bishops.
</TEXT>
