<1ST_LINE>u i AM-CannesAwards 1stLd-Writethru a0675 05-23 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cannes Awards, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0675,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Danish Film `Pelle the Conqueror' Wins Cannes Award</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 4 grafs to include more detail and CORRECT
spelling of Conqueror; picks up 4th `Through the'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CANNES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Danish movie ``Pelle the Conqueror''
won the Golden Palm award Monday night as the best film of the 41st
Cannes Film Festival.
   It was the first time the prize was given to a Danish director.
   French star Gerard Depardieu and Italian director Ettore Scola,
president of the 10-member jury, presented the Golden Palm to
director Bille August, who also wrote the screenplay.
   ``Pelle the Conqueror'' tells of 9-year-old Pelle, who moves to
Denmark from Sweden with his father Lasse at the end of the 19th
century and comes of age in a world of hardship and repression.
They work as cattlemen on a farm and are treated as slaves.
   Through the love of his father and the friendship of a farmhand,
Pelle develops a craving for freedom, rebels against his bosses and
leaves the farm.
   Max von Sydow plays Lasse and 13-year-old Pelle Hvenegaard makes
his debut as the boy.
   The prize for best actor went to Forest Whitaker of the United
States for his role as jazz great Charlie Parker in the movie
``Bird,'' directed by Clint Eastwood.
   Parker, whose bebop saxophone style influenced musicians around
the world, is well-known here even 32 years after his death.
   Whitaker, who also appeared in ``Platoon'' and ``The Color of
Money,'' was joined on stage by Eastwood, his director.
   Three performers shared the best actress award: Barbara Hershey,
an American; Linda Mvusi of South Africa, and 13-year-old Jodhi May
of Britain, who accepted the award for all three.
   They appeared in the British film ``A World Apart,'' which also
won the festival's Special Jury Grand Prize, regarded as a sort of
consolation prize given to the Golden Palm runner-up.
   ``A World Apart'' is based on the true story of Shawn Slovo,
whose parents were anti-apartheid activists. The film looks at
apartheid through the eyes of a sheltered 13-year-old girl (Miss
May) whose father flees and whose mother is imprisoned.
   Director Chris Menges accepted the award for his first film.
</TEXT>
