<HEAD>Hughes Institute Gives $30 Million to Improve College Science
Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Howard Hughes Medical Institute said
Monday it has awarded $30 million to 44 colleges and universities
to improve their undergraduate science education programs.
   Ten of the institutions are historically black colleges or
universities which received $7.2 million. Four are women's
colleges, which received $2.5 million.
   The grants ranged from $400,000 to $1.8 million.
   Purnell W. Choppin, president of the institute, said the aim was
``to strengthen the biological and related sciences in outstanding
liberal arts colleges and to increase the number of persons from
minority groups entering biomedical research careers.''
   The awards went to:
   Allegheny College, Pennsylvania, $900,000; Amherst College,
Massachusetts, $500,000; Bryn Mawr College, Pennsylvania, $800,000;
Bucknell University, Pennsylvania, $700,000; Carleton College,
Minnesota, $800,000; Clark College, Georgia, $700,000; Colorado
College, $800,000; Davidson College, North Carolina, $700,000;
DePauw University, Indiana, $600,000; Dillard University,
Louisiana, $400,000.
   Also, Earlham College, Indiana, $750,000; Franklin & Marshall
College, Pennsylvania, $400,000; Grinnell College, Iowa, $400,000;
Hampshire College, Massachusetts, $400,000; Hampton University,
Virginia, $600,000; Haverford College, Pennsylvania, $1.2 million;
Howard University, District of Columbia, $900,000; Kenyon College,
Ohio, $500,000.
   Also, Lincoln University, Pennsylvania, $700,000; Macalester
College, Minnesota, $800,000; Marlboro College, Vermont, $400,000;
Middlebury College, Vermont, $400,000; Millsaps College,
Mississippi, $600,000; Morehouse College, Georgia, $400,000; Morgan
State University, Maryland, $400,000; Mount Holyoke College,
Massachusetts, $400,000; Oakwood College, Alabama, $400,000.
   Also, Oberlin College, Ohio, $900,000; Occidental College,
California, $500,000; Pomona College, California, $500,000; Rhodes
College, Tennessee, $700,000; Saint Olaf College, Minnesota,
$600,000; Smith College, Massachusetts, $400,000; Swarthmore
College, Pennsylvania, $900,000; Tuskegee University, Alabama,
$900,000.
   And, Union College, New York, $900,000; Vassar College, New
York, $700,000; Wabash College, Indiana, $900,000; Wake Forest
University, North Carolina, $800,000; Wellesley College,
Massachusetts, $750,000; Wesleyan University, Connecticut, $1.2
million; Whitman College, Washington, $400,000; College of Wooster,
Ohio, $1 million; Xavier University of Louisiana, $1.8 million.
</TEXT>
