<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Politics     05-23 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Politics,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lords Kill Attempt to Alter Thatcher Tax Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House of Lords gave Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher an important victory Monday, killing an attempt by rebels
in her Conservative Party to amend tax legislation.
   The unelected upper chamber of Parliament voted 317-183 against
an amendment that would have mandated a closer link to a person's
ability to pay. It was the largest turnout in the Lords since 1971.
   Although the Lords and House of Commons still may consider other
amendments, the government's victory ensures passage of the major
principles of the tax legislation, which was nearly defeated by a
Commons revolt in April.
   Lord Chelwood, leader of the rebellion in the Lords, said during
debate on his amendment that the Thatcher government proposals
``are a lot less fair'' than the current system.
   ``They have very little support,'' said Chelwood, a former
Conservative member of the Commons. ``They are extremely unpopular
in the country.''
   He condemned suggestions by some peers that the chamber had no
right to challenge legislation passed by the Commons. The Lords
does not have the power to interfere with taxation, but some lords
said it was not clear whether the poll tax was an issue of taxation
or local authority.
   ``We are a revising chamber, seeking to exercise restraint on
the otherwise unfettered power of the Commons,'' Chelwood said.
``If we cannot `tamper' with legislation, we really have nothing to
do.''
   Under the so-called poll tax, which critics say is unfair to the
poor, property taxes are levied on each adult rather than on houses
or apartments. Although the poor will get rebates, they must pay a
tax of at least 5 percent.
   The legislation, a clause in the bill on local government
finances, is central to Mrs. Thatcher's legislative program for
curbing expenditures by local councils, most of which are
controlled by the opposition Labor Party.
   In the Lords on Monday, many peers echoed government assertions
that people would be less likely to elect free-spending councils if
they felt the pinch of the local tax bill.
   A rebel amendment was defeated 320-295 a month ago in the
Commons, where the Conservatives have a majority of 101.
</TEXT>
