<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ArmsTreaty 3rdLd-Writethru a0705 05-23 0933</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arms Treaty, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0705,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Kills Challenges to INF Pact as Dole Warns of
`Embarrassment'</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS lead and INSERTS 2 grafs after 6 graf pvs bgng, `Later,
the,' to UPDATE with latest vote</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Monday easily rejected three new
Republican challenges to the medium-range missile treaty and Senate
Minority Leader Bob Dole said ``it would be an embarrassment'' to
President Reagan if the pact isn't ratified before Reagan goes to
Moscow next weekend.
   The Kansas Republican told his colleagues, ``the ball is in our
court, the Republicans' court'' as the Democratic-controlled
chamber began a second week of work on the Intermediate-range
Nuclear Forces treaty.
   Later, Secretary of State George Shultz met with Republican
senators and urged approval of the pact before the summit.
   ``Here is a treaty that has been examined in more detail than
any arms control treaty in history, by far,'' Shultz said after the
Capitol Hill session. ``There is a time to inquire and there is
also a time to vote. ... It would be a good thing to have it.''
   The first decision came when the Senate voted 81-13 to kill an
amendment by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C. It would have prevented the
treaty from taking effect until Reagan reassures Congress about the
accuracy of the number of triple-warhead Soviet SS-20 missiles
which will be destroyed.
   Later, the chamber killed, on a 68-26 vote, an amendment by Sen.
Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo., that would have required a change in the
treaty's text to eliminate what he said was a loophole that would
have permitted construction of some Soviet missiles.
   Then, the Senate rejected, 81-5, an amendment by Sen. Gordon
Humphrey, R-N.H., that would have delayed the INF pact until the
two nations agreed on a more far-reaching pact providing 50 percent
cuts in each side's large arsenals of long-range atomic weapons.
   Humphrey said, ``We ought to wait until we see the whole
picture'' before approving any pact, but critics termed it a
``killer amendment'' designed to derail the treaty.
   Before the votes, Dole told his colleagues again the Senate
should approve the pact before Reagan meets Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev in Moscow from May 29 to June 2.
   Helms and other conservatives have blocked action by the full
Senate, delaying the ratification that even critics say is assured.
Ratification requires a two-thirds majority voting in favor.
   ``I'm still convinced it would be an embarrassment to the
president of the United States to sit down with Mr. Gorbachev later
this week without the Senate have taken action to consent to
ratification of the treaty,'' Dole said.
   However, he added, ``We have some serious issues that, in some
cases, may take several hours or days.''
   The treaty, signed Dec. 8 by Reagan and Gorbachev, requires
destruction within three years of all atomic missiles with ranges
between 300 miles and 3,400 miles. For the Soviets, that includes
400 deployed SS-20s and another 250 stockpiled SS-20s.
   The United States has accepted the Soviet statement of 650
SS-20s, even though Defense Intelligence Agency analysts say the
Soviets may be hiding more than 250 of the weapons.
   ``We were snookered,'' Helms said. ``The estimates are that the
Soviets have 300 to 600 more than the 650 thy admit to having.''
   ``This is a gut issue,'' Helms said. ``It could mean the
difference between survival and destruction for Europe, or a good
part of it.''
   But Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., noted that Reagan administration
officials have rejected Helms' claim, although Lugar conceded it is
difficult to prove that no SS-20s are hidden.
   ``It is akin to proving the Loch Ness monster doesn't exist,''
Lugar said.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., said that even if SS-20s are
hidden, they could not be deployed without violating the treaty and
their ``viability would degrade quickly'' without testing.
   Helms' amendment ``is not needed, it is unnecessary and it would
hamper our efforts to get the INF treaty in place,'' Cranston said.
   Wallop's proposal affected a part of the treaty which, he said,
was written in such a way as to permit production of Soviet SS-25
missiles that would be interchangeable with stages in the SS-20.
The SS-25 is not banned.
   ``This amendment just is to make certain that we do what we set
out to do,'' Wallop said, explaining that he wanted to make sure
that no SS-25s were produced that would be interchangeable with the
SS-20.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, agreed with Wallop that the treaty's language
``is awkwardly written.''
   But Pell said the amendment wasn't needed because if the Soviets
produce SS-25 stages which are interchangeable with the SS-20, they
would be in violation of the pact.
   Among the issues remaining to be settled is an amendment, backed
by the Democratic majority, which would require Senate approval
before any future administration could change how the United States
interprets the INF pact.
   That amendment is the result of a fight between Reagan and
Democrats over the U.S. interpretation of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile pact.
   Reagan asserts that his administration unilaterally can change
how the treaty is interpreted, a view disputed by congressional
Democrats. The amendment banning any INF reinterpretation was added
by the Senate Foreign Relations Committee over the opposition of
Republicans.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., said Monday the
treaty ``should be nailed in. It shouldn't be subject to
reinterpretation.''
   He said, ``I'm certainly not interested in any erosion of the
Senate's constitutional role in treaty making. ... I don't propose
to give the store away.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
