<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 2043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Jackson-Threat     05-23 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Threat,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Set for Couple Charged in Threat to Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who says he was raised to be a racist
pleaded innocent Monday to a federal charge of threatening to kill
black Democratic presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson.
   Londell Williams, 30, was accused in an indictment last week of
threatening Jackson's life. The indictment also accused him and his
wife, Tammy, 27, of possessing an unregistered automatic rifle and
threatening and intimidating a government informant.
   At their arraignment before U.S. District Judge Edward L.
Filippine, the Williamses pleaded innocent to the charges, but said
nothing in their own behalf.
   In response to questions to determine their competency, both
told the judge they do not have mental problems and do not abuse
alcohol or drugs.
   They and their lawyers declined comment following the court
appearance.
   Filippine gave lawyers on both sides 11 days to file
post-arraignment motions. The judge set a trial date of July 18.
   The Williamses were arrested May 13 at their apartment in
Washington, Mo., about 50 miles west of St. Louis. They had lived
there about a year since moving from a farm in the Ozark hills of
southwest Missouri.
   The U.S. attorney said initially that evidence _ including a
secretly recorded conversation between Londell Williams and the
informant _ indicated that a white supremacist organization called
the Covenant, Sword and the Arm of the Lord was conspiring to kill
Jackson June 21 or July 4. Williams said Jackson was targeted
because he was ``getting too close to being president of the United
States.''
   The government's complaint, which preceded Thursday's
indictment, cited a loaded AR-15 rifle that, with help from an
informant, was found by sheriff's deputies in a wooded area of
Franklin County.
   Near the rifle was a bag containing a post card addressed to
Londell Williams and maps, one of which bore his fingerprints, the
complaint said.
   Authorities charged the Williamses with threatening the
informant during a meeting on May 11.
   The indictment made no mention of white supremacists or a
conspiracy. The FBI has said that it has been unable to find any
evidence that the Williamses belonged to CSA or any other white
supremacist organization.
   Since their arrests, the Williamses have denied that they are
members of such groups. Londell Williams also has denied, in media
interviews, having planned to kill Jackson.
   Williams has said, however, that he has ``prejudices ... against
anything that isn't white.''
   ``That's how I've been raised,'' he said.
</TEXT>
