<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Guatemala-Quakes     05-23 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guatemala-Quakes,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quakes Shut Downs Businesses, Schools In Guatemala</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONZO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of small and moderate earthquakes
that began over the weekend forced schools, government offices and
many businesses to close Monday in this capital city of 2 million
people.
   The government ordered the one-day shutdown for Guatemala City
and the surrounding area, except for hospitals and other essential
services, the Defense Ministry and the National Emergency
Commission.
   Some stores opened, along with banks and La Aurora Airport
operated normally. It is near a geological fault on the south side
of the city, the epicenter of the quakes.
   The National Seismological Institute said at least 50 tremors
measuring from 2.1 to 4.0 on the open-ended Richter scale had
shaken the capital since midnight Friday.
   Many people living near the fault zone have been sleeping
outside their homes. A few old walls cracked but no major damage
was reported, according to news reports.
   On Feb. 4, 1976, an earthquake measuring 6 on the Richter scale
devastated Guatemala City and killed more than 22,000 people.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by ground motion recorded on a seismograph.
A quake registering 2 is the smallest normally felt by humans. One
of magnitude 4 can cause moderate damage.
   Communications Minister Mario Lopez described the forced
shutdown Monday as a precaution ``because of the situation caused
by the constant and continuous earthquakes.''
   He said the decision was made ``to avoid any (traffic)
congestion and so that families can be together in their homes.''
</TEXT>
