<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0677,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Syria Rejects Deal With Iran; 13 Killed In 18th Day of Fighting</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 6 grafs to include Christian fighting. Picks up
5th graf pvs, Monday's casualties ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syria called it ``out of the question''
for Iran to join any military force sent into the south Beirut
slums to end 18 days of fighting between Shiite Moslem factions,
Lebanese officials reported Monday.
   They said Syria's rejection of an Iranian proposal to join such
a force was conveyed by Syria's military intelligence chief in
Beirut, Brig. Gen. Ali Hammoud, at a six-hour meeting with Iran's
deputy foreign minister, Hossein Sheikholeslam, that ended at dawn
Monday.
   Mortar and howitzer fire pounded the 16 square miles of
tin-roofed shanties and narrow alleyways Monday, killing 13 people
and wounding 78, police said.
   In east Beirut, President Amin Gemayel's Phalange fighters and
men of the main Christian militia Lebanese Forces fought with
machine guns and hand grenades Monday night for control of the
capital's Christian sector.
   Police said five combatants were wounded in the Sin el-Fil
district, including at least one Phalangist and two from the
Lebanese Forces. They said fighting began after Lebanese Forces
gunmen wounded Nabil Kahhaleh, Phalangist commander in the
district, and that it abated at about 11 p.m.
   Representatives of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of
God, and the pro-Syrian Amal militia also attended the overnight
meeting between Syria and Iran.
   Monday's casualties raised the toll to 279 killed and 951
wounded since battles for control of the slums broke out May 6
between Hezbollah and Amal.
   The Lebanese officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the dispute over who would serve in a military force in the
slums again delayed Syria's plans to try to end the fighting.
   Most of the 18 foreign hostages in Lebanon, including nine
Americans, are believed held by Hezbollah-affiliated kidnappers in
the embattled enclave.
   Two Beirut dailies, the independent An-Nahar and leftist
As-Safir, reported that Hammoud and Amal representatives insisted
that the Syrian army take charge of security in south Beirut.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, endorsed the
demand.
   ``There is no other alternative. The Syrian army has to go in to
stop the bloodletting and end the plight of the population,'' Hoss
said in a statement.
   An-Nahar quoted the Iranian deputy foreign minister as saying
Iran would approve a Syrian military intervention in the slums only
if the hostage situation was resolved ``in a way that serves the
objective for which they were kidnapped.''
   Sheikholeslam did not elaborate, but An-Nahar quoted him as
saying the hostages were a ``vital issue for Iran.''
   Iran also demanded guarantees that Hezbollah will be free to
continue political activity in the slums after the Syrian
deployment.
   Syria has kept massed around the slums about 7,500 troops, 100
tanks and 400 armored vehicles since Hezbollah overran Amal
strongholds to seize control of 90 percent of the urban
battleground.
   Syria is Iran's main Arab ally in the 7{-year-old Persian Gulf
war against Iraq, long a rival of Syria in Arab politics.
   But Hezbollah's move to dominate Lebanon's 1.2 million Shiites
has strained that alliance.
   The Syrians consider neighboring Lebanon to be vital to their
security.
   Amal spokesmen have complained that delaying Syrian deployment
will only prolong suffering of thousands of civilians trapped in
the slums.
   Police have said about 70 percent of the slums' estimated
250,000 residents have fled to safer areas.
</TEXT>
