<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mainly Rain In Plains, Mississippi and Ohio Valleys</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain and scattered thunderstorms rolled across the central High
Plains through the middle Mississippi and Ohio valleys Monday, with
strong thunderstorms bringing 1-inch hailstones to the Deep South.
   Quarter-size hail fell at Centreville and Brent, Ala., Monday
afternoon and dime-size hail was reported at Bay Springs, Miss.
   Thunderstorms also were developing over the lower Ohio Valley,
accompanied by gusty winds and heavy rain. Heavy rain also was
reported with thunderstorms over northern Indiana.
   Thunderstorms were developing over the mountains of central
Pennsylvania into northern Virginia.
   Skies were mostly cloudy across the Southeast states, with
showers and thunderstorms developing off the west coast of Florida
and scattered over northeastern North Carolina. Temperatures were
in the 80s to low 90s.
   Skies were also mostly cloudy over New England with showers over
northern Maine. Afternoon temperatures were in the 70s and 80s.
   Partly cloudy skies prevailed from the Continental Divide west
to the Pacific Coast. The Pacific Northwest had readings in the 50s
and 60s, and the desert Southwest reported temperatures in the
middle 90s.
   Skies were mostly clear from the northern Rockies through the
northern Plains into the upper Mississippi valley and northern
Great Lakes, with temperatures in the 70s and 80s.
   The low for the nation Monday was 23 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 53
degrees at Whidbey Island, Wash.; Crescent City and Arcata, Calif.;
and Glenview, Ill., to 101 degrees at Palm Springs and Needles,
Calif.
   The national weather forecast for Tuesday called for rain and
thunderstorms scattered from the central Gulf Coast through the
Tennessee and Ohio valleys, the southern and middle Atlantic Coast
states into New England. Thunderstorms will be most numerous across
the eastern lower Ohio Valley into central Pennsylvania. Mostly
sunny skies will prevail from the Great Lakes and Mississippi
Valley west to the Pacific Coast.
   High temperatures will be in the 70s or 80s across much of the
country; in the 60s from the upper Great Lakes into the northern
half of New England; in the 90s across the Rio Grande Valley of
Texas and across much of Florida, and between 100 and 110 degrees
across much of the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
