<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SmallKidnapping 4thLd-Writethru a0699 05-23 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Small Kidnapping, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0699,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecution: Edwards Intended Kidnap Victim Small to Die</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to add quotes and background and to tighten.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man ``who made greed his god'' was
convicted Monday of kidnapping and murdering a prominent
businessman who was buried alive and suffocated in a botched $1
million ransom scheme.
   Jurors deliberated only about an hour following a week-long
trial before finding Daniel Edwards, 31, of Bourbonnais guilty of
murdering Kankakee businessman Stephen Small.
   Edwards stood quietly and showed no emotion as the verdict was
read in the courtroom of Kankakee County Circuit Judge John Michela.
   A second phase of the trial will determine whether Edwards is
sentenced to death.
   Small, 40, was the great-grandson of former Illinois Gov. Len
Small and was a member of a family with major media holdings. He
was the former vice president of Mid America Media, a group that
owned radio and cable television stations, before the company was
was sold in 1986.
   Edwards' live-in girlfriend, Nancy D. Rish, 26, also was charged
in the scheme and is awaiting trial.
   Earlier Monday, prosecutors said Edwards planned Small's
kidnapping because he craved money.
   Edwards was ``a man who made greed his god,'' said Frank
Nowicki, an assistant Illinois attorney general.
   ``All Danny boy had to do to cash in on that jackpot was put
Stephen Small ... in a box,'' said Michael Ficaro, another
assistant Illinois attorney general, slamming his hand on the top
of the coffin-sized crate in which Small died.
   ``I never saw anybody come out of a grave. You bury people who
are dead in a grave,'' Ficaro said.
   But Edwards' attorney, Sheldon Reagan, argued that Small was
buried with candy bars, lights, and water and hadn't been harmed
before being put in the box. He said a faulty air supply system
caused Small's death.
   ``It's an accident but it's not an intentional murder,'' said
Reagan, who suggested someone else abducted Small. ``I know you
want to convict somebody, but certainly not for murder.''
   Small was lured from his restored Victorian home with a
telephone call after midnight Sept. 2, 1987. His family received
clear instructions for delivering the ransom.
   Two days later, police found Small's body in the box, buried
under 3 feet of sand 13 miles southeast of Kankakee.
   The jury, picked in northern Illinois' Winnebago County because
of publicity the case received locally, heard a tape of Small's
voice relaying the ransom demand to his family, and heard witnesses
who saw Edwards building the box.
   Perhaps the most chilling evidence was the tape-recorded voice
of Small on the telephone, telling his wife, Nancy: ``It's no joke.
I'm inside ... a box. Grave.''
   ``It's under a couple of feet of sand or something, like
underground,'' Small told his wife. ``I want you to get $1 million.
God only knows how you're going to do that. He says there's 48
hours of air for me.''
   Prosecutors called the tapes the voice from the grave.
   Reagan, however, told jurors that no one had identified the
voice on the ransom tapes as Edwards' voice, and said ``the facts
don't tell you'' that Edwards was the kidnapper.
   Throughout the trial, the box was on display in the courtroom.
   ``Take a good long look,'' said Ficaro. ``Danny Edwards' greed
for the big score drove those nails, dug that grave and buried
Stephen Small alive.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
