<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 2108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Suicide     05-23 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Suicide,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>^Wanted French Criminal Succo Dies in Italian Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VICENZA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian-born Roberto Succo, one of
France's most wanted criminals as a multiple killer and a robber,
was found dead in his prison cell Monday in an apparent suicide.
   Succo, 26, who was accused in a string of murders and robberies
in France, Switzerland and Italy, was discovered with his head in a
plastic bag, said Vicenza Police Chief Piernicola Silvis.
   A magistrate was investigating the death, Silvis said.
   Last week, an Italian judge declared Succo mentally incapable of
understanding or taking part in his defense. The judge referred to
psychologists who found Succo schizophrenic and a danger to society.
   Succo was arrested Feb. 28 near Treviso, his native town in
northern Italy, on charges of illegal possession of a gun and using
false documents.
   Two days later, he bolted from his guards in the courtyard of
the Treviso jail and climbed on the roof. He stripped to his
underwear and hurled bricks at cars before he fell after dangling
from a roof cable. Succo, slightly injured, was transferred to the
more secure jail in Vicenza.
   Succo escaped in May 1986 while on furlough from a psychiatric
prison in Reggio Emilia, where he was held after killing his mother
and father in 1981.
   He fled to France, where he was accused of killing two
policemen, a doctor and two women.
   Succo was charged in the January 1988 slaying of police
inspector Michel Morandin in Toulon, where he had lived for a year
among prostitutes and sailors and was known as ``Andre.''
   He was also charged with killing a police official, Michel
Castillo, in Chambery in April 1987. Other victims included a
doctor in Aix les Bains and two women near d'Annecy, all killed in
1987.
   After Morandin's slaying, Succo escaped to Switzerland, where he
was accused of armed robbery and hostage-taking.
   Police said that when he was arrested after coming to Italy from
Switzerland, he Treviso. At the time of his arrest, Succo was
traveling in a stolen car. In the car, police found a handgun
allegedly used in the slaying of one of the French policemen.
   Both France and Switzerland approached Italy about possible
extradition, but no decision had been announced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
