<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Election     05-23 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Election,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Claims Fraud in Local Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition National Action Party
began protest actions Monday after complaining that preliminary
results were rigged in a special mayoral election in the northern
steel-producing city of Monclova.
   The party _ known as the PAN _ planned protest meetings this
week in Monclova and other cities throughout the northern border
state of Coahuila state to pressure the state legislature to reject
the figures, said Juan Antonio Garcia Villa, the PAN president in
Monclova.
   A special election commission said over the weekend that Benigno
Franco Colorado, candidate of the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, won the May 8 election by 294 votes.
More than 23,000 ballots were cast.
   The state legislature has not certified the results.
   The PAN says its candidate, Carlos Paez Falcon, won by 448 votes.
   It says it has copies of all the voting results and can prove
that the figures from seven precincts were altered.
   ``Because of this intent of fraud, the PAN is calling on its
supporters to carry out legitimate protests,'' Garcia said by
telephone Monday.
   Manuel Clouthier, PAN's presidential candidate in July 6 general
elections, broke off campaigning in northern Tamaulipas state to
head Monday for Monclova. Garcia said Clouthier will announce
``civil disobedience tactics'' at a rally there.
   Garcia said PAN supporters already were marching in protest near
the international bridges at Ciudad Acuna and Piedras Negras, just
south of the Texas border.
   The PRI won the Coahuila gubernatorial race and 37 of the 38
mayoralties at stake in regular elections on Oct. 25, 1987.
   But the state legislature, citing voting irregularities and
violence, annulled the Monclova elections and set special elections
for May 8.
   The PRI and the PAN have fought for nine years for control of
Monclova, a city of 300,000 people about 200 miles south of the
Texas border at Eagle Pass.
   Its most recent administration was controlled by a bilateral
commission, appointed after neither party could prove it won the
1984 mayoral race.
</TEXT>
