<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Daronco'sCases     05-23 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Daronco's Cases,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slain Jurist Presided Over Famous Divorce Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Fatal Decision, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slain U.S. District Judge Richard
Daronco earlier in his career issued a landmark divorce ruling and
presided over two highly publicized murder trials.
   As a state Supreme Court justice in 1982, Daronco ruled that a
woman who worked to pay her husband's way through medical school
should be awarded a financial share of her husband's medical
practice in the couple's divorce.
   In 1978, as a Westchester County Court judge, Daronco presided
over the trial of Richard Herrin, a Yale University student who was
convicted of manslaughter in the hammer slaying of ex-girlfriend
and fellow Yale student Bonnie Garland as she slept in her
Scarsdale home.
   Calling Herrin's act ``needless, heartless, cruel and brutal,''
Daronco sentenced Herrin to up to 25 years in prison.
   Earlier that year, Daronco presided over the trial of two
Connecticut men charged with the brutal killing of two Lewisboro
housewives and sentenced both men to 25-years-to-life prison terms.
   Daronco, 56, was gunned down at his home in suburban Pelham
Saturday by a former New York City policeman after ruling against
the killer's daughter in a sexual harassment and job discrimination
lawsuit, authorities said. The killer, Charles L. Koster, 67, of
Bath, Pa., committed suicide, police said.
</TEXT>
