<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Ferry Fire, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0730,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Channel Ferry Fire Leaves One Missing; Dangerous Cargo May Be
Aboard</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 7 grafs SUB for grafs 7-10 pvs, The blaze ... the way,
UPDATING with helicopter help, ship power out, other detail. Picks
up 11th graf pvs, On March ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire broke out Monday night on a Sealink freight
ferry with 75 people aboard in the English Channel, and one person
was reported missing and another injured, said the coast guard in
Dover.
   The ferry, the 5,088-ton Seafreight Freeway, told the French
coast guard at Cap Gris Nez that the blaze was under control, the
British domestic news agency Press Association said. However, there
was concern among nearby rescue craft since the ferry was
reportedly carrying dangerous cargo, it said.
   No further information was available on the dangerous cargo
report.
   A Dover coast guard spokeswoman said the ferry, sailing from
Dover, southeast England, to Zeebrugge, Belgium, carried 43
passengers and 32 crew.
   It was about 28 miles off Ramsgate on the southeast tip of
England, the British Broadcasting Corp. said.
   Sealink recently restored channel service after a walkout by
seamen supporting the continuing strike against P and O European
Ferries Ltd.
   Staff at hospitals in Canterbury and Margate went on alert.
Police said all power on the ship had been lost and the rescue was
taking place in darkness.
   The blaze was believed to have broken out in the engine room of
the ferry about two hours after it sailed out of Dover at 7:30 p.m.
(2:30 p.m. EDT) bound for Zeebrugge, Press Association said.
   A truck driver and a crew member were originally reported
missing but the driver was later accounted for, it added.
   Helicopter pilot Jonathon Noble said a Wessex helicopter from
Manston was the first on the scene and its crew airlifted a badly
burned seaman straight to the Kent and Canterbury Hospital.
   A Sea King helicopter from Coltishall flew firemen with
breathing apparatus out to the ferry and was quickly joined by a
third helicopter, this time from Lee on Solent.
   Belgian helicopters stood by in Ostend to airlift passengers and
crew from the ship if asked, but there were no plans for such an
operation.
   Ramsgate and Dover lifeboats were launched, the BBC said. The
Pride of Kent, a P and O ferry, was also reported on the way.
   On March 6, 1987, 193 people died when the British channel ferry
Herald of Free Enterprise capsized in the North Sea off Zeebrugge.
Water poured through the bow doors, which had been left open as the
vessel pulled out of Zeebrugge.
   The Seafreight Freeway ferry, built in 1981 and capable of
carrying around 70 trucks, has been on charter to Sealink since
mid-1986, operating between Dover and Zeebrugge and Dover and
Dunkirk.
   ``Information is a bit sketchy at the moment because the ship's
radio is tied up with emergency messages,'' Sealink spokesman Brian
Kelly said.
   ``The urgent thing is to ensure that the drivers and the crew
are not in danger.''
</TEXT>
