<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ThruwayFalcons     05-23 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thruway Falcons,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Expert: First Peregrine Falcons Nesting Along Hudson in 30 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TARRYTOWN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A heavily traveled bridge near New York
City is believed to contain the first pair of peregrine falcons
discovered nesting along the Hudson River in three decades, an
animal expert said Monday.
   The falcons' behavior indicates they are tending to nestlings in
a box placed by conservationists in a tower of the Tappan Zee
Bridge along the New York Thruway, said Dennis Mildner, curator of
Museum of the Hudson Highlands in Cornwall-on-Hudson.
   The state Department of Environmental Conservation and Cornell
University have been trying since 1974 to reestablish peregrine
falcons by releasing more than 160 young peregrines raised in
captivity in the hopes they will mate.
   Conservationists know of at least 10 mating pairs in New York
state, including two pairs on other New York City bridges.
   Mildner said people and pesticides have disturbed the
peregrines' traditional nesting areas in cliffs above the Hudson,
but that nesting perches in bridges afford a clifflike environment.
</TEXT>
