<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ArchitecturePrize     05-23 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Architecture Prize,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Architects From Brazil And United States Honored</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Architects Oscar Niemeyer of Brazil and Gordon
Bunshaft of the United States have been named 1988 co-winners of
the Pirtzker Architecture Prize, sponsored by the Hyatt Foundation.
   The prize was established by the Pritzker family of Chicago in
1979 to honor a creative endeavor not included in the Nobel prizes.
It includes a $100,000 grant, formal citation certificates and
medallions.
   Niemeyer, 80, and Bunshaft, 79, will share the grant equally,
the foundation said in a statement.
   Niemeyer, a native of Rio de Janiero, is perhaps best known for
his designs for most of the public buildings in Brasilia, the
Brazilian capital. He also designed, in collaboration with the late
French architect Le Courbusier, the United Nations headquarters in
New York City.
   A communist since 1945, Niemeyer was the 1962 recipient of the
Lenin Peace Prize.
   Bunshaft was born in Buffalo, N.Y., and educated at
Massachusetts Institute of Technology. In his work for the firm of
Skidmore, Owings and Merrill, Bunshaft became famous for his
skyscrapers of the 1950s, many in New York City.
   Bunshaft's 24-story Lever House there, finished in 1953, is the
most contemporary building to be granted landmark status by the New
York Landmarks Conservancy.
   Other New York buildings designed by Bunshaft include the
60-story Chase Manhattan Bank, the Union Carbide Building and the
original PepsiCo building.
   He also designed the Hirshhorn Museum in Washington, D.C., the
Lyndon Baines Johnson Library in Texas and the Albright-Knox Art
Gallery in his native Buffalo, as well as buildings in Belgium,
Turkey and Saudi Arabia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
