<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Debate     05-23 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Debate,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Far Right Walk Out on First South African Joint Debates in
Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White and non-white members of
Parliament took part in joint debates Monday for the first time.
Members of the far-right Conservative Party walked out in protest.
   The party said in a statement the members wanted to ``record
anew our deep-felt rejection of being co-governed by other
population groups.''
   The debates dealt with the budgets of South Africa's four
provinces and were conducted in the provincial capitals by members
of the relevant committees in the white, Asian and mixed-race
chambers of Parliament.
   The government, in revising parliamentary rules to allow the
joint debates, stopped short of permitting joint voting on any
issues.
   ``Until we can debate and vote together, this meeting today is
an historical farce,'' said Marius Barnard of the anti-apartheid
Progressive Federal Party.
   The Asian and mixed-race chambers were created in 1984 under a
new constitution which continued to exclude the black majority from
national affairs.
   The white chamber, dominated by President P.W. Botha's National
Party, is able to get its way on all major legislative issues. The
Conservative Party, with 23 of 178 seats, is the largest white
opposition party.
   In Pretoria, where the Transvaal Province budget was debated,
several legislators objected to stringent security checks conducted
as they entered the meeting hall.
   ``We cannot allow ourselves to be subjected to such demeaning
checks,'' said Yusuf Seedat of the Asian chamber after he and other
lawmakers were ordered to empty their pockets, offer their
briefcases to be searched, and produce their parliamentary identity
cards.
   During the debates, government officials pledged to expand black
hospital facilities, suggested that new laws would be enacted to
control black squatters, and reported that the first ``recreation
resort'' for blacks in the Orange Free State would be ready next
year.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
