<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Awad 1stLd-Writethru a0602 05-23 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Awad, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0602,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Reserves Decision on Deportation of Arab-American</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf, ``Asked what ... with 1 graf to
INCLUDE Awad is Christian.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>With AM-Israel, Bjt
^By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court heard an appeal Monday by an
Arab-American advocate of civil disobedience who asked the judges
to revoke a deportation order against him.
   He threatened to convert to Judaism and return to Israel if the
order stands.
   Mubarak Awad, 44, was ordered deported by Israeli officials on
May 6. They said he had played a leading role in the 24-week Arab
uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The three-judge panel reserved decision after Monday's appeal
hearing, but did not set a date for its ruling. The decision is
expected to have far-reaching consequences for the legal status of
the 130,000 Arabs living in Israeli-annexed east Jerusalem.
   During the three-hour hearing, lawyers for both sides focused on
Awad's legal status under Israeli immigration law.
   The court must consider whether the Jerusalem-born Awad and
other east Jerusalem Arabs enjoy an irrevocable status as permanent
residents, or if they can lose their rights under certain
conditions, such as leaving the country for more than seven years.
   Nili Arad, an attorney for the Interior Ministry, argued that
Awad should be deported because he forfeited his right to permanent
residency by leaving Israel for 13 years, from 1970 to 1983, and by
accepting U.S. citizenship. Awad lived in Wapakoneta, Ohio, while
maintaining a home in Jerusalem.
   Awad's attorney, Avraham Gal, said Israel had no right to deport
his client because, as a longtime resident of Arab east Jerusalem,
Awad enjoys a special status that cannot be revoked.
   Israel annexed east Jerusalem after the 1967 Middle East war,
but never defined the legal status of the sector's Arab residents,
most of whom rejected offers of Israeli citizenship.
   Ms. Arad argued that since the annexation, the Interior Ministry
in practice has applied the rules of permanent residency to
citizens of east Jerusalem, and that Awad falls into that category.
   If the court rules in favor of the Interior Ministry, ``all east
Jerusalemites are in danger of mass transfer,'' said Jonathan
Kuttab, a West Bank lawyer also representing the Arab-American.
   ``Those who grant residency permits can also take them away,''
he added.
   Awad, who has been jailed since May 5, looked pale when he
entered the packed courtroom wearing a beige suit and a
blue-striped shirt. He kissed his American-born wife, Nancy Nye,
and talked to reporters during recess.
   Awad rejected government allegations that he had helped incite
often violent anti-Israeli protests. He said he stood by his
advocacy of non-violent action such as tax boycotts and strikes.
   He also said Israel's effort to deport him has helped popularize
his ideas. ``My ideas have caught, thanks to the Israelis who put
so much pressure on me,'' Awad said.
   However, Awad seems fairly isolated in the Palestinian
community, and underground leaders have not mentioned his case in
the leaflets they distribute in the occupied lands.
   Asked what he would do if deported, he told reporters he had the
option of converting to Judaism and coming back under Israel's Law
of Return, which grants automatic Israeli citizenship to all Jews.
Awad is Christian.
   Awad's troubles began in August when the Interior Ministry
refused to renew his identity card, issued by Israel in 1968. Since
his return from the United States in 1983, Awad had stayed in
Israel on tourist visas stamped into his U.S. passport, but in
November the Interior Ministry refused to renew that permit.
</TEXT>
