<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Religion     05-23 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Religion,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules Women Should be on Religious Panel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday overruled a
decision by the Tel Aviv City Council barring women from voting for
the city's chief rabbi.
   The court ordered the council to hold new elections for its 10
delegates to the 30-member body which will elect the chief rabbi
and warned it not to discriminate against women.
   The city's Labor Party faction last year elected two women,
Haviva Avigai and Lili Menachem, to the elective body. The council
nullified the choices under pressure from orthodox leaders, who
said religious law forbade women from electing rabbis.
   Rabbi Yisrael Lau, Mayor Shlomo Lahat's choice for the vacant
post, said at the time he would not submit his candidacy if women
were on the elective body.
   Ms. Avigai hailed Monday's decision. ``The Supreme Court has
again shown it is the guardian of human rights and that women have
equal rights,'' she said in a telephone interview.
   Lau told Israel Television: ``We have a problem. It has been
customary to choose someone to fill a traditional post in a
traditional way.''
   Tel Aviv has been without an Ashkenazi chief rabbi, one
representing Jews of European descent, since late 1986 because of
squabbling over female representation.
   Monday's decision was the latest in a series which have pitted
the secular law of the land against Israel's religious
establishment.
   The court also went against the rabbis' wishes last week, when
it upheld the appointment of Lea Shakdiel, the first woman
nominated to serve on a religious council in Israel.
</TEXT>
