<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Italy-Anti-Semitism     05-23 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Anti-Semitism,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic Bishops Deplore Anti-Semitism in Italy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's Roman Catholic bishops on Monday deplored
recent demonstrations of anti-Semitism that have apparently
occurred in reaction to Israel's policies toward Palestinians.
   The statement by the Italian Bishops' Conference followed
charges by Jewish leaders that the Italian press, including Roman
Catholic publications, have helped incite anti-Semitism through
their reporting on the Middle East conflict.
   The bishops' statement, published in the Vatican daily
L'Osservatore Romano and carried by Vatican Radio, made no direct
reference to the allegations by Jewish officials. But it strongly
urged Catholics to distinguish between the Jewish people and the
policies of the Israeli government or political parties.
   ``The tensions between Palestinians and Israelis continue to
provoke in the Italian milieu, and therefore also among Catholics,
grave preoccupations for the risk of distortions of information and
consequent emotive reactions, which in the extremist fringes, can
explode into violence,'' the statement said.
   ``Anti-Semitism in Italy seems to some a marginal phenomomen and
uncharacteristic of Italian society,'' it added. ``Still, episodes
of intolerance against Jews and Jewish institutions, occurring even
recently ... provoke in our community feelings of profound
preoccupation for the risk of painful civil and religious
lacerations that can derive from them.''
   The statement also stressed the need to ``promote a dialogue
between Jews, Christians and Moslems and to be builders of peace
together.''
   Last week, Rome's chief rabbi, Elio Toaff, and Jacob Sabban,
president of the Jewish community, held a news conference to detail
recent anti-Semitic incidents in Italy. Among other things, they
displayed packs of anonymous and threatening letters and dozens of
photos of swastikas painted on walls.
   The two said the media, including Catholic publications, fueled
anti-Semitic feelings in Italy with reports from the Middle East
that tend to compare Israelis to Nazis because of the Israelis'
policies toward Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The Vatican earlier expressed ``surprise'' at the Jewish
allegations and noted that Pope John Paul II has often spoken out
against anti-Semitism.
   Riots began Dec. 8 among the 1.5 million Palestinians of the
West Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel captured from Jordan and
Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war. At least 194 Arabs have been
killed, and an Israeli soldier and Jewish settler also have been
slain.
</TEXT>
