<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 0752EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:3-SSociety Adv26   05-23 0974</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: 3-S Society, Adv 26,0995</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs, May 26 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Three American Journalists Honored in China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three American writers, ostracized and ignored in
their own country during their lifetimes, have an organization in
China dedicated to remembering their contributions to the communist
revolution.
   The Smedley-Strong-Snow Society of China, a wing of the
prestigious Academy of Social Sciences, was founded in 1984 to
honor the three Midwesterners who were among the first to tell the
world of the cataclysmic events in China in the 1920s and '30s.
   The most famous of the trio is Edgar Snow (1905-72), the first
Westerner to interview Mao Tse-tung and Chou En-lai in the caves of
their guerrilla stronghold in northwest China, and author of ``Red
Star Over China,'' his classic account of the communist leadership.
   He is joined by Agnes Smedley (1892-1950), a fiery supporter of
revolutionary causes; and Anna Louise Strong (1885-1970),
chronicler of socialist upheaval in both the Soviet Union and China.
   In June, the ``3-S Society'' marks the 50th anniversary of the
publication of ``Red Star Over China'' with a major symposium on
the book at Beijing University.
   The society, made up of more than 100 scholars and writers who
knew the three Americans or studied their works, is also holding an
essay contest on the book, and will invite students from schools in
Beijing, Shanghai and Kansas City, Snow's hometown, to attend the
symposium.
   ``We want young people to read history, to find out how China
traversed this road and reached this stage,'' said former Foreign
Minister Huang Hua, president of the ``3-S Society.''
   Huang, Snow's interpreter when he interviewed Mao Tse-tung, said
young Chinese read too many books of ``love, martial arts and
adventure.'' Works of people such as Snow ``should be popularized
so their contributions to the Chinese cause will not be forgotten.''
   Snow arrived in Shanghai in 1927 for a planned six-week visit
and stayed nearly 14 years. In one of journalism's greatest scoops,
he found his way to the Red army headquarters in northwest China's
Baoan in 1936 and spent five months observing and talking to Mao
and his fellow communists.
   He was the first Western journalist to break the news blockade
Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalists had imposed on the communists. ``Red
Star,'' published in Britain in 1937 and in Shanghai and the United
States the next year, became the seminal work on the band of
revolutionaries who were to change the face of China.
   His book gave not only the West but also many Chinese their
first detailed look at the communist leaders, and many
intellectuals trekked to communist headquarters after reading it.
   ``It's hard to imagine what our image of China would be today
without Edgar Snow,'' said former New York Times reporter Harrison
Salisbury, a prominent writer on the Soviet Union and China.
   Salisbury said Snow, whom he met in the Soviet Union in World
War II, ``had been my hero as he had been the hero of a whole
generation of newspaper men.''
   Snow left China in 1941 and worked around the world as a roving
correspondent for such publications as the Saturday Evening Post,
the Chicago Tribune and the New York Herald Tribune.
   In 1959, after years of being hounded by anti-communist
McCarthyites, he left the United States for Switzerland. But he was
to make one last contribution to his native land: In 1970, Mao told
Snow that China would welcome a visit by then-President Nixon,
setting the stage for Nixon's historic trip in 1972.
   China showed its respect for Snow by sending a medical team to
Geneva in a futile attempt to save the life of the dying writer in
1972. Some of his ashes are buried in New York and some on a
university campus in Beijing where he once taught.
   Unlike Snow, who was never a Marxist, the two women writers were
outspoken in their support for leftist causes. Smedley, born into
poverty in St. Joseph, Mo., and raised in mining towns, was a
strong advocate of women's rights and anti-colonial struggles in
Germany, India and China.
   She worked with Sun Yat-sen's widow, Soong Ching-ling, and
China's most famous modern writer, Lu Xun. She wrote a biography of
Red army commander Zhu De and, in 1937 in the communist camp at
Yenan, taught Chou En-lai and other communists to square dance.
   In 1949, a U.S. Army report accused her of spying for the
Soviets, and she died in London in 1950 while trying to get back to
China.
   Strong, a native of Friend, Neb., was a pacifist opponent of
World War I and left for the newly founded Soviet Union in 1921.
   A resident of Moscow for almost 30 years, she wrote some 30
books on revolutions around the world. She, too, made her way to
Yenan in 1937, and interviewed Mao in 1946 when he made his famous
statement, ``All reactionaries are paper tigers.''
   She was arrested as a spy and expelled from the Soviet Union in
1949, only to be further attacked on her return to the United
States for her communist leanings. She died in Beijing at age 84
during the extreme leftist Cultural Revolution, isolated in her
last haven by the suspicion that prevailed then against all
foreigners.
   Dong Leshan, translator of a 1980 edition of ``Red Star Over
China'' that sold 1.3 million copies in China, said the works of
the three writers were not always welcomed in China.
   ``After the revolution Snow was still taboo because he told the
real story of the party. Some in the party took a negative view of
this,'' he said.
   It was only after the Cultural Revolution ended in 1976, Dong
said, that ``Red Star'' and Snow found acceptance.
   End Adv PM Thur May 26
</TEXT>
</DOC>
