<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Barbados-IceCream Adv02   05-23 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Barbados-Ice Cream, Adv 02,0528</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs June 2 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Ice Cream Entrepreneur Claims 751 Flavors, Including `Sex'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN M. ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGETOWN, Barbados (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ice cream entrepreneur Charles
Sandford didn't believe vanilla and chocolate were enough to draw
in customers, so he added such flavors as fire, flying fish _ and
sex.
   ``Sex is the most exotic,'' the 37-year-old Sandford said. Asked
what's in it, he replies: ``Large, ripe, juicy Barbados cherries
that simmer in crystal-clear champagne until they pop.''
   Sandford's recipe for the flying fish flavor includes fish mash
and smooth peanut butter, as well as milk, eggs and butter. The
flying fish is the national symbol of Barbados, a former British
colony.
   ``I just invented a new flavor, to commemorate the island's 21st
anniversary of independence,'' Sandford said. The concoction
includes 21 different kinds of fruit and is called, appropriately
enough, ``The 21.'' It tastes like a very rich punch.
   Sandford grew up in New York City, where he studied to be a
clothes designer. He ran his own small store until his
Barbados-born wife, Judy, suggested eight years ago that an ice
cream shop in her prosperous and hot Caribbean island might be more
fun and profitable.
   Sandford sold his business in New York and went to Milan, where
he served an apprenticeship at Fragole Fabri, one of Italy's
biggest ice cream factories.
   ``I learned the basics, just enough to make vanilla ice cream,''
he said. ``After the first six months, I knew how to make ice
cream, but I had to learn to improve it and then to master it.''
   Today, he said, ``I am the king.''
   Sandford makes 18 flavors fresh each day. He claims he has
created 751 in all, and is seeking an entry in the Guinness Book of
Records.
   ``Every single recipe is different,'' he said. ``I do not take a
vanilla base ... and simpl change the name as I add different
ingredients.''
   Sandford also meets special requests.
   On Wednesdays, he prepares ice cream for diabetics, using
artificial sweeteners instead of sugar.
   For vegetarians, Sandford makes carrot and zucchini ice cream.
Creamy avocado also is popular.
   Not every flavor is a bestseller.
   ``Tomato did not do too well,'' he said. ``Too acidic.''
   Some flavors contain promotional gimmicks. The main ingredient
in ``money'' ice cream is a tightly-rolled Barbados dollar wrapped
in plastic.
   Sandford did not set out to become a one-man Baskin Robbins or
Howard Johnson's when he opened Gelato five years ago in a chic
mall in suburban St. Michael, one mile outside Bridgetown.
   But shipping delays, high costs and import duties convinced him
he could not rely on importing the ``starters,'' or basic flavors,
from the United States.
   ``I first started experimenting with local fruits,'' he said.
Now, his favorite sherbets are made with mangoes, watermelons and
passion fruit.
   Sandford won't say what goes into his ``fire'' ice cream, which
tastes like hot cinnamon candies.
   But he guarantees, ``This will burn your palate.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs June 2</NOTE>
