<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, May 31, the 152nd day of 1988. There are 214
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On May 31, 1962, World War II Gestapo official Adolf Eichmann
was hanged in Israel for his role in the Nazi Holocaust. His body
was cremated, and the ashes were scattered into the Mediterranean
the following day.
   On this date:
   In 1809, composer Franz Josef Hayden died in Vienna, Austria.
   In 1819, poet Walt Whitman was born in West Hill, N.Y.
   In 1889, more than 2,000 people perished when a dam break sent
water rushing through Johnstown, Pa.
   In 1910, the Union of South Africa was founded.
   In 1913, the 17th amendment to the Constitution, which provides
for the popular election of U.S. senators, was declared in effect.
   In 1916, during World War I, British and German fleets fought
the Battle of Jutland off Denmark.
   In 1961, South Africa became an independent republic.
   In 1970, tens of thousands of people in Peru died in an
earthquake.
   In 1976, Martha Mitchell, the estranged wife of former Attorney
General John N. Mitchell, died in New York.
   In 1977, the trans-Alaska oil pipeline, three years in the
making, was completed with the final weld made by construction
workers near Pump Station Three.
   In 1986, Bobby Rahal won the rain-delayed Indianapolis 500 with
a record average speed of 170.722 mph.
   Ten years ago: NATO leaders concluded a two-day summit
conference in Washington by adopting guidelines for a long-range
defense program and issuing a communique cautioning the Soviet
Union about its military activities in Africa.
   Five years ago: Jack Dempsey, heavyweight boxing champion from
1919 to 1926, died at his home in New York at age 87.
   One year ago: Addressing an audience of AIDS research supporters
in Washington, President Reagan said the epidemic ``calls for
urgency, not panic,'' but he drew scattered boos when he announced
he would seek expanded testing for the disease.
   Today's Birthdays: Author-minister Norman Vincent Peale is 90.
Actor Don Ameche is 80. Prince Rainier of Monaco is 65. Actor Clint
Eastwood is 58. Opera singer Shirley Verrett is 55. Singer Peter
Yarrow is 50. Anglican Church envoy Terry Waite is 49. Singer
Johnny Paycheck is 47. Actress Sharon Gless is 45. Former football
star Joe Namath is 45. Actor Tom Berenger is 38. Actor Gregory
Harrison is 38. Actress-model Brooke Shields is 23.
   Thought for Today: ``Pity costs nothing, and ain't worth
nothing.'' -- Henry Wheeler Shaw, alias ``Josh Billings,'' American
author (1818-1885).
