<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1402EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--GoneFishingII-Camp Adv05   05-23 1154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Gone Fishing II-Camp, Adv 05,1187</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv05</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 5</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Gone-Fishing II</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCK SPRINGS, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From the flat high desert of western
Wyoming a traveler looks far back over his shoulder to see distant
white clouds high in the northeastern sky.
   But what seems to be clouds are actually peaks that soar 13,000
feet high and straddle the Continental Divide for 120 miles.
   They are the Wind River mountains, and no one knows them better
than Finis (rhymes with highness) Mitchell.
   At 87, he is one of the few living Americans to have a physical
landmark _ 12,482-foot Mitchell Peak _ named after him by the U.S.
Geological Survey. It was the government's way of thanking him for
helping it correct topographical maps. He has a near-perfect memory
of the 2{ million acres of the Wind Rivers public patrimony.
   Mitchell earned the sobriquet ``Lord of the Winds'' by hiking
15,000 miles, climbing 276 peaks (some two dozen times) and
amassing more than 100,000 color slides of what he calls ``my back
yard.''
   He also is responsible for some of the finest fishing in the
world. Along with his wife, Emma, his father and brother, and a
string of pack horses, Mitchell stocked 314 of the 4,000 lakes in
the Wind Rivers a half century ago. From those, the fish migrated
to 700 others in the chain.
   Steep waterfalls and hostile terrain had previously kept them
barren of fish since their creation.
   ``These waters were all virgin and were just full of water lice,
leeches, freshwater shrimp ... so those fish just gorged
themselves,'' Mitchell wrote in his book ``Wind River Trails.''
   ``Some of the brook trout weighed 3 pounds the third year.''
   Today the Wind River Range is one of the finest high-altitude
fisheries anywhere.
   In 1906, when Mitchell's daddy traded 40 acres in Missouri for
160 acres at the foot of the Wind Rivers, the family moved west in
a boxcar with a wagon, two mules, a cow, a dog and a few household
treasures.
   They arrived in Rock Springs on April 26 and headed north only
to find their new land was worthless. Mitchell's father started
hauling freight at a penny a pound to feed his family, and
5-year-old Finis helped out. From then on, his life was a great
adventure centered in the Wind River mountains.
   ``The cutthroat trout were the only fish in the Wind Rivers,''
Mitchell said. ``They weighed about 12 pounds apiece. There were no
fish in the lakes unless somebody put them there. We think
sheepherders may have packed a few fish up there to have something
to eat.''
   As a young man Mitchell explored the mountains every chance he
got, but after marrying in 1925 he settled down in Rock Springs to
work for the Union Pacific Railroad.
   In 1930, the Great Depression cost him his job and the couple
took their chances living off the land after a bank failure wiped
out their savings.
   ``A hide buyer took us and all our stuff up into the
mountains,'' Mitchell recalled. ``I had 15 $20 bills. Two went to
the hide buyer and we were on our own.
   ``We followed a wagon track left over from the sheepmen's and
cattlemen's war of '03. When we got settled we decided to open a
fishing camp. We asked the Forest Service for a permit and they
said fine. We were the only ones doing it.''
   Mrs. Mitchell cooked meals for 50 cents apiece, her husband
borrowed 10 horses from friends and charged $1.50 a day to rent
them to fishermen. Soon folks from Rock Springs were coming up to
Mitchell's Fishing Camp for some badly needed fun in those hard
times.
   ``Only Big Sandy, Black Joe, Dad's, and a couple other lakes had
fish in them when we got started,'' said Mitchell.
   On their own, the Mitchells began stocking more. When
Superintendent Bill Rowley of the nearby Daniel Hatchery heard
about it, he came to see them.
   ``He said to me, `Finis, if you're going to run a fishing camp
you ought to stock other lakes, too. We don't have any money, but
we'll bring you the fish free if you'll pack 'em into the
mountains,''' Mitchell recalled.
   Rowley's hatchery was less than a decade old when he struck his
deal with Mitchell. The state of Wyoming provided a three-room log
cabin for the superintendent, the hired hand and his wife, and
their six children.
   Today the hatchery uses trucks with oxygen tanks and elaborate
cooling systems, as well as helicopters, to haul fish to lakes and
streams. Mitchell's and Rowley's methods of transportion were more
primitive.
   ``In the old days we used 5-gallon milk cans, a dozen at a
time,'' he said. ``The fish were an inch long and there were 1,000
in a can. We covered the tops of the cans with burlap and steadied
them by putting them in wooden apple crates which we tied to pack
horses.''
   Mrs. Mitchell's job was to walk the horses around in circles as
they arrived from the hatchery. That was to keep the water
splashing inside the cans, distributing oxygen to the fish and
keeping them from smothering.
   ``The men would all go inside our camp tent and eat and leave me
outside walking those pack animals,'' she said, recalling those
days with good humor.
   In 1939, the railroad recalled Mitchell. When the couple broke
camp and left the Wind Rivers to return to Rock Springs, they were
$4,000 in debt. But, for free, they'd stocked 2.5 million
cutthroat, rainbow, in many isolated lakes every
trout caught by a happy angler is directly descended from the ones
Finis and Emma Mitchell packed in 50 years ago.
   ``Trout multiplied into the millions, only to reach weights of 4
to 12 pounds and then die without seeing a single hook,'' Mitchell
wrote in his book, a small guide to the mountains which he sells
through mail order from his home.
   Finis Mitchell walks with the help of two sturdy sticks now, but
his aging legs haven't kept him from going to the mountains every
summer. He's been honored by his state with an honorary doctorate
of law, and by his nation when the Environmental Protection Agency
gave him its outstanding achievement award.
   But his biggest thrills still come in the Wind Rivers, walking
with young people.
   ``Children ask me who owns the mountains and I'm happy to tell
them `You own it,''' Mitchell said. ``It's true, too.''
   To remind Americans of their stewardship, he writes in every
copy of his book:
   ``This is your wilderness.
   ``Take only pictures,
   ``Leave only footprints,
   ``Kill nothing but time.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
