<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 2230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--GoneFishingII-Flies Adv05   05-23 0974</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Gone Fishing II-Flies, Adv 05,1000</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv05</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 5</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to restore byline.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Gone Fishing II</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHERIDAN, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tucked away in a corner of the Ritz
Sporting Goods store, across the room from a lunch counter
surrounded by a covey of good ol' boys drinking six cups of coffee
on one quarter, sits owner Sam Mavrakis.
   When he isn't selling fishing licenses or tackle, or swapping
lies with the coffee drinkers, he's holding court at the little
table littered with beautiful bits of fur and feathers.
   Without looking up from his flying fingers, Mavrakis keeps up a
running commentary about great fish he's known, famous people he's
guided and the merits of one trout stream over another.
   But it's not the colorful stories of visiting with Prince Philip
or fishing with Joe DiMaggio that keep his audience enthralled:
It's his flashing fingers. Mavrakis is one of the West's best
artificial fly tiers. Every fly he sells in his store, located in
the heart of some of America's best fishing country, is hand-tied.
   And like thousands of other fishermen who've channeled their
summertime love of fly fishing into wintertime fly tying, he needs
very specific materials to create fake critters to lure trout
straight out of a river and onto a hook.
   Without realizing it, Mavrakis, like fly tiers from Japan to
Tasmania, Venezuela to Iceland, and all points in between, is
largely dependent on three men.
   They are a Wyoming elk hide tanner, a New Hampshire cotton
spinner and a Pennsylvania chicken farmer. Together they form the
tripod of international fly tying because they provide nearly all
the commercial raw materials needed to practice the art.
   Each stumbled into the lucrative business by accident.
   Steve Kennerk, owner of Rocky Mountain Dubbing in Riverton,
Wyo., was a hide tanner whose clientele dropped off because of his
state's depressed economy. He now provides nearly all the wild
animal hair used by foreign factories to manufacture the bulk of
ready-made artificial flies.
   ``I export to 16 countries and have been named this year's
Wyoming Exporter of the Year,'' said Kennerk, whose tanning
techniques are self-taught and secret.
   ``Last year I had gross sales of $225,000, with 90 percent of my
business now concentrated in providing hair for flies. It's growing
about 40 percent a year.''
   He has a new catalog listing the 26 colors of the animal hair he
tans and dyes, including caribou, Australian possum, deer, elk,
moose and rabbit.
   Caught by surprise at the success of what started in 1981 as a
sideline, Kennerk now has five full-time employees and pays 16
mentally handicapped youngsters to bag and label his products. He
also buys hides from local hunters who pump that money back into
Riverton, and is doubling the size of his building.
   Ray Merrick's Danville Chenille Co. has been in business 55
years. It began by providing chenille _ a cotton yarn twisted
together around a hard core _ for ladies' hats and handbags. But
fashions changed and in the late 1950s, when Merrick's family
bought the New Hampshire firm, its product was popular mainly with
hobbyists. Most chenille was then sold for novelty items, such as
pipe cleaners.
   Recently the boom in fly tying has created a whole new market
for chenille, which forms the body of the fly. Merrick's company is
now the world's major supplier of the product named after the
French word for caterpillar.
   ``We grossed $550,000 last year, with all but $50,000 of that
from our fish and tackle business,'' said Merrick, who employs 11
full-time and five part-time workers.
   ``We have so many orders it's going like crazy around here.
One-third of our sales are to fly factories in Hong Kong and
Singapore, and to people in Japan, Mauritius, New Zealand, England,
Australia _ all over.''
   Buck Metz's chicken hatchery in Bellville, Pa., anchors the
third corner of the raw materials triangle.
   His father, grandfather and uncle started the chicken farm in
the late 1930s.
   ``It was a commercial poultry operation. We raised chickens for
meat and eggs,'' said Metz, who now runs the hatchery with his
brother, John.
   ``We got into providing specialty neck feathers because I needed
them to tie my own flies and they were very hard to come by. Before
us, most of the hackles came hit-and-miss from India and the
Philippines.''
   Metz bought his first specialty chickens in 1972 from breeds
that had been genetically modified to produce unique neck feathers.
``My dad thought I was crazy when I paid $10,000 for 150
chickens,'' he said.
   Last year that division of the family business took in nearly
$1.5 million, while the farm's regular chicken and egg sales
totaled $3 million.
   ``I realized within two years that there was an unknown level of
demand out there for our hackle production,'' said Metz, referring
to the prized neck feathers of his pedigreed poultry.
   ``We've been trying ever since to find out how big the market
is, but it keeps growing faster than we can keep up with it.
   ``We have 35 distributors in Europe, Asia and South America, as
well as here, and we're far and away the largest feather supplier
to fly tiers in the world.''
   Metz now employs 60 full-time and 60 part-time workers to give
his 100,000 pampered chickens the individual care they require.
   ``These are somewhat delicate birds, prone to diseases more than
commercial strains of poultry, and each one has to be individually
caged to protect them from each other,'' he said.
   Kennerk, Merrick and Metz all know about each other and their
importance to fly tiers.
   They have another thing in common: They're avid fly fishermen
who're now so busy working they don't have time to go fishing
anymore.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
