<DOCNO> AP880523-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1411EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv05   05-23 0844</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 05,0872</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv05</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 5</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Angela Lansbury, making a return
engagement as hostess for tonight's ``1988 Tony Awards,'' wants to
get back to Broadway where she collected her share of the prizes in
earlier years.
   ``I think there's an electricity that takes place in the theater
and nowhere else but in the theater,'' says Miss Lansbury, familiar
to TV audiences as Jessica Fletcher on ``Murder, She Wrote.'' ``It
makes you want to get back to it. Applause, applause, you know.
It's meat and potatoes to us.''
   Three musicals received 10 nominations for Tonys, which go to
the best of Broadway from the season just ending. They're Andrew
Lloyd Webber's ``The Phantom of the Opera,'' Stephen Sondheim's
``Into the Woods'' and a revival of Cole Porter's ``Anything Goes.''
   The CBS producers of the awards presentations, which will be
televised from Broadway's Minskoff Theater, invited Miss Lansbury
back for a second year as hostess.
   ``Last year, it intrigued and honored me enough that I felt I
had to host it,'' Miss Lansbury said by telephone from her home in
Southern California.
   ``Through my connection with `Murder, She Wrote,' I knew I was
going to be welcome in the nation's living rooms. Some people saw
me glamorously gowned for the first time.''
   Miss Lansbury became known in Hollywood at 17, became a star on
Broadway at 40 in ``Mame,'' and became a TV star at 59, as Jessica
Fletcher, who writes and solves mysteries.
   She was nominated for an Academy Award for her first movie,
``Gaslight,'' and twice more, for ``The Picture of Dorian Gray''
and ``The Manchurian Candidate,'' where she played Laurence
Harvey's mother. She also played Elvis Presley's mother in ``Blue
Hawaii'' and Elizabeth Taylor's sister in ``National Velvet.''
   On Broadway, she was in only three shows, ``Hotel Paradiso,''
``A Taste of Honey'' and ``Anyone Can Whistle,'' before she started
winning Tonys. She has Tonys for the musicals ``Mame,'' ``Dear
World,'' ``Gypsy'' and ``Sweeney Todd.''
   About her gown for this year's show, Miss Lansbury says,
``That's a prime concern for a woman. We're going to try to outdo
ourselves this year.''
   Last year she appeared first in a gown of dramatically
contrasting panels of black and white and later wore glittering
gold.
   ``I'm lucky enough to be gowned by Bob Mackie, a great Hollywood
designer,'' she says. ``He created one of the most stunning gowns
I've ever seen last year _ the black-and-white creation.
   ``It's such a great dress I cannot let it hang in a bag in a
closet. I'm sure it will go into one of the Hollywood museums _ if
I can keep it away from my granddaughter. She's a big
dresser-upper. She's only 3.
   ``My son _ her father _ is director Anthony Shaw. He directed a
lot of `Murder, She Wrote,' which is very nice. My daughter has a
restaurant with her husband in Italy.''
   Another concern is the strike by the Writers Guild of America.
   ``Last year, a tremendous amount of what I did say was me,'' she
says. ``I told them I didn't want to get up there and spout a lot
of things I wouldn't be comfortable saying. I wanted to talk from
the heart.
   ``This year, I don't know how they'll script. With everything
that has been written about the shows, it would be possible for me
to put together anything that's needed. If necessary, that's what
I'll do.''
   Earlier in May, the 62-year-old actress made an exercise and
lifestyle tape. ``It's how to keep your body moving, light and
graceful and how to keep your energy up,'' she says. ``I throw in
all sorts of homilies about rest and exercise and how to get the
most out of life.''
   This season's ``Murder, She Wrote'' series kept her working long
hours from last July 5 to early May, Miss Lansbury says. ``We shot
25 episodes. Normally we do 22. We had the scripts so we decided
we'd go ahead, so we'd have something to start the new season with.
We hope to start back Aug. 1. We have no way of knowing. We're in
the midst of this dreadful strike. People are rather grim about
it.''
   At the end of next season, Miss Lansbury says, ``My five-year
stint on `Murder, She Wrote' will be over. I cannot stay, on a
week-to-week basis. Perhaps we can work out an arrangement where I
do several a year, which would leave me free to do other things.
That's what I want.
   ``Especially when you get up in my years, if you're still
energetic, which I am, and still love working in the theater,
movies and TV, you want to feel you've got some time to do it. I
really think I'm one of the luckiest people on two feet. I do have
tremendous stamina and energy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
