<2ND_LINE>BC-Summit-Gorbachev's Team, Adv 29,0625</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Profiles of Gorbachev's Advisers for Summit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are brief biographical sketches of the top
Soviet officials likely to be at the side of Soviet Communist Party
General Secretary Mikhail Gorbachev at his summit meeting this week
with President Reagan.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>EDUARD A. SHEVARDNADZE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The 60-year-old foreign minister has been the main Soviet
contact with Secretary of State George P. Shultz on summit
planning. Earlier this month in Geneva, he and Shultz tackled the
final problems holding up U.S. Senate ratification of the treaty
banning medium- and shorter-range nuclear weapons. The two also
tried to resolve the differences over a treaty to cut in half the
superpower arsenals of strategic nuclear weapons.
   Shevardnadze, the only non-Slavic member of the 13-member ruling
Politburo, succeeded Andrei A. Gromyko as foreign minister in July
1985, less than four months after Gorbachev took power.
   The white-haired Shevardnadze has given Soviet diplomacy a more
personable face than Gromyko, frequently smiling and joking with
reporters. He and Shultz have developed what both describe as a
good rapport in their frequent meetings.
   Before becoming foreign minister, Shevardnadze headed the
Communist Party in the Georgian republic, where he gained a
reputation for cracking down on rampant corruption.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ALEXANDER N. YAKOVLEV</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A former Columbia University exchange student and ambassador to
Canada, Yakovlev's career has skyrocketed with that of Gorbachev.
Yakovlev, the 64-year-old Communist Party propaganda chief, is
considered the chief architect of the general secretary's
``glasnost,'' or openness policy. He has played a prominent role in
liberalizing Soviet cultural life.
   Yakovlev became head of the Central Committee propaganda
department in 1985, a candidate member of the Politburo in January
1987 and a full member just five months later.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ANATOLY F. DOBRYNIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   When Dobrynin returned to Moscow from the United States as a
Central Committee secretary, he transformed the Central Committee
International Department from an organization dealing largely with
non-ruling Communist parties to one that engages in hands-on
diplomacy with non-Communist politicians. This was once the
exclusive domain of the Foreign Ministry.
   Dobrynin, 68, had been ambassador to the United States for an
unprecedented 25 years. During his Washington tenure, the tall,
rotund Dobrynin gained a reputation as a charming but tough
diplomat and a skillful chess player.
   He has accompanied Gorbachev to every summit with Reagan, in
Geneva; Reykjavik, Iceland, and Washington.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SERGEI F. AKHROMEYEV</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A marshal of the Soviet army, the 65-year-old Akhromeyev dropped
by the Pentagon during the Washington summit for a brief tour. He
is the Soviet Union's military chief of staff and a first deputy
defense minister.
   Akhromeyev took part in the Reykjavik arms control negotiations,
where an American participant said, ``He was tough and determined,
but he was trying to get an agreement.''
   A soldier since 1940, Akhromeyev has wide command experience. In
1984, he replaced Nikolai Ogarkov as chief of staff.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ANDREI A. GROMYKO</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A key figure in Soviet foreign policy for more than three
decades, Gromyko now holds the largely ceremonial post of
president. As head of state, he will greet Reagan upon arrival in
Moscow. He spends most of his time now on domestic concerns,
chairing meetings of the country's parliament, the Supreme Soviet,
and officiating at Kremlin awards presentations.
   But he remains a Politburo member, and as such keeps his hand in
foreign affairs by meeting with visiting foreign dignitaries.
   Gromyko, 78, was at various times ambassador to the United
States, to the United Nations and to Britain. But he is best known
as foreign minister, a post he held from 1957 to 1985.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday May 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
