<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1430EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Summit-Reagan'sTeam Adv29   05-23 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Summit-Reagan's Team, Adv 29,0579</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are brief sketches of key members of the U.S.
delegation to the fourth summit between President Reagan and Soviet
Communist Party General Secretary Mikhail Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GEORGE P. SHULTZ</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Shultz, 68, a former president of Bechtel Corp. in San
Francisco, has served as secretary of state since July 1982.
Trained as an economist, Shultz was Treasury secretary under
President Ford and director of the Office of Management and Budget
under President Nixon. Shultz has held frequent meetings with his
Soviet counterpart, Eduard A. Shevardnadze, to set the agenda for
the summit. His wife, Helena, and first lady Nancy Reagan are the
only spouses planning to attend the summit.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FRANK C. CARLUCCI</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Carlucci, 58, took over the helm at the Pentagon in late 1987,
succeeding Caspar Weinberger. Before becoming secretary of defense,
Carlucci spent more than a year as the president's national
security adviser. Known as a pragmatist, Carlucci also has served
as ambassador to Portugal and as undersecretary of the Department
of Health, Education and Welfare.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>COLIN L. POWELL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Powell, head of the National Security Council, moved up to the
position as the president's personal adviser on foreign affairs
after Carlucci went to the Defense Department. Powell, one of the
highest-ranking blacks in government, had served as Carlucci's
deputy. Powell has received high marks in his current job for his
negotiating skills and his ability to solve disputes between the
various agencies. He is 51 and holds the rank of lieutenant general
in the Army.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HOWARD BAKER</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Baker, a former Senate majority leader from Tennessee, took over
day-to-day responsiblity for running the White House in February
after Reagan fired Donald Regan. Baker, 63, quit the Senate to run
for president, but gave up his ambitions to succeed Reagan when he
was appointed White House chief of staff. He was a lawyer before
re-entering government service.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MAX KAMPELMAN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Kampelman, a lawyer and educator, holds the title of ambassador
and heads the U.S. negotiating team on nuclear and space weapons.
He has had a wide-ranging career and a variety of jobs in and out
of government. He was an arms control negotiator from 1980 to 1983.
A native New Yorker, Kampelman is 66. He has a wide interest in
human rights and has written a book about anti-semitism in the
Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PAUL H. NITZE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Nitze, 81, is adviser to the president on arms control
negotiations. He has had a long and distinguished career in
government, including stints as secretary of the Navy and deputy
secretary of Defense. He headed the U.S. negotiating team for
intermediate-range nuclear weapons treaty, which Reagan and
Gorbachev signed at the Washington summit last December.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ROZANNE L. RIDGWAY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   As assistant secretary of State for European and Canadian
affairs, Ridgway frequently accompanies Shultz on negotiating trips
and has handled many details on the summit. A career foreign
service officer, Ridgway, 52, has served as ambassador to Finland
and East Germany.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JACK E. MATLOCK JR.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Matlock, 59, is the U.S. ambassador to the Soviet Union. Before
his appointment as ambassador, he served as the top Soviet expert
at the National Security Council. A Russian speaker, Matlock
graduated from Duke University. He is a former ambassador to
Czechoslovakia and has held a variety of posts in Vienna, Accra,
Ghana and Dar-es-Salaam, Tanzania.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sun May 29</NOTE>
