<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1600EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Bowling Adv29-2Takes   05-23 1206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bowling, Adv 29-2 Takes,1248</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Sport's Identity Crisis _ Purple Balls? Heated Bags? This is
Bowling?</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NANCY SHULINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every evening around 7, the thudding,
rumbling and clashing that have filled the convention center for
11{ hours suddenly cease. For 15 minutes, there's silence.
   Then the organ swells. Spectators cheer. Gold curtains snap
open. And 200 bowlers, their faces flushed with pride and
embarrassment, march up the center aisle, flanked by 20 gleaming
bowling alleys.
   Uh, strike that. We don't use ``alley'' anymore. And hey! Get
your mind out of the gutter. Take it from the American Bowling
Congress: ``Gutter'' is out. ``Channel'' is in.
   Ask Joe Bowler and you get a different opinion.
   ``A gutter's a gutter,'' says Joe, better known as 33-year-old
Rick Haemmerle of Indianapolis. Chosen at random to represent
bowlers everywhere, he was crowned Feb. 13, opening day of the 85th
annual ABC tournament that ended in Jacksonville last week.
   Question: How long does it take 38,000 bowlers from 50 states
and nine foreign countries bowling 18 hours a day, seven days a
week, to bowl 341,430 games, thereby toppling 58 million pins?
   Answer: 103 days, which is about 102 longer than it takes to
realize that bowling is experiencing an identity crisis.
   Gutter or channel? Recreation or sport? Ralph Kramden or Ralph
Lauren?
   Don't be fooled by the plastic bowler-in-a-seashell, the ``beer
frame'' keychains and other doo-dads for sale at the tournament.
Out on the lanes, bowling's taking the high road: No smoking. No
shorts. No collarless shirts. No drinking. NO HOT DOGS. You're here
to bowl, not to eat.
   What's gotten into bowling? Where'd all that high-tech equipment
come from?
   A black rubber ball in a zippered bag was good enough for Ralph
Kramden. Today, it's three, four, five balls. Rubber balls.
Urethane balls. Polyester balls. In purple. Blue. YELLOW, for
heaven's sake. Carried in _ are you ready for this, Norton? _
battery-heated, insulated, temperature-controlled bowling bags.
   Behold the modern bowling pin: Laminated on the outside, holes
on the inside. The slightest tap and it's to the moon, Alice!
   Consider the lane: Spread a little oil on today's
urethane-coated surfaces and it's bang, zoom! To the pocket, Alice!
   ``Nah, I don't practice,'' says Joe Bowler. ``If you're not
hitting your shot, you just buy another ball. I carry five of the
urethanes.''
   Alas, five aren't always enough. In his first official act, Joe
Bowler opened the tournament with a gutterball. What do you want
from a guy forced to bowl in front of 2,234 people while wearing a
robe and a crown?
   Bowling's split personality begins to make sense when you
consider that there's bowling the sport, and then there's bowling
the game.
   Bowling the sport is math, physics and sophisticated terms like
``coefficient of friction'' and ``kinetic energy.''
   Bowling the game is nachos, chili dogs and simple terms like
``Miller'' and ``Bud.''
   Unlike the sport, the game has no image problem. It couldn't
care less, an attitude that irks the sport no end.
   Let the sport compile all those demographics about how
young-bright-affluent its 68 million participants are. Let it lie
awake nights worrying about the impression it makes.
   The game has better things to do, like order another
cheeseburger.
   The American Bowling Congress, gatekeeper of the sport and
recipient of $10 million in dues from 3.4 million league bowlers,
stresses skill, complexity, pride and tradition.
   The National Bowling Council, the industry's advertising arm,
and AMF and Brunswick, its largest manufacturers, stress leisure,
recreation and fun, fun, fun.
   Eddie Wise, a 9-year-old who pushed his bowling ball two-handed
to a near-perfect 299, was immortalized in the early '80s in a
Brunswick ad promoting easy-to-topple pins. In the same era, the
Young American Bowling Alliance put an orangutan on the cover of
its magazine, and the National Bowling Council enthusiastically
promoted a ``Real People'' segment featuring a bowling pig.
   Fun for all ages! Anyone can play! You don't have to be good.
You don't have to be a grown-up. You don't even have to be human!
   Bowling's critics say it's going to the dogs.
   Its kingpins say it's going to the Olympics.
   What's a swell game like bowling doing in a mess like this?
   It didn't get there overnight.
   The ancient Egyptians were bowlers; it's been traced back to
5200 BC.
   Germans bowled in the 6th century; Martin Luther in the 16th. In
those days, the game was called ninepins, ``lawn bowling'' in
England, where Henry VIII banned it as ``a form of vicious
gambling.''
   No respect, even then.
   Lawn bowling and ``skittles,'' a Dutch game, got a warm welcome
in the New World, where tavern owners embraced them as a way to
boost beer sales.
   It didn't take long for gambling charges to resurface. Prim and
proper Connecticut banned ninepins in the late 1830s. That might
have been the end of that, had not some enterprising soul _
evidence points to one Jonathan Coe of Madison, Conn. _
circumvented the law by adding a 10th pin. Bowling was legalized in
1841.
   Like other German immigrants, bowling headed West in the 19th
century. It settled in the Midwest, still bowling's stronghold with
Michigan No. 1.
   Bowling generally thrives wherever blue-collar and shift workers
are found. ``If you work from 7 to 5, you don't have time for
daylight sports like golf or tennis. Bowling is something you can
do at night,'' says Steve Harding, a bowler who owns a pizzeria in
Sherman, Texas.
   Almost from the beginning, would-be bureaucrats descended on
bowling, bent on organizing, standardizing and merchandizing what
was, until the late 1800s, a haphazard affair involving however
many pins of whatever shapes and sizes happened to be on hand.
   That all changed in 1895, when the American Bowling Congress
first met, in New York. Formed to represent bowlers' interests, the
ABC quickly adopted the 300-point scoring system and set uniform
standards for pins, balls and lanes.
   And what did it get for its trouble? It got trouble.
   The bickering started almost immediately: High scores vs. high
standards. Commercial interests vs. bowler interests. Sport vs.
game.
   Bad press dogged bowling from the beginning (Ever read ``Rip van
Winkle?''), only to be replaced many years later by something
infinitely worse: no press at all.
   Legislators picked on bowling. In some states, it was illegal
for minors to walk to or from a bowling alley unless accompanied by
an adult. Those laws were repealed in the 1950s.
   By that time, bowling had reached new heights of respectability.
The glamorous beer teams, touring the country in their all-white,
good-guy outfits, helped boost bowling's image, along with sales of
Stroh's, Falstaff, Budweiser and Pfeiffer. Automatic pin-spotters
brought respectability, just as the National Child Labor Committee
was about to crack down on the low pay and late hours given
erstwhile pinboys. And women developed an affinity for the game,
prompting proprietors to class up the joints.
   As Ralph Kramden went, so went the nation. Between the mid '40s
and the mid '60s, the number of league bowlers quadrupled.
Suddenly, everyone was going bowling _ 4.5 million people
regularly, in ABC-sanctioned leagues.
</TEXT>
