<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1602EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Bowling Adv29-1stAdd   05-23 1205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bowling, Adv 29-1st Add,1246</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>JACKSONVILLE: ABC-sanctioned leagues.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   From 1955 to 1960, membership in the Women's International
Bowling Congress rose by 150 percent.
   Entrepreneurs were quick to spring into action. A little too
much action, it turned out.
   In 1944, there were 38,203 bowling lanes.
   By 1964, there were 159,079.
   So ended ``The Competitive Era'' of bowling. So began ``The
Commercial Era.'' So says Dr. George Allen of Tempe, Ariz., a
former college professor with four decades of involvement in
bowling and a Ph.D. in finance.
   He's also the author of two scholarly volumes on industry trends
that combine a desire to drag bowling's leaders behind the woodshed
with a penchant for capital letters. ``NO INDUSTRY OR ORGANIZATION
HAS AN INHERENT RIGHT TO EXIST FOREVER,'' he writes.
   Allen considers bowling a sport, and he'd like you to. Actually,
what he'd really like is for you to consider it ``a microcosm of
life itself,'' but what the heck. He's a reasonable guy.
   Besides, this is no time to argue. ``Bowling,'' Allen warns,
``is on the verge of extinction,'' done in by bouncy pins and
urethane balls with built-in hooking power, unscrupulous lane
conditions and greedy commercial interests.
   If it's true that the sport of bowling is dying, Allen thinks
the business of bowling is what's killing it. ``We have eroded the
integrity of the SPORT of bowling to create the RECREATION of
bowling,'' according to the text of a speech to the Bowling
Proprietors Association of America in 1986.
   Meanwhile, recreational bowlers are scoring up a storm.
   The same 213 average that made one Detroiter the highest-ranked
bowler in his league in 1987 puts him between 50th and 60th on this
year's roster.
   Consider the perfect game: 12 strikes, for a score of 300, once
so rare that the ABC gave a 14-carat gold ring to anyone who
managed to pull it off.
   Today, the same ring costs a bowler $350. The free ones are
silver-plated _ a good thing for the ABC, considering the number of
perfect games bowled last year: 8,537, up from 1,375 a decade ago.
   Honor scores in general _ 300, 299 or 298 for a single game or
800 for a three-game series _ totaled 21,022 for 1987, exceeding
the totals for 1977, 1978 and 1979 combined.
   During a single day of competition at a tournament in Hartford,
Conn., in April, there were four perfect games.
   Kathy McBride, who works the counter at Bowl-Era Lanes in
Hammond, Ind., still remembers the excitement of the center's first
300 game. ``It was a big day. Of course, that was five years ago.
So far this year, we've had six.''
   At Bowl-Era, ``180 used to be considered a high average. Now
we're seeing 225 averages. Last year, my own family brought home 16
trophies. Finally, I told them, `Enough!'''
   Bill Taylor of Pasadena, Calif., has had enough, too. Taylor is
a self-appointed guardian of the sport's integrity _ what's left of
it, anyway.
   He'd sooner lock bowling in its room than let it strut its stuff
as scheduled in a one-day exhibition the day before opening
ceremonies at the summer Olympics in Seoul.
   ``Bowling is not going to any parties until it cleans itself
up,'' vows Taylor, a former pro coach who now manufactures his own
line of ``honest'' pins and lane finishes, products he insists
would solve the whole problem. Products he claims the ABC refuses
to approve. The ABC says he's never asked.
   Bowling, says Taylor, ``has become a low-life game. A
24-year-old with a 227 average just bowled his 14th career 300
game. If the great bowlers of the past were here instead of in
their graves, they would shoot him.
   ``A bowling lane today is the equivalent of a concave golf green
with a 36-inch cup,'' contends Taylor, who, using a speed trap of
his own invention, recently clocked a bowling pin at 42 feet per
second. ``In the old days, they traveled 16 feet, 17 feet per
second. Now they're flying all over the deck.''
   Next to bouncy pins, nothing makes Taylor madder than
``blocked'' lanes.
   Oil is applied to bowling lanes to protect them from the
friction of the landing ball as well as to provide a ``skid'' area,
thereby enabling the ball to follow the ``skid-roll-hook'' pattern
required for effective delivery.
   How to apply that protective coating is infinitely more
complicated.
   Taylor believes _ and he has lots of company _ that
less-than-scrupulous bowling centers have ``learned how to place
oil on the lanes to reguide errant shots into the pocket. This lane
blocking, along with today's powerful balls, has made bad bowlers
appear good. We have horrible bowlers now.''
   Not so, says Wally Hall, vice president of the Bowling
Proprietors Association of America and chairman of Fairlanes Corp.,
which owns 4,000 lanes, more than any other chain.
   ``What we have today is an extremely skilled sport. Technical
improvements may well have helped. But I do not agree that today's
bowlers aren't as good.
   ``Some proprietors _ not the majority, but a few _ are using oil
as a marketing strategy,'' Hall concedes. ``But the average bowler
isn't able to exploit those conditions.''
   The oil crisis has been under closer scrutiny than OPEC by the
ever-vigilant ABC, whose previous efforts to resolve it have
succeeded only in further depleting its stock of honor-score rings.
   ``We want to see any rule change result in a condition that is
fair and competitive to all bowlers, and that will leave the pride
of accomplishment in the hands of the bowlers instead of the
maintenance people,'' ABC assistant secretary-treasurer Burt
Kellermann says through clenched teeth.
   At the tournament in Jacksonville, lanes were constantly
monitored to ensure the same conditions for each bowler, as well as
to prevent lanes from becoming blocked.
   This meticulous maintenance may have accounted for both the low
numbers on the scoreboard and the long faces in the parking lot.
   ``A lot of people take bowling too seriously,'' confides Joe
Bowler, whose mother went bowling the night she gave birth to him.
``Mom was tough. I grew up with, `Head down! Don't bend your wrist!
Keep your damn shoulder up!' She used to be a killer. Now she's in
it for fun.''
   For what it's worth, Joe Bowler has never done well at the ABC
tournament, either. ``But no matter how bad you do, you always come
back.''
   Indeed, bowling badly at the championships is an annual
tradition, right up there with the march up the center aisle and
the crowning of Joe Bowler.
   Like today's bowling pins, bowlers are mighty resilient.
   ``Conditions are always rough,'' confirms Joe Ahler of Bay City,
Mich., whose 50th tournament appearance won him a diamond lapel pin
and warm applause when he marched up the aisle in April.
   The organist played ``Over the Rainbow.'' Ahler bowled 177.
   Like 60 percent of this year's bowlers, he's planning to try
again next year, when the tournament moves to Wichita, Kan.
   ``It's an impossible tournament,'' says Jim Wagner of Joliet,
Ill. ``But you keep wondering: When's your lucky year gonna come?''
   One of these days, Alice.
   One of these days.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
