<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WeekendTV-DirtyDozen Adv03-05   05-23 0808</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-Dirty Dozen, Adv 03-05,0824</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03-05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, June 3-5, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Dirty Dozen' Films Fox TV Series in Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was only a matter of time before ``The
Dirty Dozen'' arrived as a weekly series.
   Fox Broadcasting Co. recently snatched it up, and a cast and
crew from MGM is busy re-creating this fantasy version of World War
II on location in Yugoslavia.
   It began as a hit movie in 1967 with an all-star cast, and NBC
revived it three times, once with Lee Marvin reprising his movie
role as the tough, good-guy leader, and twice with Telly Savalas,
who played a bad guy in the original movie, as the leader.
   It's a great concept. Take a bunch of convicted murders, offer
them an outside chance of freedom and send them off on a suicide
mission against the Nazis. The bad guys suddenly become the
underdogs and capture audience sympathy.
   Everybody's happy, except the Germans, who reportedly are a
little miffed at once again being the patsies in a war film.
   ``They're the classic underdogs,'' said executive producer John
Furia Jr. in a telephone interview from Zagreb, Yugoslavia.
``They've made mistakes of various kinds and are looking to redeem
themselves by heroic action.''
   Ben Murphy stars in the weekly series, which Fox began running
Saturdays last month. He plays Lt. Danko, the head of the group.
But this time he's also a convicted felon. Danko assaulted a
colonel he says was responsible for getting 80 of his men killed in
combat.
   ``Danko's a no-nonsense career soldier who doesn't want to be
there but doesn't know what else to do,'' said Murphy, also
speaking from Yugoslavia. ``It's sort of the story of my
experience. I've never done a series where life imitated art so
much. It's like going to war for a year. You leave home, go to
another country.
   ``Our accommodations are better than barracks, but the
filmmaking process is very much like being in the Army. You have
periods of hurry up and wait, then periods of intense work. I think
it's the toughest show on television in terms of man-hours,
hardships and the effort that goes into it.''
   Furia said Zagreb is like a big studio backlot because of its
old buildings, various architectural styles, cobbled streets and
variety of countryside just outside the city.
   ``There aren't many places left in Europe that still look like
the 1940s,'' said Furia. ``In addition, Yugoslavia has a lot of
equipment, military and otherwise, from the period. It's very
economical to shoot here. We have an excellent local film crew.
   ``Our shows are a combination of melodrama, action-adventure and
strong characters. We have a good cast and the luxury of being able
to tell many different kinds of stories within the framework of the
series. We've done stories on teen-age partisans, the Cossacks of
Eastern Europe and one that was supposed to be set on an island off
Scotland.''
   The show also stars John Slattery, Jon Tenney, John DiAquino and
John Bradley. That doesn't add up to a dozen, but various guest
actors are brought in for each episode. They're usually casualties
by the end of the show.
   ``Danko keeps a certain distance from his men, because of rank
and age, but there's also a comraderie,'' said Murphy. ``He's a
40-year-old lieutenant. I've been in four war movies, and in one 20
years ago I played a lieutenant. I've never gone beyond that in
rank. In `The Winds of War' I was a Navy lieutenant.''
   Murphy said he spends his off time playing tennis with his
Yugoslavian buddies. ``They have nice courts here,'' he said. ``We
found one the other day on an army base. My buddies talked our way
in. If I can play tennis a few times a week I have few problems
being anywhere.''
   Yugoslavia has become a major film site in recent years. The
sequel to ``The Great Escape'' was also filming there. ``War and
Remembrance'' had been there earlier. The movie ``High Road to
China'' and an NBC miniseries on Mussolini were also filmed there.
   ``They make a lot of World War II movies on their own,'' said
Furia. ``So they're used to our special effects bombs and the
machine guns. We're blowing up so many buildings and trucks I
sometimes think we're laying waste to half of Europe.''
   Furia is an old hand at working abroad. In recent years he's
produced ``Rage of Angels'' in France and Mexico, ``The Sun Also
Rises'' in Spain and France and ``We Are The Children'' in Kenya.
   ``Dirty Dozen: The Series'' began filming in Yugoslavia last
December and will not complete 13 episodes until July. It takes 10
days to make each episode.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 3-5</NOTE>
