<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Dolby Adv03-05   05-23 0779</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Dolby, Adv 03-05,0811</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03-05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, June 3-5, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: A Wide Musical Vocabulary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The songs on Thomas Dolby's new album bear
little resemblance to the synth-pop sound of his biggest hit, ``She
Blinded Me With Science,'' and that's just the way he wants it.
   Every song I've ever written has been different from every other
one,'' Dolby says. ``That's one of my rules of thumb. I like to
break ground with every song I write.''
   ``Aliens Ate My Buick'' is Dolby's third album. With music
ranging from reggae to pop to funk, he hopes no one will identify
him with a particular sound.
   ``That can be a terrible trap to fall into,'' he said. ``I am
very fortunate to have a wide musical vocabulary. I can use any
musical idiom to make a point.''
   Dolby, an Englishman who now lives in Los Angeles, calls himself
a satirist and relates to such musicians as Frank Zappa and George
Clinton, whose song ``Hot Sauce'' appears on ``Aliens.'' Dolby
pokes fun at men and women, at Americans and especially at himself.
   ``The songs are like `Tommy Goes to Hollywood,' a journal of an
Englishman who goes to America,'' he said in an interview.
   The first single is called ``Airhead.''
   ``The song is about one specific female from first-hand
experience,'' he said. ``The big crime is that the lady behaves
like an airhead even though she has a brain.''
   Dolby's concern about how women would feel about ``Airhead'' was
eased when a friend showed him some lyrics for a song called
``Bonehead.''
   ``It's about a guy who wears all the right clothes. I read them
and I was in fits of hysterics,'' Dolby said. ``It occurred to me,
`Do I feel insulted as a man by these lyrics?' No. They're not
about men, they're about a stereotype. It's making fun of the
stereotype.
   ``The only complaints I've had have been from men.''
   Dolby has worked with a number of artists, including Joni
Mitchell, Joan Armatrading, Foreigner and Def Leppard. He is
intrigued by the idea of producing a relatively new artist.
   ``I'd really like to take a raw talent like Terence Trent D'Arby
and mold him. He just doesn't have the experience to optimize his
talent,'' Dolby said. ``There are a lot of people who are at the
top of the strata who are good at optimizing the little talent they
have. I'd like to get the opposite side.''
   On the ``Aliens'' LP, actor Ed Asner's voice can be heard
shouting ``murder'' on ``My Brain Is Like a Sieve.'' Robin Leach,
the host of television's ``Lifestyles of the Rich and Famous,''
introduces the album's first song, ``Key to Her Ferrari.''
   ``I was looking for a good attitude to begin the album,'' Dolby
said. ``He (Leach) has a production office in Los Angeles for
`Lifestyles' so I sent him a tape and he really liked the song.''
   ``Aliens'' was produced by Dolby and Bill Bittrell, who worked
on Michael Jackson's latest album, ``Bad.''
   ``They had a good dozen engineers working on that album,'' said
Dolby. ``Everybody said the most creative and sweetest to work with
was Bill Bittrell.''
   Dolby's first album, ``The Golden Age of Wireless,'' was
released in 1982 and included ``She Blinded Me With Science.''
Dolby toured in 1984 after the release of his second album, ``Flat
Earth,'' but had difficulty reproducing the sound from his studio
recordings. He does not anticipate that problem when he tours this
summer.
   ``The songs on this album lend themselves a lot more easily to
being performed live,'' he said. ``They're a lot more
groove-based.''
   Dolby will tour with the band he used on ``Aliens.'' Although
Los Angeles is famous for having big name session players, Dolby
auditioned unknown musicians to play on his new album.
   ``I was looking to find some people with enthusiasm. The LA
lifestyle is not conducive to challenging music,'' he said. ``There
are a lot of musicians who are technically proficient but don't
seem to do it with that much conviction.
   ``I was determined to turn up some fresh talent. I wanted people
who were good players but had some hunger.''
   The success of ``She Blinded Me With Science'' was helped
considerably by the accompanying video, which received heavy
airplay on Music Television. Dolby says he often writes with visual
images in mind.
   ``I'll have a picture in my head from a magazine or a book,
sometimes a scene from a movie,'' Dolby said. ``Sometimes I'm
already thinking ahead to the videos.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 3-5</NOTE>
