<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Chabon Adv3-5   05-23 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Chabon, Adv 3-5,0787</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03-05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, June 3-5, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: First-Time Novelist Astounded by Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the new kid on the literary block, Michael
Chabon should have plenty of tips for aspiring writers after his
first novel earned him a record-breaking $155,000 advance.
   The 24-year-old Wunderkind doesn't have any words of wisdom,
though. Getting ``The Mysteries of Pittsburgh'' published was just
plain luck, he tells fledgling authors somewhat sheepishly. His
coming-of-age novel was actually his master's thesis.
   An unsuspecting Chabon turned it in last year to a professor at
the University of California at Irvine, who, instead of critiquing
the manuscript, sent it to his agent. The agent was impressed, as
was William Morrow & Co., which offered $155,000 for the hardcover
rights.
   Since its April release, ``The Mysteries of Pittsburgh'' has
jumped onto best-seller lists, with 130,000 hardback copies in
print. Foreign rights have been sold to editors in 13 countries and
bids for the paperback rights are in the six figures. A movie deal
also is in the works.
   The book is about a gangster's mild-mannered son who spends the
summer after college graduation with new, flashy friends, including
a young woman and man who vie for his affections. The protagonist,
like Chabon, attended the University of Pittsburgh, and the drama
unfolds in this city.
   ``To me, it's the first novel. It has all the weaknesses of
first novels. I mean, it's the first time I ever tried to write a
book,'' the slim, soft-spoken Chabon said on a recent visit here.
   The pricetag is irrelevant, he said, ``because it seems so
inflated to me. I just can't correlate it with the worth of the
book. All I ever really wanted was just to get my book published,
or get a book published.''
   Always an avid reader, Chabon decided while growing up in
Maryland he was going to become a writer. He honed his talents at
Pitt, where he received a bachelor's degree in 1984.
   After living in Paris six months, he applied to the two-year
writing program at Irvine. He began working on ``The Mysteries of
Pittsburgh'' in May 1985 in preparation for graduate school that
fall.
   ``I just thought ... there are going to be all these serious
writers there, real writers, and I'll bet they're all working on
novels and I've just been doing short stories,'' he recalled.
   By the time he arrived in Irvine, Chabon had written 100 pages,
80 of which he quickly scrapped. Over the next 1{ years, he spent
every evening working on the book, required for his master of fine
arts degree.
   He took his title from ``The Mysteries of Paris'' by
19th-century French novelist Eugene Sue. ``I substituted the word
Pittsburgh and I went, `Ooooh, neat,''' he said.
   Chabon finished the 297-page novel in February 1987 and, eager
for some feedback, dropped off the manuscript with novelist and
English professor Donald Heiney. Three days later, he was informed
a copy of his thesis was on its way to Heiney's agent in New York.
   ``It didn't look like student work. It had the look of
professional work,'' Heiney said.
   A month later, nine publishing houses took part in an auction
for the rights.
   Chabon is unimpressed and, in fact, feels downright
uncomfortable with all the praise.
   ``I like what I'm writing when I'm writing it and for about two
weeks thereafter. It has a very short half-life in my esteem,'' he
said, laughing. ``After that, I'm even assailed by intense doubts.
No amount of praise from other people can convince me of the worth
of what I've done.
   ``There's entire stretches of the novel that I can't read
without wincing. I say, `Ooooh, why did I say that? It's so
clumsy.'''
   Chabon has since sold several short stories to The New Yorker
and other magazines. He's working on a second novel as well as the
screenplay for ``The Mysteries of Pittsburgh,'' to be directed by
Alan J. Pakula of ``All the President's Men'' and ``Sophie's
Choice.''
   Despite his good fortune, Chabon has made few changes in the
quiet life he leads in Newport Beach, Calif., with his wife,
Lollie, 32, an English doctoral student and poet. Their splurges
include a new car, a color television and a honeymoon in Italy.
   ``Our strategy has been pretty much the same,'' he said. ``We
just basically pretend that it's not really happening.''
   Naturally, though, ``It's all real. And I'm just still me.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 3-5</NOTE>
