<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Groce Adv03-05   05-23 0833</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Groce, Adv 03-05,0859</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03-05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, June 3-5, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: `Junk Food Junkie' Stars on Radio Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer-songwriter Larry Groce says his
1976 novelty hit tune ``Junk Food Junkie'' was a prelude to some of
the music he has performed on his radio show, ``Mountain Stage.''
   The two-hour program, originating from the Capitol Plaza Theater
in Charleston, W.Va., is carried by about 125 National Public Radio
stations across the country.
   The show, similar to the defunct ``Prairie Home Companion,''
features an eclectic group of performers who sing country,
bluegrass, folk, blues, jazz and classical. Others recite poetry or
tell their favorite stories.
   Groce, as host of the show, has performed a routine in which he
intertwines the names of country music stars and song titles with
the names of classical music greats.
   He has introduced numbers such as George Friedrich Jones'
``Bourbon and Water Music,'' Waylon Wagner's ``Mommas Don't Let
Your Babies Grow Up to Be Valkyries'' and Johann Sebastian Bach
Owens' ``Branding Iron Concertos.''
   To sing some of them, he has assumed the identity of Plastico
Flamingo.
   Although the show focuses more on music than on humor, the
40-year-old Groce says ``Junk Food Junkie'' was similar to the
spoofs he has been doing on the program.
   ``It gave a preview of that,'' he said in an interview from his
rural home near Philippi, W.Va. ``I poked fun at organic food and
junk food eaters.
   ``I'm fairly knowledgeable about country music and sort of
knowledgeable about classical. I like to hit both targets. I've
done this in the past.''
   In ``Junk Food Junkie,'' which Groce wrote, he sang about eating
natural food such as yogurt by day and enjoying ``a genuine junk
food high'' at night. He rattled off a list of his favorite
munchies in a tune that caught the public fancy like few others.
   ``I had always admired satire and humor in songs,'' he recalled.
``I had written others like it _ satires of common, American
things. I felt this was a natural.
   ``I poked fun at myself, and I had no idea so many others fell
in the syndrome I do. The response was more than I thought it would
be. It got a lot of exposure in the press because of the odd nature
of the song.''
   He wrote the tune based on his experiences while working in an
organic restaurant in New York. ``After work, the cooks would go
out and get a hamburger,'' he said.
   The peculiarity of the song tended to stereotype him, he said.
   ``I like the song; it's clever and I'm not ashamed of it. But
they assume you're an oddball and can't sing. Actually my career
has been based on singing.''
   Since the hit, he has been the opening act on concert tours,
performed to smaller audiences in coffeehouses and worked in arts
programs.
   ``I did pretty much what anyone does who's not a big star,''
Groce said.
   Included in his work are a half-dozen albums for the Walt Disney
Co., including two volumes of ``Disney's Children's Favorites''
that sold 2 million each.
   ``They haven't made me famous but they are known quite a bit,''
he said.
   He's just completed a special for the Disney Channel on cable
TV, ``Larry Groce in Concert.''
   He's been doing ``Mountain Stage'' since 1984, first on West
Virginia Public Radio and then branching out coast-to-coast in July
1986.
   Groce says ``Mountain Stage'' stresses music more than ``Prairie
Home Companion,'' in which host Garrison Keillor touted his
fictional Minnesota town, Lake Wobegon.
   ``We do very different things,'' he said. ``We tend to feature
music and showcase the performers. They are the star of the show as
much as our regulars. Ours is a little more of a true variety show
where the guests take a bigger role. We give them much more time,
and our show is not so much anchored in me.''
   Guests have included bluegrass acts such as the Doug Dillard
Band from the ``Andy Griffith Show,'' comedy by Dr. Demento, poetry
by Allen Ginsberg, blues by Roy Bookbinder, country music by Kathy
Mattea, classical music by the Montani String Quartet and jazz by
the Bob Thompson Trio.
   ``This show takes chances and it's on the frontier of music in
certain ways,'' Groce said. ``We specialize in singers and writers
to a great degree. We don't tell them how to act, how to look or
what to sing. They appreciate that. There's no pretense. We just do
it.
   ``Our role is to get people who are trend setters, even though
they may not be well-known.''
   He still gets the inevitable question: What is your favorite
junk food these days?
   ``I stick with my old favorites like Dr. Pepper and Chee-tos. I
also am kind of addicted to peanut butter crackers. Actually,
anything with sugar in it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 3-5</NOTE>
</DOC>
