<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   05-23 0841</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0878</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Looking for a different way to celebrate a
birthday or anniversary? Try ``VideoScrapbooks'' _ a line of
cassettes featuring the cultural highs and lows of bygone years.
   Using still photos, TV, film and newsreel footage, Halcyon Days
of New York has created videos for nostalgia junkies.
   The 1958 cassette shows Elvis in uniform and television ads for
that bold sound innovation, hi-fidelity stereo _ ``with you in the
middle.'' There are also gasps at space shots, fun with hula hoops,
Ed Sullivan and that legend in her own time, Barbie.
   The 1938 video has jitterbug marathons, Joe Louis, Fibber McGee
and Molly on radio and the Orson Welles joke of all time, ``The War
of the Worlds.''
   The VHS cassettes retail for $19.95 and feature the years 1958,
1948, 1938 and the 1920s.
   Meanwhile, for students and others in need of a little
``style,'' Paperback Visual Publishing has produced a video
adaptation of the Strunk and White English handbook, ``Elements of
Style.''
   The cassette, narrated by CBS newsman Charles Osgood, features a
color-coded screen to serve as index and to facilitate rewinding
and forwarding to specific chapters.
   Videos reviewed this week: ``Overboard'' and ``The Couch Trip.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Overboard'' (CBS-Fox, VHS@Beta, $89.98, Rated PG)
   
   Take one insufferably rich, perpetually bored blonde, throw her
into the ocean, add a case of temporary amnesia and stir it up with
a hunky handyman bent on revenge, and you've got ``Overboard,'' a
charming comedy that looks better on tape than it sounds on paper.
   Goldie Hawn is Joanna Stayton, a ``Lifestyles of the Rich and
Famous'' poster girl who changes bathing suits every 15 seconds and
gets her jollies by making other people miserable. Enter Dean
Proffitt, played by Hawn's real-life honey, Kurt Russell, a widowed
carpenter who comes aboard the Stayton yacht to remodel a closet.
   Joanna stiffs him and tosses his tools overboard. Later that
night, she falls overboard herself and emerges from the drink with
no idea of who she is. Seeing a chance to make her pay for her
nastiness, Dean convinces her she is his wife, Annie, mother of his
four no-neck monsters and keeper of the disaster area they call
home.
   The shock of real life almost kills her, and the transformation
from rich witch to human being is fun to watch, though predictable.
   Hawn, always at home with funny stuff, makes Joanna-Annie
alternately despicable and lovable, and Russell actually shows some
comedic flair in the hands of director Garry ``Happy Days''
Marshall.
   Clean enough for the kids, intelligent enough for the adults,
``Overboard'' is one of those warm, fuzzy little comedies
guaranteed to make the whole family feel good.
   _ By Lisa Levitt Ryckman, AP National Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Couch Trip'' (Orion Home Video, VHS@Beta, $89.98, Rated R)
   
   ``The Couch Trip'' sets an enormous challenge for itself by
trying to be fresh and funny while using one of the most hackneyed
plot lines in the book: Psychiatrists are crazier than their
clients; mental patients are more madcap than mad, and often
possess, exclusively, truths of a very high ethical order; and said
patients appear crazy but it's really the rest of the world that's
lost its marbles.
   Dan Aykroyd stars as John Burns, a small-time criminal
institutionalized in a Chicago mental hospital where his specialty
is cheering up the other patients, making it with the receptionist
and driving the head shrink nuts.
   Meanwhile in Los Angeles, big-time radio shrink George Maitlin
(Charles Grodin) is having a breakdown _ that's what movie shrinks
do best _ because he's had an affair, or his wife has had one with
his best friend, or something like that. He wants to leave it all
behind for a sabbatical but he needs a replacement for his radio
program.
   Through some complicated machinations, Aykroyd schemes his way
out of the hospital, impersonates the head prison psychologist and
wins the spot as Maitlin's radio replacement, providing the film's
few hilarious moments.
   Along the way, Aykroyd's ruse is discovered by, who else?
another loonie, played by Walter Matthau. They have their little
quarrels but mostly seem to enjoy conversing in the higher-truth
patois of the Hollywood insane.
   Aykroyd's most ardent devotees may see something to like in
``The Couch Trip,'' but only if they don't mind the constant stream
of genital humor and four-letter words.
   _ By Lee Mitgang, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
