<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 2222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   05-23 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0541</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN WINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Serious Slammin''' (RCA) _ Pointer Sisters
   
   Side 1 of the Pointer Sisters' latest album is awful _ dance
music as mindless and soulless as anything that surfaced in the
disco craze of the 1970s.
   The sisters redeem themselves a bit on the second side of
``Serious Slammin'.'' Still, it's hard to believe this is the same
group that turned out one of the decade's best pop records,
``Breakout,'' just five years ago.
   One problem with ``Serious Slammin''' is that June, Anita, Ruth
and producer Richard Perry haven't changed their formula a bit
since ``Breakout,'' and the sisters sound tired of it. They're
still singing uptempo dance tunes over synthesizers and drum
machines and, for a change of pace, mixing in steamy ballads over
synthesizers and drum machines.
   Another reason for the droopy energy level could be the
material, all provided by outside writers. The tunes are tuneless,
the lyrics lame. The nadir is ``Shut Up and Dance,'' which begins,
``All I want to do with you is dance; I don't need no verbal
expose.'' There must have been something else the Pointer Sisters
could have recorded instead.
   When the songs are decent, so is ``Serious Slammin'.''
   ``My Life,'' which opens Side 2, is the first cut that creates
any kind of rhythmic momentum. The mid-tempo ``I Will Be There,''
which closes the record, deserves a place alongside such past hits
by the group as ``Slowhand'' and ``Fire.'' Alas, most of ``Serious
Slammin''' is pointless, sisters.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``That Special Part of Me'' (MCA) _ Onaje Allan Gumbs
   
   Onaje Allan Gumbs is unknown despite the company he keeps. The
veteran producer, composer and pianist has worked with such jazz
artists as Woody Shaw, Nat Adderley, Stanley Jordan and Billy
Cobham, but ``That Special Part of Me'' is his first album in more
than a decade.
   Much of the record is terrific. Jazz is the common thread,
although there are also elements of pop and rhythm & blues. Gumbs
writes melodies that give his instrumentals instant appeal, and yet
the improvisations _ particularly by Gumbs on piano _ are intricate
and reward listeners who play the record through more than once.
   There are few frills but plenty of variety in the arrangements.
``Shadowlight'' features a trio and gives Gumbs a chance to
stretch; the Keith Jarrett-like ``The Dancer'' is Gumbs playing one
grand piano part overdubbed on another.
   The R & B influence comes into play on the title cut and ``Quiet
Passion,'' which find a groove and stay there.
   The pop element, however, is incorporated with less success.
Gumbs makes Muzak with his cover of ``Didn't I Blow Your Mind (This
Time),'' while ``All My Love (For You),'' the only tune featuring
vocals, unfortunately sounds like a duet between Dionne Warwick and
Donnie Osmond.
   Aside from the two awry crossover ventures, ``That Special Part
of Me'' represents a welcome and successful try by Gumbs for a
higher profile.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 2223EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Hogan Adv03-05   05-23 0887</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Hogan, Adv 03-05,0909</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03-05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, June 3-5, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Crocodile's Last Lap?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In October 1986, the Paramount publicity
department needed a hard sell to persuade journalists to interview
an Australian pitchman-turned-actor named Paul Hogan. No problem
now.
   What made the difference was ```Crocodile' Dundee,'' a surprise
blockbuster that grossed $175 million in the United States and
Canada and did comparable business wherever it played. Now Hogan's
back with ```Crocodile' Dundee II,'' which he swears will be the
end of the outback adventurer.
   ``I've completed the circle,'' he said. ``The new one is a good
movie; it stands up all by itself. It's the end of `Crocodile'
Dundee.
   ``Yes, I'm sure I'll be asked the same questions in three years
and five years. Like, `What if 10 million people write you and say
they want to see more?' That's getting a bit unfair.
   ``The challenge now is to come up with another character that
surpasses `Crocodile' Dundee. That doesn't mean I'll start playing
`The Hunchback of Czechoslovakia.' I won't stretch credibility too
far.''
   His remarks will be filed for future reference. Remember when
Sean Connery said no more James Bond? Remember ``Never Say Never
Again''?
   If the success of ```Crocodile' Dundee'' has changed Paul Hogan,
it's not visible. He remains the same wry, laid-back observer of
the passing scene.
   Can he really be just plain Paul Hogan any more?
   ``Yes,'' he said. ``In my home I can. I'm there as often as
possible. When I work, I work seven days a week, however long it
takes. When I finish the job, I disappear off the planet. Then I
become bored with myself very quickly, and I go back.''
   About the only places where he can now travel freely, he
admitted, are the Soviet Union and China: ``Six months from now it
may be different. But I don't really want to go to Russia anyway.''
   Hogan recently talked about the origins of ```Crocodile' II.''
   ``I decided about the time I finished No. 1,'' he said. ``In the
back of my head I thought I'd like to see this go further. I'd like
to see this character get in real trouble. The first one was mostly
a small-brackets adventure, a comedy and a love story with a little
adventure.
   ``I thought I'd like to do a high adventure _ if I could make it
better than the first one.''
   In the new film, Dundee's girlfriend (Linda Kozlowski) becomes
the target of South American drug dealers. After escaping death
attempts in New York, the pair flee to the Australian outback. The
villains pursue them, and Dundee faces seemingly insuperable odds.
   The script was written by Hogan and his oldest son, Brett. Hogan
said they made a good combination: ``We were like a team writing
songs _ one writing the lyrics and the other the music. He writes
very much in story lines, and I write in scenes.''
   The Paul Hogan story is the kind that makes the film business
ever so fascinating. Who could figure that an Australian TV
comedian would become an international star with one movie? Hogan
didn't even start out to be an entertainer. He was making $75 a
week as a workman on Sydney's Harbour Bridge in 1972 when a buddy
dared him to appear on the Down Under version of ``The Gong Show.''
   The object of ``New Faces'' was to humiliate the contestants.
Hogan ``turned the tables and ripped them to pieces. People all
over the country loved seeing me get revenge. I was an overnight
sensation.''
   Soon he became partners with John Cornell (who directed ``Dundee
II'') in ``The Paul Hogan Show,'' which drew high ratings and was
syndicated in the United States and 30 other countries.
   Hogan became a familiar face here with his commercials for
Australian beer and tourism. So many visitors came to Australia
that facilities were overtaxed. Hogan is no longer pitching his
native land: ``We don't want tourists sleeping in tents,'' he said.
   A visit to New York in 1984 planted the seed for ```Crocodile'
Dundee.'' Fishing with friends in the Northern Territory, Hogan
mused about what would happen if his fellow fishermen were
transported to Manhattan _ ``they would really think they're on
another planet.''
   Hogan and Cornell raised the $5.6 million to finance the movie.
It became Australia's biggest grosser, and Paramount bought the
U.S. rights and 20th Century Fox the rest of the world.
   Before the American opening, Hogan suffered a cerebral
hemorrhage while weightlifting. He quickly recovered and has had no
recurrence. ``It was just one of those things that come along to
remind you that you're not Superman,'' he said.
   Paul and Noelene Hogan, who married in 1958, divorced in 1981
and remarried a year later, have five children and have become
grandparents. He was asked if he receives more respect at home
since ```Crocodile' Dundee.''
   ``I'm still the head of the house, by sufferance,'' he replied.
``I don't get any special privilege. I still can't turn off the
television set and sit in front of everybody and tell them about my
day. `Aw, shut up, Dad,' they say. `It's boring, get out of the
way.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 3-5</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--TransplantRules Adv26   05-23 1217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Transplant Rules, Adv 26,1248</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, May 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>National Sharing of `Cadillac Kidneys' Gets Mixed Reviews</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The first time Louise Adams entered a Houston hospital for a
kidney transplant, the donated organ ended up being sent halfway
across the country.
   A week later, it happened again. The kidney, her ticket to a
dialysis-free life, was shipped a thousand miles away at the last
minute.
   ``I'm sure the person who got it is very deserving, but it's
still very disappointing,'' said the 57-year-old Houston woman.
``You find yourself feeling guilty about your feelings because I
thought, `Well, I wouldn't feel quite so badly if it had stayed in
Houston. But to ship it out...'''
   She knew she was competing not only with local patients but also
with those waiting and praying, just like her, around the country.
   One of those waiting and praying was Denise Warren, 27, of
Jordan, Minn., who got the second kidney thanks to new national
guidelines designed to make transplantation more efficient and
equitable.
   ``I'm just happy it happened,'' Ms. Warren said. ``I was
prepared to be on dialysis for a while. I didn't think I'd get one
for a long time.''
   Because of an unsuccessful kidney transplant March 16, 1986, two
years to the day before her latest operation, Denise Warren's
immune system had built up an unusually large number of antibodies.
Her best hope was a perfectly matched kidney, a rare and therefore
prized possession.
   When such an organ became available in Houston in mid-March, the
Gulf Coast Independent Organ Procurement Organization was forced to
relinquish it under the new rules. After a computerized search by
the United Network for Organ Sharing, Ms. Warren was found to be
the best candidate.
   And Louise Adams was sent home, once more, to wait. Her wait
ended May 20, when she received a new kidney at Hermann Hospital in
Houston.
   That's the way it goes under the 8-month-old program, which
requires America's 201 kidney transplant centers and 120 organ
procurement agencies to share all ``six-antigen'' kidneys.
   Antigens, simply, are features of alien organisms or tissue that
can provoke an attack by the immune system. If antigens of a
transplanted organ match those of the recipient's body, the immune
system usually does not attack. The six-antigen organs, only 2.6
percent of all donated kidneys, had been snapped up where they were
procured until the new rules were implemented.
   ``The nurses and doctors say it's a fair system,'' said Ms.
Adams. ``Of course, I can only believe what they tell me.''
   The kidney-sharing policy was adopted last summer by the
31-member board of directors of UNOS and implemented Oct. 1.
   The Virginia-based computer center operates the Organ
Procurement Transplantation Network, to which all transplant
centers must belong to receive Medicare reimbursements. The network
was recommended by the National Task Force on Organ
Transplantation, formed under the 1984 National Transplant Act.
   UNOS also instituted a standardized scoring system for
distributing other increasingly scarce organs, like hearts, livers
and lungs. Patients are awarded points based on medical urgency,
length of time on the waiting list and proximity to the donor,
among other things.
   ``It's a great improvement over what existed before, which was a
mish-mash of politics and old-boy networks,'' said Arthur Caplan,
director of the Center for Biomedical Ethics at the University of
Minnesota.
   More than 13,550 people are awaiting organ transplants in the
United States, 12,200 of whom need new kidneys, according to Arthur
Harrell of the American Council on Transplantation. Virtually all
of the kidney transplant candidates are on dialysis, the
exhausting, week-after-week mechanical elimination of impurities
from the blood.
   To increase the number of nationally shared kidneys and help
more hard-to-match, sensitized patients like Ms. Warren, the
network in March expanded the guidelines to cover certain kidneys
with fewer than six identified or detected antigens. Failure to
comply with any of the guidelines could result in suspension or
expulsion from the network, and loss of Medicare funding.
   Gene Pierce, executive director of UNOS, expects the change to
double the number of perfectly matched kidneys UNOS offers. There
were 115 organ donors reported to UNOS from Oct. 1, 1987, to April
30 who matched a potential kidney recipient for all six antigens.
Not all were transplanted, for various reasons.
   Whether it's sharing kidneys or assigning points, the transplant
surgeon still has the final say, according to Dr. John McDonald,
president of UNOS and of the American Society of Transplant
Surgeons. ``The physician has the option of using his best medical
judgment. Now he has to defend that.''
   The guidelines have not ``changed what they (centers) have been
doing in terms of getting the right organ to the right patient,
because they were doing that anyway,'' he said. ``But it has
reduced that process to a written policy which they are able to
follow and defend and argue about.''
   Reaction has been mixed, and McDonald said, ``One cannot have a
national organization of this type with everybody being perfectly
happy about it. There is no organized group out there that is in
opposition. No rebellion is going on. No centers have refused to
participate and abide by these guidelines.''
   Mandatory kidney sharing has produced the most grumbling.
   Some experts maintain that the long-term success of kidney
transplants depends on careful matching of the donor and recipient.
Others argue that does not justify flying kidneys all over the
country since the more they are moved and the longer they go
unused, the less viable they become.
   Donated kidneys can be preserved outside the body for up to 48
hours, four times longer than livers and nearly 10 times longer
than hearts.
   ``Obviously, some people are a little upset when they have to
send them out. They could have used them locally just as well,''
Pierce said. ``We keep trying to remind them that when you give,
you get back. If everyone is cooperating, and they must, then there
will be a fair distribution.''
   Brian Broznick, executive director of the Pittsburgh Transplant
Foundation, winces every time he sends a ``Cadillac kidney'' out of
town. ``I do this job because I want to see people transplanted.
Period. But I'm a Pittsburgher. I'm very proud of the program here.
I want to see this program work. I don't want to see my kidneys go
to waste or share them with everybody.''
   Mary Jane LaCombe, transplant coordinator for the Hennepin
County Medical Center in Minneapolis, is ahead of the game. As of
early May, she had given up one prized kidney but got back three,
one of which went to Ms. Warren.
   Broznick had shipped out two perfect kidneys, but got only one
back.
   In Houston, four went out but none came in. ``We provided four
people with kidneys and a chance they might not have otherwise
had,'' said Rebecca Davis, executive director of Gulf Coast. ``On
the other hand, it just so happens that twice the same patient (Ms.
Adams) was asked to come in for the potential transplant and twice
told, `I'm sorry, we have to ship these kidneys out.'
   ``It's a very difficult, very touchy issue. But if you look in
the global viewpoint, we're probably doing what is correct.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for May 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
