<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--Transplant-Glance Adv26   05-23 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Transplant-Glance, Adv 26,0381</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, May 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Sketches of Transplant Law, Organizations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-EXP--Transplant Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the law governing organ transplant, the
task force that grew out of it, and the network under contract to
help implement it.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>National Organ Transplant Act</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Organ Transplant Act was passed by Congress in 1984
in response to the growing need for a national transplant system
and medical and ethical guidelines. It called for formation of a
National Task Force on Organ Transplantation and mandated
establishment of a national Organ Procurement and Transplantation
Network to be administered by a private group with oversight of the
U.S. Department of Health and Human Services. It provided grants to
organ procurement groups to help increase their effectiveness and
promote organ donation. It also called for establishment of a
registry of recipients.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>National Task Force on Organ Transplantation</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Task Force on Organ Transplantation is a 25-member
panel that made 70 recommendations to Congress and to the secretary
of Health and Human Services in 1986. The panel of doctors and
experts, which no longer exists, recommended:
   _That hearts and livers go to Americans whenever possible and
that foreigners make up no more than 10 percent of the total kidney
recipients at any transplant center.
   _A ban on the exportation of donor organs, except when no
appropriate recipients can be found in the United States.
   _That all states pass laws under which hospitals would be
required to approach families about the possibility of organ
donation.
   _That a federal entity be established for organ transplantation.
That entity is the Division of Organ Transplantation, part of the
U.S. Department of Health and Human Services.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>United Network for Organ Sharing</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   UNOS is a non-profit organization based in Richmond, Va., that
was given a federal contract in 1986 to set up the national Organ
Procurement and Transplantation Network, which links by computer
all U.S. transplant centers, organ procurement agencies and
tissue-typing laboratories. Membership is mandatory in order for
these institutions to receive federal Medicare reimbursements.
   UNOS' 31-member board in 1987 approved mandatory guidelines for
allocation of donated organs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for May 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
