<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--LymeDisease Adv26   05-23 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Lyme Disease, Adv 26,0625</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, May 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Experts Predict Increase in Lyme Disease Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Allen Steere is making his spring rounds,
spreading the word that tourists wearing shorts and sandals are
easy prey for ticks carrying the disease he identified.
   Steere speaks about Lyme disease not only as the doctor who
first classified the infection 13 years ago but also as a parent
whose son caught it despite his father's expertise and caution.
   ``As this disease spreads into areas where it has not been
before, it becomes even a more difficult problem to deal with,''
said Steere, director of the Lyme disease clinic at the New England
Medical Center.
   He was working at Yale University when he discovered the disease
and named it for Lyme, Conn., where he identified it in a group of
children. Cases have been confirmed in 33 states, Europe, Asia,
Australia and New Zealand.
   To detail the rapid spread of the disease, Steere tells of his
son, who caught Lyme disease in 1983 despite daily tick checks.
They lived then in North Branford, Conn., 30 miles from Lyme.
   ``When I first arrived in Connecticut, it was only in the
southeast corner of the state,'' he said in a telephone interview
from Martha's Vineyard, where he was briefing local health
officials. ``Just during the time I was there we saw the tick
spread into our community and it hasn't stopped.''
   The disease is transmitted by the bite of a pinhead-sized deer
tick, but the real culprit is Borrelia burgdorferi, a spiral-shaped
bacteria. Populations of infected ticks have been found along the
Northeast coast from Maine to Maryland, and in Wisconsin,
Minnesota, Oregon and California.
   Early signs of Lyme disease include flu-like symptoms and a
circular rash that expands from the bite. Patients given
antibiotics early generally are cured without lasting effects. If
untreated, 60 percent of patients develop arthritis-like symptoms.
Other possible complications include hepatitis, respiratory
distress and damage to the heart and central nervous system.
   Fifteen-hundred cases are reported in the United States each
year, but Steere and Dr. Andrew Spielman of the Harvard School of
Public Health said many go unreported because victims believe they
have other ailments.
   Some scientists predict an increase in the number of cases this
year because of a growing deer population and an accompanying rise
in the number of deer ticks.
   The majority of tick bites occur from mid-May through July, and
most victims report having been in or near a woods with a deer
population. Although the ticks that carry the ailment live on deer
in their adult stages, Lyme disease is transmitted by bites from
immature ticks, which feed primarily on mice.
   The immature ticks bite humans at ``mouse-belly height,''
placing people with exposed feet and legs at highest risk, Spielman
said. ``That means a good thing to do when in an area of high risk
is to wear light-colored trousers and tuck the cuffs into your
stockings. You need to check your pants frequently and carefully,
because the ticks are very small, about the size of a poppy seed.''
   Those bitten are unlikely to contract the disease if the tick is
removed with tweezers within 24 hours of the bite.
   A Boston company Spielman is associated with, EcoHealth, is
marketing ``Damminix,'' small tubes filled with cotton treated with
a chemical that kills the ticks. Mice carry the cotton to their
nests, where the immature ticks live. The chemical is available in
a clothing spray but doesn't have federal approval and is licensed
in only a few states, Spielman said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for May 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1422EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary Adv26   05-23 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary, Adv 26,0725</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, May 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: This is the Explorations package for May 26 in summary form.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The first time Louise Adams entered a Houston hospital for a
kidney transplant, the donated organ ended up being sent halfway
across the country. A week later, it happened again.
   Ms. Adams, 57, knew that under new national guidelines designed
to make transplantation more efficient and equitable she was
competing not only with local patients but also with many of the
more than 12,200 people awaiting kidney transplants in the United
States.
   When a perfectly matched kidney _ only 2.6 percent of all
donated kidneys _ became available in Houston in mid-March the Gulf
Coast Independent Organ Procurement Organization had to relinquish
it under the new rules. A computer search by the United Network for
Organ Sharing found that instead of Ms. Adams, the best candidate
was Denise Warren, 27, of Jordan, Minn.
   The kidney-sharing policy was adopted last summer by UNOS and
implemented Oct. 1. UNOS operates the Organ Procurement
Transplantation Network, to which all transplant centers must
belong to get Medicare reimbursements. The network was recommended
by a National Task Force on Organ Transplantation formed under the
1984 National Transplant Act.
   UNOS also instituted a standardized scoring system for
distributing other increasingly scarce organs, like hearts, livers
and lungs. Patients get points based on urgency, time waiting and
proximity to the donor, among other things.
   Reaction has been mixed, and Dr. John McDonald, president of
UNOS and of the American Society of Transplant Surgeons, said,
``One cannot have a national organization of this type with
everybody being perfectly happy about it.
   ``There is no organized group out there that is in opposition.
No rebellion is going on.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Allen Steere is making his spring rounds,
spreading the word that tourists wearing shorts and sandals are
easy prey for ticks carrying the disease he identified.
   Since Steere, director of the Lyme disease clinic at New England
Medical Center, classified it 13 years ago after an outbreak in
Lyme, Conn., cases have been confirmed in 33 states, Europe, Asia,
Australia and New Zealand.
   Lyme disease is transmitted by a tiny deer tick, but the real
culprit is a bacteria. Infected ticks have been found in wooded
areas from Maine to Maryland and in Wisconsin, Minnesota, Oregon
and California.
   Tick bites mainly occur from mid-May through July, but those
bitten are unlikely to contract the disease if the tick is removed
with tweezers within 24 hours of the bite. Early signs include a
circular rash and flu-like symptoms. Patients given antibiotics
early generally are cured without lasting effects.
   If untreated, 60 percent of patients develop arthritis-like
symptoms. Complications can include hepatitis, breathing trouble
and damage to the heart and nervous system.
   The ticks bite humans at ``mouse-belly height,'' putting people
with exposed feet and legs at highest risk, said Dr. Andrew
Spielman of the Harvard School of Public Health. In high-risk
areas, people should wear light-colored pants, making the tick
easier to see, and tuck the cuffs into socks.
   Fifteen-hundred U.S. cases are reported each year, but Steere
and Spielman said many go unreported because victims believe they
have other ailments. Scientists predict more Lyme disease cases
this year because of an increase in the deer population and a
corresponding rise in the number of deer ticks.
</TEXT>
