<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--What'sNew-StoringCorneas Adv26   05-23 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--What's New-Storing Corneas, Adv 26,0291</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, May 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Cell-Preservation Process Could Help Eye, Tissue Banks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A freeze-drying process that creates undamaged
tissue specimens for microscopic analysis is under study as a way
for eye banks to store human corneas indefinitely for transplant.
   LifeCell Corp. researchers have used the process developed at
the University of Texas Health Science Center to store baboon and
rabbit corneas a month before reattaching them, said Jake Requard
of Tissue Banks International, a non-profit network of 11 eye and
tissue banks.
   TBI has awarded a $15,000 grant to Dr. John D. Gottsch, a cornea
specialist at The Wilmer Institute at Johns Hopkins Hospital who
will assess the process' value in humans. Corneas now are viable up
to about seven days.
   In the LifeCell process, a sample is cooled so rapidly _ using a
liquid nitrogen-chilled copper bar at minus 196 dugrees Centrigrade
_ that it bypasses the phase when ice crystals form, said Paul
Frison, LifeCell Inc. president. It then is transferred to a
molecular distillation dryer, which evaporates most of the water
and returns the sample to room temperature, saving laboratories the
cost of refrigerated storage.
   Current chemical processes alter the proteins, enzymes and
genetic components of tissue, freezing produces ice crystals that
harm cell structures, and use of dimethyl sulfoxide to reduce ice
damage alters cells, Frison said.
   LifeCell, of The Woodlands, Texas, is a profit-making enterprise
set up in 1986 to market technology developed at the Houston health
center. Investors include Allstate Insurance Co. Venture Capital
Division, First Boston Corp. of New York, and Tenneco Ventures of
Houston.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for May 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
