<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   05-23 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0550</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lazarus, a division of Federated Department
Stores Inc., announced plans to lay off 1,200 employees as a result
of Federated's purchase by Campeau Corp. of Canada.
   Lazarus, a Cincinnati-based department store group, said on
Friday that 600 workers will be let go from the company's central
organization and the remaining 600 will be laid off from the 43
stores and regional organization. Lazarus has 15,000 employees and
operates in Ohio, Kentucky, Indiana, West Virginia and Michigan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of General Motors Corp. retirees marched
outside GM's annual meeting to protest changes in health-care
benefits they say discriminate against salaried workers.
   They were protesting on Friday a GM plan to force salaried
workers _ both active and retired _ to pay deductibles and part of
the premiums on certain types of insurance. The plan, which goes
into effect in July, was designed to encourage the use of health
maintenance organizations and preferred provider organizations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nova Pharmaceutical Corp. said it has agreed to
a joint venture with SmithKline Beckman Corp. to develop and market
a variety of painkilling and central nervous system drugs.
   The preliminary agreement, estimated to be worth $72.5 million
to Nova, eventually will give Philadelphia-based SmithKline an
estimated 20 percent stake in Nova.
   The two firms would be advancing work on a range of drugs Nova
has developed, including a class of painkillers targeted at
bradykinin, which plays a key role in relaying pain messages to the
nervous system.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Income tax payments in April helped shrink the
federal budget deficit, but the monthly surplus was less than a
year ago, leaving government red ink so far this year 24.6 percent
higher than 1987, the Treasury Department said.
   The April surplus of $13.9 billion, representing the difference
between what the government took in and what it spent last month,
helped hold the deficit for the first seven months of the fiscal
year to $105.0 billion, according to Friday's report.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USG Corp. has declared victory in its proxy
battle with Desert Partners LP, saying a preliminary vote count
showed a management-backed slate of directors had defeated one
nominated by the investor group.
   But Desert Partners said Sunday it would continue pursuing its
$2.2 billion hostile buyout offer for the building materials
company, and noted it had a pending lawsuit challenging the proxy
vote.
   In the contest for six seats on the company's 15-member board of
directors, USG said the management-backed slate received
approximately 57 percent of the votes cast, according to a
preliminary count.
   Final results are to be announced Friday, the company said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks crawled to a mixed finish in the lightest trading of the
year as investor apathy and concern over higher interest rates
dominated the market.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks on Friday finished
with a 6.13 point loss to 1,952.59.
   Elsewhere, bond prices fell broadly. The yield on the bellwether
30-year Treasury issue jumped to 9.34 percent, the highest since
last December.
   The dollar was little changed, while grain and soybean futures
finished higher.
</TEXT>
