<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Dips, Gold Firms In London</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dipped in thin, trendless European
trading early today, with exchange dealers predicting a quiet
session because of the closure of many European markets for a
religious holiday. Gold firmed in London.
   ``The dollar only seems to move once a month now,'' said one
trader in Milan, referring to the midmonthly release of the U.S.
trade figures.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar edged down 0.02 yen to a closing 124.80. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 124.78 yen.
   ``With no specific market-moving incentives at hand, the dollar
remains in a narrow range,'' said an exchange dealer at a major
commercial bank in Tokyo.
   He said market participants were trying to keep the U.S.
currency at a low 124-yen level.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday,
were: 1.7020 West German marks, down from 1.7030; 1.4180 Swiss
francs, down from 1.4195; 5.7520 French francs, down from 5.7560;
1.9055 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9070; 1,263.15 Italian lire,
down from 1,263.50; 1.2417 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2420.
   One British pound cost $1.8675 in London today, more expensive
for buyers than late Friday's $1.8615.
   The price of gold firmed in quiet London trading, following an
earlier jump in platinum prices in Asia, bullion dealers said.
   The city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price
of $460.25 a troy ounce at midmorning, unchanged from the opening
bid but up from late Friday's $455.20.
   The Zurich bullion market was closed for the religious holiday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.22 to close at a bid $460.91.
   Silver traded in London at a bid price of $6.76 a troy ounce, up
from Friday's $6.64.
</TEXT>
