<DOCNO> AP880523-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 0853EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Mexico-Economy     05-23 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Mexico-Economy,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Extends Wage, Price Freeze for Three Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says it will extend for three
more months a freeze on wages and the prices of federally regulated
goods and services as part of its battle against inflation.
   President Miguel de la Madrid decided to hold wages, prices and
the peso-dollar exchange rate steady until the end of August, the
government news agency Notimex reported Sunday.
   ``We will not be able to sing victory in the fight against
inflation until (the rate) gets to comparable levels with the
trading partners of our country and ... stays (at that rate) for
several months,'' the news agency quoted de la Madrid as saying.
   De la Madrid unveiled the program, called the Economic
Solidarity Pact, in December in an effort to bring under control
the nation's skyrocketing inflation rate. Consumer prices soared a
record 159.2 percent in all of last year.
   When the program was announced, government officials said its
goal was to reduce the monthly inflation rate to 2 percent to 3
percent by year's end.
   But the government reported earlier this month that consumer
prices rose 3.1 percent in April, well under the record 15.5
percent posted in January.
   Budget Secretary Pedro Aspe said last week that May's inflation
pace may run about 2 percent.
   The economic program, as initially drafted, called for the
monthly indexing of wages and prices. But administration officials
quickly turned the plan into a quasi-shock program featuring the
wage and price freezes.
   Prices on government-controlled goods and services, such as
tortillas, subway fares and gasoline, have been frozen since March.
   The exchange rate for the peso currency also has held steady
since then, trading at about 2,260 pesos to the U.S. dollar.
   By extending the wage-price freeze through the summer, the
government appears to have guaranteed that inflation will be low
for the crucial July 6 presidential elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
