<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Discrimination-Dealership     05-23 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Discrimination-Dealership,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auto Dealer Ordered to Rehire Discrimination Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also ran on general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An auto dealership fired two black salesmen for
racial reasons and must reimburse them for back pay and rehire them
if they want their jobs back, a federal judge ruled.
   Perillo Pontiac in Chicago violated the Civil Rights Act when it
fired Walter Gilyard and Marion L. Jones in 1986, Judge Prentice
Marshall said.
   Marshall ordered full back pay for the men, who are black, and
ordered Perillo to rehire them if they want their jobs back.
   Gilyard, 48, and Jones, 60, said they were among four blacks on
a 10-member sales staff when new management took over the
dealership in 1986. Within 60 days no blacks were employed at the
company, the two men claimed.
   In ruling on Friday, Marshall said Dennis Kreeger, new-car sales
manager at Perillo, ``manifested the agonies of the damned'' as he
tried to defend the firings when he testified.
   ``We should have had a videotape of Mr. Kreeger,'' the judge
said. ``He trembled, licked his lips ... telling a phony story for
Perillo Pontiac.''
   Kreeger and Anthony Scala, Perillo's general manager, argued
that they fired Gilyard because of absences and insubordination and
fired Jones because he was rude to customers and used ethnic slurs.
   Marshall said the allegations of rudeness were ``absolute
falsehoods,'' noting that the customer who allegedly overheard the
slur ``has amazingly never been found.''
</TEXT>
