<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-USTrade     05-23 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-US Trade,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Envoy To US Urges Free Market System For Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's top envoy to Washington on Monday urged the
Japanese government to open up its market to foreign traders, and
said reassuringly that U.S. leaders were not seeking to destroy the
protected beef and citrus fruit markets.
   Japanese Ambassador Nobuo Matsunaga, in Tokyo for briefings,
said a breakthrough was inevitable in stalled U.S.-Japan talks over
liberalizing Japanese beef and citrus fruit markets.
   Discussions on U.S. access to Japan's beef and citrus markets
``are under way at present and I think that an agreement will be
reached soon,'' Matsunaga told reporters at the Japan National
Press Center.
   The ambassador, a key negotiator in negotiations to replace the
beef and orange agreement that expired in March, said the time was
at hand for Japan, which has benefited from the U.S. free trade
system, to open its markets.
   After talks to settle the beef and orange dispute broke down in
April, Washington on May 4 brought the issue before the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, a Geneva-based forum for
international trade disputes.
   Washington has flatly rejected a Japanese concession plan that
would counterbalance a market-opening timetable with new surcharges
on U.S. beef imports, aimed at bringing up prices up to domestic
beef levels.
   Matsunaga discounted criticism in Japan that an open farm market
would destroy the domestic producers.
   ``I feel that the U.S. government is not ignoring'' the plight
of domestic growers, said Matsunaga, who took up his Washington
post three years ago.
   Japanese farmers cultivate uneconomical plots averaging only 2.5
acres in size. Combined with high prices for feed and fertilizers,
domestically produced fruit and beef are among the highest priced
in the world.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
