<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ChemicalIndictment     05-23 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Chemical Indictment,0191</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury has indicted four officials
of one of the nation's largest chemical companies on charges of
negligence in a Tacoma chemical leak.
   The charges against officials of Philadelphia-based Pennwalt
Corp. stem from a Jan. 2, 1985, incident in which a tank collapse
released 75,000 gallons of chemical containing sodium dichromate
into drains that flowed into the Hylebos Waterway.
   Charged Thursday with one count of criminal negligence each
were: Robert S. Custer, former corporate vice president in charge
of chemicals; Franklin M. Shanahan, vice president in charge of the
inorganic chemical division; Edward R. Golinski, chief of the
inorganic chemical division; and Orvil G. High, manager of the
Tacoma plant. All, except High, were based in Pennsylvania.
   High also was charged with four other counts, including filing a
false report with state officials.
   Pennwalt, named in six counts, was charged with federal water
act violations.
   The three Pennsylvania executives were accused of failing to
exercise their duties when they approved what the goverment
contends were inadequate expenditures and measures to deal with the
problems.
</TEXT>
