<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   05-23 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Plummet At Opening</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened sharply
lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to
unexpectedly heavy weekend rain in major crop-growing areas.
   Soybeans plummeted more than 20 cents a bushel within moments of
the opening bell.
   Over the weekend, more than three inches of rain fall in the
extreme western edge of the Corn Belt, which is also prime soybean
land. Rain was falling in Illinois and Indiana today and was
expected to linger in the central Midwest.
   Grain and soybean prices had skyrocketed in the last two months
as dry conditions dominated the spring weather.
   ``This is obviously just a continuation of a very emotional
market and, I think, a forebearer of things to come,'' said Ted
Mao, grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in Chicago.
``I think there is uncertainty not only about the weather but about
final acreage as well, and the market will have to sort itself
out.''
   In early trading, wheat was 6\ cents to 13 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.38 a bushel; corn was 4} cents
to 7{ cents lower with July at $2.16{ a bushel; oats were 4\ cents
to 4} cents lower with July at $1.69{ a bushel; soybeans were 20}
cents to 27} cents lower with July at $7.58 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were lower in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .47 cent lower with June at 72.90
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .55 cent higher with
May at 81.05 cents a pound; hogs were .23 cent to .45 cent lower
with June at 53.60 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .17 cent
to .50 cent lower with May at 52.75 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Friday.
</TEXT>
