<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HousingStarts     05-23 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing Starts,0468</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Survey: Housing Starts at Lowest Point in 5{ Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Builders started 16 percent fewer new housing
units in the first quarter than they in the same period of 1987,
pushing the total to its lowest point in 5{ years, a business
information group reported Monday.
   A nationwide survey by the F.W. Dodge division of McGraw-Hill
Information Systems Co. found that 318,967 units were started in
the first three months of the year, down from 381,292 units in the
1987 period.
   The last time a quarterly total was lower was in 1982, when
298,307 units were started in the third quarter, the company said.
   George A. Christie, chief economist for F.W. Dodge, said the
housing industry faced two problems in the first three months of
1988.
   ``While the rental housing market was digesting the excess of
the mid-'80s tax shelter boom, last year's steady rise of mortgage
rates took its toll of one-family building,'' he said.
   Only three of the nation's largest 25 homebuilding areas posted
gains in the period, according to the survey.
   Washington, D.C., topped the list with 13,310 units started, a 7
percent rise from a year earlier. Norfolk-Virgina Beach-Newport
News, Va., ranked 21st with 3,371 starts, for an 8 percent rise,
while Charlotte-Gastonia-Rock Hill, N.C.-S.C., was No. 25 with
2,817 units and a 7 percent increase.
   Los Angeles-Long Beach, Calif., ranked second in the nation with
11,715 units started, a 16 percent drop from the 1987 first quarter.
   Here is how the other top housing areas did:
   _Riverside-San Bernardino, Calif., 11,390 units, down 6 percent.
   _Atlanta, 10,350 units, down 17 percent.
   _Phoenix, Ariz., 6,974 units, down 4 percent.
   _Philadelphia, 5,620 units, down 21 percent.
   _Tampa-St. Petersburg-Clearwater, Fla., 5,350 units, down 28
percent.
   _Orlando, Fla., 5,119 units, down 8 percent.
   _Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood-Pompano Beach, Fla., 4,930 units,
down 10 percent.
   _Chicago, 4,842 units, down 27 percent.
   _Seattle, 4,634 units, down 9 percent.
   _Miami-Hialeah, Fla., 4,391 units, down 30 percent.
   _Detroit, 4,372 units, down 34 percent.
   _Anaheim-Santa Ana, Calif., 4,012 units, down 19 percent.
   _San Diego, 3,978 units, down 51 percent.
   _Minneapolis-St. Paul, Minn., 3,748 units, down 30 percent.
   _Boston-Lawrence-Salem-Lowell-Brockton, Mass., 3,687 units, down
22 percent.
   _West Palm Beach-Boca Raton-Delray Beach, Fla., 3,681 units,
down 41 percent.
   _Sacramento, Calif., 3,622 units, down 3 percent.
   _Las Vegas, Nev., 3,579 units, down 19 percent.
   _Baltimore, 3,246 units, down 2 percent.
   _Oakland, Calif., 2,874 units, down 55 percent.
   _New York, 2,830 units, down 47 percent.
</TEXT>
