<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AlliedVanLines     05-23 0153</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Allied Van Lines,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allied Van Lines To Consolidate Illinois Headquarters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois successfully fended off an effort by two
other states to lure away the corporate headquarters of Allied Van
Lines Inc., the nation's largest moving company, Gov. James R.
Thompson said Monday.
   Allied will consolidate its five current offices, including the
main one in suburban Broadview, at a new facility in suburban
Naperville, Thompson told a news conference.
   Allied, which has 830 agents nationwide, will get a $3 million
loan under the Build Illinois Large Business Development Program to
help with relocation costs, the governor said.
   ``Illinois has beaten the Sunbelt,'' Thompson said. ``Texas and
Nebraska were competitors for this consolidation.''
   The decision will keep 850 jobs in the state, and Allied's
parent company, the National Freight Consortium of Britain has
pledged to create an additional 150 jobs in Illinois over the next
two years, the governor said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
