<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout to UPDATE with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange closed
near their lows Monday after falling prey to the slipping Wall
Street market.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
fell 8.9 points, or 0.50 percent, at 1,761.3, slightly above the
day's low of 1,761.1
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average opened 4.80
points better at 1957.39, but soon changed course and headed lower.
   Throughout most of Monday's trading, dealings were uninspired
and quiet as many players were absent for a religious holiday in
Europe. But Wall Street's influence began to be felt by
mid-afternoon, dragging London shares lower in its wake.
   ``I don't know exactly what it will take to get this market
moving again,'' said Andy Wood, an equities trader at Morgan
Grenfell Securities Ltd., adding that until large institutions
muster the courage to re-enter the market, enthusiasm would likely
remain thin.
</TEXT>
