<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Allegis     05-23 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Allegis,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Final Chapter In Allegis Shuffle Comes This Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegis Corp. stockholders, rejecting the
diversification plans of former Chairman Richard J. Ferris, are
scheduled to meet Thursday to officially change the company's name
back to United Airlines.
   The planned move is welcomed by current Chairman Stephen Wolf.
   ``Now we're back to the core business,'' he said recently. ``We
intend to stay in the core business and build the financial
wherewithal to start growing it.''
   Shedding the Allegis name follows the process of selling off the
company's Westin and Hilton International hotel chains and its
Hertz rental car unit, which were acquired under Ferris.
   Ferris envisioned Allegis as a complete travel service umbrella,
but that philosophy was rejected by stockholders and led to his
ouster in June 1987.
   Hertz Chairman Frank A. Olson took over as interim chairman
until an experienced airline executive could be recruited to take
over the streamlined company.
   In the past four years, Wolf, 46, has specialized in changing
courses for carriers.
   Under Wolf's management, Republic Airlines emerged from
near-bankruptcy to become a healthy merger partner for Northwest
Airlines, and a once-ailing cargo line, Flying Tigers, began
posting record profits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
