<DOCNO> AP880523-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1453EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Microsoft-Excel     05-23 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Microsoft-Excel,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Microsoft Giving Money-Back Guarantee on Excel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDMOND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Microsoft Corp. on Monday announced a
money-back guarantee for its Excel spreadsheet, saying it was
making the offer in its battle against Lotus Development Corp.'s
best-selling 1-2-3 software package.
   Microsoft's Excel has won acclaim, but many customers are
reluctant to switch to it because they are familiar with Lotus
1-2-3. Both products sell for $495.
   Microsoft said buyers of Excel can receive a full refund through
Jan. 1, 1990.
   ``This guarantee is designed to give customers ample time to
evaluate upcoming versions of Lotus 1-2-3,'' Microsoft said in a
news release.
   Lotus has announced plans for new versions of its popular
spreadsheet software, but in March said the first wouldn't be out
until the fourth quarter.
   Lotus said in a news release Monday that it will ship its 4
millionth spreadsheet product this week. That is nine months after
the company, founded in 1982, shipped its 3 millionth product.
   Excel was introduced six months ago. Pete Higgins, group product
manager for spreadsheets, said sales were increasing at a rate of
30 percent to 40 percent a month.
   Analysts estimate that Lotus 1-2-3 is selling at about 100,000
copies a month, while Richard Sherlund, an analyst with Goldman,
Sachs & Co. in New York, said Excel is selling at about 10,000 a
month.
   Microsoft said it plans a six-week, $700,000 promotional
campaign on its money-back guarantee.
</TEXT>
