<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Steel,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Output Rose 0.9 Percent in Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel production rose to 2.009 million tons in
the week ended May 21, an increase of 0.9 percent from the previous
week's 1.991 million tons, the American Iron and Steel Institute
reported Monday.
   The industry's production amounted to 93.8 percent of capacity
during the week, compared with 92.9 percent in the previous week.
   Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at
39.550 million net tons, an increase of 25.0 percent from the
31.645 million net tons in the previous year.
   Production so far this year used 90.9 percent of capacity,
compared with 73.0 percent a year earlier.
   Net tonnage by district for the week ended May 21: Northeast
Coast, 279,000; Pittsburgh, 207,000; Youngstown, 122,000; Lake
Erie, 171,000; Detroit, 162,000; Chicago, 554,000; Midwest,
192,000; Southern, 221,000; and Western, 101,000.
