<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1605EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-EntrepreneurStudy     05-23 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Entrepreneur Study,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Entrepreneurs Differ From Small Business Owners, Study Shows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Entreprenueurs are characterized as intuitive thinkers focused
on the future, while small business owners prefer the here and now
and are intent on seeing to details, a study released Monday by
Inc. magazine said.
   A questionnaire poll of 151 founders and co-founders of Inc. 500
companies found these entrepreneurs to be introverted, thinking and
perceiving, according to Charles Ginn, director of the Cincinnati
Small Business Development Center.
   The study showed the profile of the entrepreneur closely mirrors
the classic profile of a professor.
   These findings were compared to a 1982 study of small business
owners conducted by the University of Georgia, which found these
business people commonly making immediate decisions.
   The small business owner is similar to an accountant in
personality profile.
   While both groups were considered successful, the Inc. 500
companies experienced more rapid growth, the study showed.
   Results of the study were released at the 1988 Inc. 500
conference in Cleveland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1534EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-23 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Plunge After Wet Weekend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed sharply lower
Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade following a weekend of
unexpectedly wet weather in the Midwest.
   Soybean futures took the hardest hit, with most contracts off at
least 20 cents a bushel at the closing bell. Prices had skyrocketed
in the previous two weeks due to extremely dry weather during the
planting season.
   Some spots in the western Corn Belt received more than three
inches of rain over the weekend.
   ``We got some rains and that pretty much did it,'' said Joel
Karlin, an analyst in Chicago with Research Department Inc. ``The
technical indicators were grossly overbought and we had a lot of
liquidation right from the start.''
   Karlin said many traders decided to take profits ahead of the
afternoon release of the National Weather Service's six-to-10-day
forecast. But the market's sentiment remained ``extremely
positive,'' he said.
   At the close, wheat was 2\ cents to 7 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.43 a bushel; corn was 5} cents
to 7{ cents lower with July at $2.15{ a bushel; oats were 3 cents
to 3{ cents lower with July at $1.70\ a bushel; soybeans were 18}
cents to 20} cents lower with July at $7.58 a bushel.
</TEXT>
