<DOCNO> AP880523-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1700EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ChipEquipment     05-23 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chip Equipment,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Company Tops List Of Chip Equipment Makers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's Nikon Inc. knocked Perkin-Elmer Corp.
from its traditional top spot to become the world's No.1 seller of
equipment for semiconductor manufacturing last year, according to a
survey released Monday.
   It was the first time a Japanese company headed the list,
according to VLSI Research Inc., a San Jose, Calif.-based
consulting firm that compiles the annual list.
   Nikon moved up from seventh place on the strength of a 62
percent gain in its sales of semiconductor manufacturing equipment,
while Perkin-Elmer's sales in the category fell 20 percent, the
consulting firm said.
   Perkin-Elmer, based in Norwalk, Conn., had held the top spot in
the world listings since 1980. One reason for its decline was the
discontinuation of two lines of business that accounted for 5
percent of its sales of semiconductor equipment, VLSI Research said.
   VLSI Research released the full results to The Associated Press
on Monday after Nikon issued a statement Monday saying it had been
listed first.
   The U.S. government has given a high priority to preserving the
health of American companies that make equipment for producing
computer chips, considering them crucial to national security.
   The industry in general, U.S. and Japanese alike, fared somewhat
better in 1987 than in 1986, partly because of streamlining and
improved market conditions, VLSI Research said.
   Nikon's 62 percent rise in sales was partly the result of an 11
percent rise in the value of the Japanese yen. Also, VLSI Research
said its estimate of the company's 1986 revenue in the category,
$149 million, was about 12 percent low.
   Japanese companies' revenue was converted to dollars at a rate
of 150.7 yen to the dollar in 1987 and 168.4 yen to the dollar in
1986.
   Here are the names of the top 10 companies in 1987, followed by
their 1986 rankings and their 1987 revenue from semiconductor
manufacturing equipment:
   _1. Nikon Inc., Japan, up from 7th, $242 million.
   _2. Perkin-Elmer Corp., Norwalk, Conn., down from 1st, $213
million.
   _3. General Signal Corp., Stamford, Conn., unchanged, $208
million.
   _4. Advantest, Japan, down from 2nd, $205 million.
   _5. Applied Materials Inc., Santa Clara, Calif., up from 6th,
$174 million.
   _6. Tokyo Electron Ltd., Japan, down from 4th, $173 million.
   _7. Canon Inc., Japan, down from 5th, $151 million.
   _8. Teradyne Inc., Boston, up from 11th, $130 million.
   _9. Varian Associates, Palo Alto, Calif., up from 10th, $125
million.
   _10. LTX Corp., Westwood, Mass., previous year ranking
unavailable, $121 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
