<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OilPrices     05-23 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Prices,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Slip In Dull Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices edged lower in light trading
Monday, as the market worried about speculation of growing supplies
amid weaker-than-expected demand.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for July delivery
of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, closed at
$17.35 per 42-gallon barrel, down 35 cents from Friday.
   Among refined products for June delivery, wholesale unleaded
gasoline settled at 51.44 cents per gallon, down 0.92 cent, while
wholesale heating oil closed at 46.91 cents per gallon, down 0.80
cent.
   ``This was a dull day,'' said Jayne Ball, an analyst at the Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. securities firm.
   Prices fell because ``OPEC's production is still up there, while
there's some speculation that demand is not as good as a lot of
people thought,'' she said.
   Ms. Ball cited a Wall Street Journal article Monday that quoted
a European consulting firm as putting the 13-nation cartel's
production at 200,000 barrels a day above projected demand for its
crude in the second half of this year.
   Traders have been nervously awaiting the upcoming ministerial
meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, due
to begin on June 8.
   The cartel officials are expected to try again to find a way to
limit their output to support prices.
   Meanwhile various reports have suggested that inventories have
been growing as OPEC's production has increased, analysts said.
</TEXT>
