<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Rise</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS typo in price of Comex silver in last graf, $6.738
sted $6.378.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of gold continued to rise Monday as
the dollar drooped slightly against several major currencies in
thin trading.
   Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $460.30
a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $456.25 an ounce late Friday.
   Gold has risen more than $15 an ounce since early May, partly
because the strength of the U.S. economy has raised fears that the
economy will become overheated and inflation will rise.
   Gold was given an additional boost Monday by a big jump in the
price of platinum, said James Koppel, managing director of Deak
International Trading (U.S.) Ltd.
   Platinum jumped $17.30 a troy ounce to $581.90 an ounce Monday
on the New York Mercantile Exchange. That was in reaction to
renewed rumors that right-wing elements in South Africa would
succeed in cutting off sales of strategic metals to the United
States, Koppel said.
   Gold has been led upward by buyers from the Far East, where
unprecedently strong local currencies make gold look like a
bargain, said Ian MacDonald, a vice president of Credit Suisse in
New York.
   Moreover, MacDonald said, ``The stock markets have looked so
dull and uninteresting, money is clearly coming into metals.''
   In the London market, gold hit its most recent low, $444 a troy
ounce, on May 9. Its lowest point of the year was $425 an ounce on
Feb. 29.
   Foreign currency trading was thin in Europe because many
European markets were closed for a religious holiday. In the United
States, Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. did about 40 percent of its
normal amount of business, said James Hohorst, the bank's managing
director for foreign exchange.
   ``It's incredibly quiet,'' Hohorst said.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.8675 from late Friday's
$1.8615. Later in New York, the pound rose to $1.8687 from $1.8640
late Friday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar edged down 0.02 yen to close at 124.80 yen. Later in
London, it was quoted at 124.75 yen. At the end of the trading day
in New York, the dollar fell to 124.52 yen from 124.81 yen late
Friday.
   Other dollar rates in late New York trading, compared with rates
late Friday, included: 1.7018 West German marks, down from 1.7026;
1.4166 Swiss francs, down from 1.4181; 1.2425 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.2428; 5.7560 French francs, up from 5.7520; and
1,263.50 Italian lire, up from 1,262.90.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday: 1.7030
West German marks, unchanged; 1.4198 Swiss francs, up from 1.4195;
5.7570 French francs, up from 5.7560; 1.9075 Dutch guilders, up
from 1.9070; 1,263.75 Italian lire, up from 1,263.50, and 1.2427
Canadian dollars, up from 1.2420.
   In Hong Kong, gold bullion rose $3.22 a troy ounce to close at a
bid $460.91 an ounce.
   The price of gold rose in quiet London trading to a bid price of
$459.60 a troy ounce from late Friday's $455.20. The Zurich bullion
market was closed for the holiday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery was bid at $462.20 a troy ounce, up from $458.10 an ounce
late Friday.
   Silver traded in London at a bid price of $6.70 a troy ounce, up
from Friday's $6.64. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery rose to $6.738 a troy ounce from $6.690 an ounce
late Friday.
</TEXT>
