<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1802EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-GreatLakesPlan Bjt   05-23 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Great Lakes Plan, Bjt,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Great Lakes States Reveal Economic Development Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials from six Great Lakes states signed an
agreement Monday to showcase the region's strengths and promote
economic development through a program of joint lobbying and
marketing.
   The Council of Great Lakes Governors revealed the 13-point plan,
based on recommendations made by a commission appointed by the
council a year ago.
   The governors could not put a price tag on the plan, but said
some of the programs would involve existing state programs. Any
costs will be shared by the states, or the council will seek
outside funding, they said.
   The plan includes a marketing campaign highlighting the region's
business climate and recreational attractions under the theme
``Great Lakes@Great Future.''
   ``The (agreement) represents a blueprint for our future,'' said
Ohio Gov. Richard Celeste. ``Following it, we expect to fashion and
sustain economic progress across our region.''
   Celeste signed the agreement, along with Michigan Gov. James J.
Blanchard, Wisconsin Gov. Tommy G. Thompson, and Minnesota Lt. Gov.
Marlene Johnson. Illinois Gov. James Thompson and Indiana Gov.
Robert Orr did not attend Monday's announcement but had endorsed
the agreement, the council said.
   The governors agreed to participate in a joint trade mission
next year, and Celeste suggested Canada as a possible destination.
A trade office also is being planned.
   The agreement also includes:
   _An inventory of educational opportunities in the region.
   _A campaign promoting research capabilities.
   _The establishment of a Great Lakes Development Bank to provide
supplemental financing for small- and medium-sized companies.
   _Creation of a Buy Great Lakes computer network of goods and
services.
   _Development of telecommunication projects for agricultural use.
   _Appointment of a liason to work with state offices in
Washington.
   Celeste, responding to a question, said the agreement did not
specifically include a provision preventing the states from trying
to lure businesses from each other, but said he didn't think that
was a problem.
   ``I think very few of us these days invest any time or energy in
really going into our neighbor states to try to lure business
away,'' he said. ``From time to time there are companies who
propose a move within the region, and we're obliged as governors to
talk to those companies in the interest of our own citizens.''
   Celeste said the Great Lakes states' toughest competition isn't
coming from among themselves or other areas of the country but from
foreign countries.
   According to the council, the six Great Lakes states include the
headquarters of about one-third of the Fortune 500 companies. About
one-fifth of the nation's manufacturing is within the region,
including 70 percent of the steel producaiton, 55 percent of
machine tool business and over half of the automobile production.
   The Great Lakes region also has a $12 billion annual tourist
industry, the council said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880523-0285 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-88 1847EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FarmCredit 1stLd-Writethru f0098 05-23 0789</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Credit, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0098,0812</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poor Management Involved in Federal Land Bank Closing, Congress
Told</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Thor testimony. Picks up
2nd graf pvs, We are ... A version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poor management practices accompanied losses
that drove the Federal Land Bank in Jackson, Miss., into insolvency
last week, a farm credit official said Monday.
   ``As of last Friday the bank's liabilities exceeded its earning
assets by aproximately $500 million,'' Eric P. Thor, president of
the Farm Credit Assistance Board, told the Senate Agriculture
subcommittee on agricultural credit.
   ``This means that the board of directors and management of the
bank have lost over $300 million in the past three years,'' he
added.
   Thor said sour loans, high debt costs and heavy operating costs
had plagued the bank.
   He said the Jackson bank sought $410 million to $610 million in
assistance this year but was unable to come up with a workable plan
to get out from under.
   ``It seems you have indicated a lot of what you might call poor
management practices down there,'' said Sen. John Breaux, D-La.
   ``I would say that's a fair assessment,'' said Thor, whose board
was established by Congress last year to bail out the ailing Farm
Credit System.
   Lawmakers expressed dismay that the Jackson bank had been
allowed to go downhill until it was beyond rescue. They prodded
officials to avoid any recurrence at other land banks.
   ``We want to avoid another Jackson in Omaha,'' Sen. Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., said.
   Meanwhile, the Jackson bank reopened its doors Monday to provide
information to borrowers. A key federal regulator expressed hope
for quick action to restore loan service under supervision of a
receiver.
   ``We are trying very hard to work out an agreement to restore
service with the cooperation of some of the other system
institutions,'' Frank W. Naylor Jr. told a news conference.
   Naylor, chairman of the Farm Credit Administration, stressed
that the receiver, REW Enterprises Inc. of Tulsa, Okla., was not
authorized to make loans to customers of the bank, which serves 90
local lending associations in Alabama, Mississippi and Louisiana.
   Thus it would be necessary to reach an agreement with other Farm
Credit System banks to make loans through the receiver-operated,
billion-dollar lending cooperative, whose doors were closed Friday
afternoon after months of losses averaging $4.5 million.
   Such loans would be on an interim basis while the receiver winds
down the activities of the bank, Naylor said.
   The Jackson institution is one of 12 Federal Land Banks within
the massive Farm Credit System, a $50 billion, nationwide network
of borrower-owned banks and local lending associations. The system,
largely unknown to city folk outside the financial industry, is a
longtime bulwark of U.S. agriculture.
   Doldrums in the farm economy in the early 1980s combined with
unfavorable credit agreements plus high overhead within the system
brought some of the banks into hard financial straits in recent
years. That prompted Congress to pass a major bailout bill last
year.
   The Jackson bank received $30 million in aid under the bailout
bill but the assistance board that makes such decisions turned off
the tap last week and instead asked the Farm Credit Administration,
the system's federal regulator, to place the institution in
receivership.
   ``Our responsibility will be to wind down the activities of this
institution,'' Naylor said, adding that it should take less than a
year.
   Naylor was asked if the administrartion's action meant there
soon would be a rash of foreclosures.
   ``Quite the contrary,'' he said. He said those whose loans are
not performing would get the full benefit of ``borrowers rights''
provisions under last year's bailout legislation.
   The receiver's task also would involve placing the bank's
business with other lending institutions, Naylor said. He said it
was expected that some other system lender would move into the
three-state area to take over the Jackson business but that it was
too early to say which one.
   ``We would expect fairly quick action,'' he said.
   He said it would be legal for the receiver to sell assets to
private lending institutions. But he said the Farm Credit
Administration ``certainly will be reviewing all significant
actions in the district.''
   Nayor said there is ``evidence of a turnaround for many'' of the
Farm Credit System institutions during the last year. ``There are
still several land banks facing serious problems, but they're
working their way through them,'' he added.
   The Jackson bank's porfolio of more than 21,000 loans totaled
$1.68 billion at year's end, but 40 percent of that amount was tied
up in loans classified either as nonaccrual or high-risk.
Liabilities, meanwhile, reached $1.909 billion on March 31.
</TEXT>
