<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-WesternUnion     05-23 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Western Union,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Western Union Reports $625 Million Quarter Loss, Mostly Special
Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UPPER SADDLE RIVER, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western Union Corp. on Monday
reported a $625.2 million first-quarter loss, most of which
resulted from costs connected with the telecommunication company's
reorganization.
   The loss, blamed on the costs of a major restructuring, compared
with a loss of $18.8 million in the same period a year ago.
   Special charges of $603 million in the first quarter resulted
from write-downs connected with the planned unloading of the
company's microwave and voice-switching facilities, officials said.
   The write-downs reflect the company's exit from the business of
providing communications facilities to focus on specialized
business and consumer services.
   The charges also resulted from severance and pension costs
stemming from its previously announced plan to lay off 1,800
employees, or 25 percent of the work force, by the end of the year,
and from costs related to the curtailing of a management pension
plan.
   Revenues were $235 million, compared to $205 million for the
previous first quarter. Figures in 1987 do not include revenues
from ITT Corp.'s international telex unit. ITT World Communications
Inc. was acquired in December 1987 as part of Western Union's
down-to-the-wire restructuring.
   Savings from the layoffs were not reflected in the 1988 figures.
   President Robert J. Amman said the facilities sales would ``help
reduce the burden of fixed costs associated with the operation of a
nationwide telecommunications plant.''
   The company's stock on the New York Stock Exchange dropped to
$3, down 12.5 cents, on the news.
   One analyst said he looked on the write-downs as expected and
not unwelcome, and usually a good sign in the telecommunications
business.
   ``It's better to take them right off, get the bad egg out and
move ahead'' rather than let old wounds fester, said Stuart Ganes
of Shearson Lehman Bros. Inc. in New York.
</TEXT>
