<1ST_LINE>u f AM-RubberStrike 1stLd-Writethru   05-23 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rubber Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0161,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firestone, URW End Strike; Goodyear Pact Ratified</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after lede with URW president's comments;
picks up 3rd graf pvs, The URW .... ADDS 2 grafs to end on Uniroyal
Goodrich.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firestone Inc.'s U.S. plants were up to
almost full operation Monday after a tentative contract agreement
ended a weeklong strike by 4,700 members of the United Rubber
Workers union.
   The president of the United Rubber Workers, Milan Stone, said
the results of the bargaining showed the effectiveness of using the
Goodyear contract as a pattern for the Firestone contract.
   ``While some companies and some analysts have said our system
(of pattern bargaining) has outlived its usefulness, we feel that
it is the most fair and reasonable way to accomplish our goals,''
Stone said in a written statement.
   The URW, meanwhile, was awaiting the results of a vote by a
local in Gadsden, Ala., on a settlement reached last week with
Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co. Union officials, though, announced
Sunday that enough locals had voted in favor of the contract to
ensure its approval.
   Nine of 11 Goodyear locals, representing 10,575 URW members,
approved the contract.
   Firestone employees returned to work at plants in six states
late Sunday, the same day company and union negotiators approved a
tentative contract. Firestone spokesman James Strandberg said
production was approaching normal levels on Monday.
   URW spokesman Curt Brown said the Firestone pact followed a
pattern set by the settlement reached with Goodyear shortly before
a strike deadline May 17.
   Brown said the union's contract with Goodyear was effectively
ratified when the 1,700-member Local 2 in Akron ``overwhelmingly
approved'' the contract Sunday. No figures were released.
   Ratification votes on the Firestone proposal are expected to be
held this week at company offices and plants in Akron; Noblesville,
Ind.; Des Moines, Iowa; Decatur, Ill.; Russellville, Ark.; and
Oklahoma City, Brown said.
   The Firestone and Goodyear contracts both offer workers an
immediate 25-cent wage increase that is to be deducted from future
cost-of-living increases in increments of 10 cents, 10 cents and 5
cents.
   The 6,500 URW members who work for Uniroyal Goodrich Tire Co.
ratified a three-year agreement by May 16 that guarantees against
plant closings but includes a limitation on cost-of-living raises
during the first year, the union said.
   ``The URW demonstrated its concern for keeping Uniroyal Goodrich
viable, and we trust this will pay off in future improvements for
these members,'' Stone said.
</TEXT>
