<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Scotus-Business 1stLd-Writethru   05-23 0875</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Business, 1st Ld-Writethru,0903</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Says Fixed Annuities Fall Under Securities Law</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Restores dropped word ``involved'' in 8th graf, The insurance
...; picks up 9th graf, Among these ....</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Versions also moved on general news wires
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Monday let stand a ruling
that put millions of so-called fixed annuities under the
jurisdiction of federal securities laws.
   Under the lower court ruling, fixed annuities paying fluctuating
interest rates could be regulated the same as stocks and bonds.
   Insurance industry officials had opposed the rule, claiming it
imposed a heavy regulatory burden that would raise company costs
and translate into higher prices for consumers.
   In other business-related actions Monday, the high court:
   _Agreed to study the power of states to regulate natural gas
production, including ``use-it-or-lose-it'' rules designed to
stimulate production.
   _Refused to unravel a merger between units of Eastman Kodak Co.
and Fuqua Industries Inc. that created the nation's largest
wholesale photofinishing operation.
   _Gave states some power to enforce safety codes at federal
nuclear production facilities for hazards unrelated to radiation.
   The insurance industry had been watching the annuities case
closely, since it involved policies held by millions of customers
and representing billions of dollars.
   Among these, fixed annuities traditionally have been regarded as
insurance contracts because investors never risk their principal.
Annuity holders are assured of receiving the money contributed plus
a certain amount of interest in payments made at regular intervals.
   Holders of fixed annuities are assured of a minimum rate of
return on contributions. And most annuity plans provide for
``excess interest'' paid at the discretion of the annuity company.
   In 1967, the Supreme Court ruled that so-called variable
annuities, those that do not assure any minimum interest payments
on contributions, may be treated as securities regulated by federal
law.
   But a ruling by the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last April
15 marked the first time a fixed annuity was also treated as a
security.
   Beverly Otto sued the Variable Annuity Life Insurance Co.
(VALIC) in 1982, contending that the fixed annuity is a
``security,'' and that VALIC had violated anti-fraud provisions of
federal securities law.
   A federal judge threw out the suit, ruling that the fixed
annuity is not a security.
   But the 7th Circuit court reversed that ruling, reinstating the
suit. The appeals court said VALIC's fixed annuity did not qualify
for such treatment because its excess-interest rate on existing
deposits could be changed at any time at VALIC's discretion.
   By refusing to hear the case, the high court let that ruling
stand.
   ``We were hoping the Supreme Court would take the case,'' said
John Adney, an attorney representing the Washington-based industry
group, National Association of Life Companies, on Monday.
   He noted that under the appeals court ruling, fixed annuities
contracts must be filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, ``and be subject to their regulation _ not just
regulation by state insurance departments.''
   ``That means considerable expense and complications for the
insurance companies _ and for the situation of the policy
holders,'' he added.
   While big companies can afford those added expenses, he said,
the NALC feared that the increased costs could mean that ``smaller
companies might not be able to shoulder the increased risk, or to
compete in the market.''
   In the natural gas case, the high court said it would review a
ruling upholding the power of Kansas officials to control
production from what is believed to be the largest natural gas
reservoir in the world.
   The Kansas Supreme Court in 1987 upheld rules adopted by the
Kansas Corporation Commission covering gas from the Hugoton Field,
most of which is carried outside the state through pipelines.
   Since 1944, the Kansas Corporation Commission permitted owners
of underproducing wells to ``save up'' their authorized production
ceilings _ creating what are called ``underages'' _ and overproduce
in future months to make up for shortfalls.
   To create a production incentive, the Kansas commission changed
the rules in 1983 by declaring that underages must be used within
specified periods of years or they would be canceled.
   The rule was challenged by Northwest Central Pipeline Corp., one
of the major buyers of the Hugoton gas for transport outside the
state. It asked the Supreme Court to strike down the 1983
regulations on grounds that the Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission has exclusive authority over natural gas production.
   In the Kodak-Fuqua case, the court rejected a competitor's
arguments that the deal violates antitrust laws.
   The competitor, Phototron Corp. of San Bernardino, Calif.,
sought to block the merger pending the outcome of its antitrust
lawsuit seeking $300 million in damages.
   A federal judge in Fort Worth, Texas, temporarily blocked the
merger but the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in March
overturned the injunction and allowed the merger to occur while
Phototron pursues its suit.
   Kodak and the Atlanta-based Fuqua Industries merged to create
Qualex Inc., combining the Fuqua subsidiary Colorcraft Corp. with
Kodak-owned laboratories. In a ruling on injuries, the court, said
a worker injured falling from a scaffold at a federally supervised
nuclear plant in Ohio, is entitled to seek a ``bonus'' compensation
award under a state law.
   The court ruled against Goodyear Atomic Corp., which operates
the Portsmouth Gaseous Diffusion Plant near Piketon, Ohio.
</TEXT>
