<2ND_LINE>AM-Murray Ohio, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0239,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules For AB Electrolux In Murray Ohio Takeover</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS new grafs 2-3 to UPDATE with Electrolux raising bid to
$197 million; picks up 2nd graf pvs bg'ng, U.S. District ...; ADDS
new final graf with Electrolux statement on operating plans; No
pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Monday cleared the way
for Sweden's AB Electrolux to pursue its $182 million hostile bid
for Murray Ohio Manufacturing Co., a maker of lawn mowers and
bicycles.
   Electrolux announced immediately that it would increase its bid
to $197 million _ upping the tender offer from $48 to $52 per share
of Murray Ohio common stock. Electrolux said the tender offer would
be subject to shareholder approval ``only if AB Electrolux is not
satisfied that the Ohio Control Share Act is inapplicable to the
offer.''
   The Ohio Control Share Act is an anti-takeover law, and the
Electrolux statement said it would seek a ruling from federal
courts in Ohio that the act is inapplicable.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas A. Wiseman dissolved a temporary
injunction against Electrolux's $48-a-share offer by discounting
Murray Ohio's allegations that a New York law firm which once
represented the Tennessee company passed confidential information
to Electrolux.
   The firm, Sullivan & Cromwell, had advised Murray Ohio on how to
defend itself against takeovers before it represented Electrolux in
its tender offer.
   Hans G. Backman, executive vice president of the Stockholm-based
appliance maker, had testified last week that Electrolux received
no confidential information directly or indirectly from Sullivan &
Cromwell.
   He said his company based its action on Murray Ohio's annual
stockholders' report as well as other public documents.
   ``All the information appeared in an (magazine) article that was
readily available to any professional investigator,'' Wiseman
agreed, in his ruling.
   Electrolux also said Monday it has no plans to move Murray Ohio
operations from the present plant at Lawrenceburg, Tenn.
</TEXT>
